value:
WAACOO0006 is established in same vicinity as WA Museum site BS46.
Some fire intrusion shown by acacia regeneration and some charred logs. Mostly older understorey. Likely Boorabbin fire 2  to 3 years before visit. Most of the plot was unaffected by recent fire. Older very hot fire across plot evidenced by black charcoal beds where logs once were and by saplings- possibly salmon gums. More recent fire in very small pockets may be about 3 to 5 years. Very rare surface rocks included quartz, iron conglomerate and weathered granite. Rocks may be of colluvial origin. 
Soils were salmon coloured and very hard-setting. The upper profile commonly has termite galleries, mostly old, and low termite mounds were common.
 North east cnr. has 10 x 10 m area of Melaleuca fire scorch death.

Established in same vicinity as WA Museum site BS5 . Plot on a large gypsum dune on the edge of a salt lake chain. Erosion has affected parts of the surface (terrace and minor gully). There are eucalypt saplings on one side, but quite a number of very old Callitris have died, possibly due to drought and likely due to persistent rabbit warrens and root damage. There are some Callitris seedlings. There were some limited patches of step and gully erosion. Amyema miquelii on older Euc sp., terete mistletoe on Grevillea sarissa. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.

WAACOO0007 is established in same vicinity as WA Museum site BS43a and 0.5 km west of WAACOO0005.This site stands out as having been affected by fire in the last 3 to 5 years. Almost all mature trees were killed and so Mallee resprouts and saplings dominated.  Acacia acuminata (fieldname) dominates on the granite outwash sandier loams on the northeast edge as it does in the wheat belt. Long unburnt, responding to intermittent seasonal rain.

Northern part of granite complex. Outcrop to 8m. Complex trends south to WAACOO 0009.Soil in north west and south west corners is humic granitic sand and close to source, ne corner is silty sand and se cnr. is clay-sand with Mel. uncinata. Plot dominated by granite dome which sheds shattered material and has been dammed in the mid-east part. The apron has a well developed grassland and herb field. Soils on the edge mainly sandy detritus. In the SE washaway there are clays at depth.  Virtually all the granite area lacks vascular plants and so cryptograms were scored where the cover on rock was 50% or more; note that all such un-vegetated cryptogam points could have equally well have been scored as outcrop. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.
Co-located site with WA Museum site BS39.Heavier soils in Woodland. Austrostipa common and forming semi-savannah. Site not affected by more recent fires. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.

"Established in same vicinity as WA Museum site BS11. A shallow composite basin depression.  There is significant granite outwash from the complex to the north. This contributes light pinkish sand. Red sands form a lunette to the east and south. In the plot the SW has heavy grey-green hard-setting sediment at medium depth (decayed granite and/or sump/acidic?); the centre heavy similar sediment; the north-west cracking clays; and the NE light-coloured coarse-grained beach-like sand. 
 The plants suggest episodic and persistent inundation and/or soil saturation. Namely Callistemon, Marsilea, Muehlenbeckia, Juncus. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.

Site overlays with South Western Australian Transitional Transect WATCOO0001
 Dense shrubland. Cryptogam duricrust (overlooked on about first four south to north transects.)  About 5 to 12 years since fire. 
 No ephemeral plants present.
 Rabbit activity at low to moderate levels.

Outer fringe of larger lake chain, isolated by reddish dunes, yellow sand fan into western edge. Very few, 3, plants regenerating after recent moderate rains. Silt, sand with scattered iron conglomerate stones on surface.

WAACOO0005 is established in same vicinity as WA Museum site BS4a. Granite exposure with skeletal soils, reflects basement in adjacent profile. Holding water at points in granite basins. Largely granite flora with adjacent shrubland and Mallee. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.

Some disturbance to south east from motorbikes and from tracks and minor grading in the north-west.
 Plot is central part of lower slope to upper slope catena. Rim of a circular sump or drainage depression with some lower slope exposure of saprolite and dune sand to the north-west.

Co-located site.WAACOO0023 established in the vicinity of  CSIRO Supersite TCN.Grazed by rabbits, kangaroos, cattle and horses. Areas of black gravel less common than COO 0022. More fine silty sediment in surface profile.

Co located site.WAACOO0020 is established at same location as a CSIRO Supersite SG 100E. Grazing by rabbits, then cattle and horses evident. Woodland. Red loam over hard-setting clay and calcic nodulated.

Co-located site.WAACOO0024 established in the vicinity of  CSIRO Supersite MUL.
Plot subject to grazing by cattle (pats common, both large and very small; prints common esp. on creek to south), kangaroos, and rabbits. Several canine droppings. Closed canopy provides sheltering micro environment. Around 1 in 10 mature mulga have died and tend to hollow out with multiple knot holes as exits; some in use by fauna. Cheilanthes a significant structural component.

Co-located site.WAACOO0025 established in the vicinity of a CSIRO Supersite SB. Shrubland surrounded by hills with woodland. Somewhat degraded by regular stock, rabbit and  horse activity. Main grasses are mown flat. Maireana sedifolia is squared-off by grazing in places. Cat scat present. Many cow prints; though duricrust still intact.  Depressions show consistent damp-land elements including Eragrostis dielsii, Cuscuta, Austrodanthonia (edges), Sida "fibulifera", and Enteropogon, and minor patches of raised complex salinity via Frankenia and Tecticornia. High impact of introduced plant species- Medicago minima and Salvia verbenaca high cover, Centaurea melitensis low cover.

Co located site. Established in the vicinity of  CSIRO Supersite GB100.Open to grazing by rabbits, cattle and horses. Between dam and troughs. Probably heavily grazed. Also possibly cut over for fencing?

Co-located site. WAACOO0026 overlays with South Western Australian Transitional Transect WATCOO0013.
Grazing appears to be mainly due to kangaroos. (from end) and there are still black stakes and fire skeletons of Acacias. Plot appears to have been burnt 5 (3 to 8) years before, Acacias, Allocasuarina and Grevilleas are relatively young, Triodia is ~20cm
Co-located site. WAACOO0027 overlays with South Western Australian Transitional Transect WATCOO0014

Co located site. Established in vicinity of CSIRO Supersite G 200W. Like WAACOO0020, 0022 and 0023 has black gravel patches. Has minor depressions in north and north-west with quasi-cracking clays. Shares black gravel patches with Open to grazing by cattle, horses and kangaroos; some evidence of rabbit activity. Cattle dung at all supersite plots.

Co-located site.WAACOO0028 overlays with South Western Australian Transitional Transect WATCOO0015.
Kangaroos main grazers. Yellow sand ridge on laterite. Surface level termite mounds evident, dragons frequent as at WAACOO0026 and 0027.Slightly down ridge compared to 0026 and 0027. Some small areas of mining excavation, or spoil.. Regenerating after fire some 5 years or more.

Co-located site. WAACOO0029 overlays with South Western Australian Transitional Transect WATCOO0016.Burnt 5 to10 years. Triodia older? Some patches of mature Callitris persist to east. Some Rabbit diggings and Kangaroo droppings. Dragons common.

Site overlays with South Western Australian Transitional Transect WATCOO0005.
Likely 50mm or more fell on the site; plenty of recent insect activity and some shrubs flowering. Termites and wasps active. Grazing by kangaroos and rabbits. Triodia and Callitris mature in places; !likely 10 - 20 or more years since rain. May have been closely impacted by Boorabbin when occupied, e.g. fire frequency.

Site overlays with South Western Australian Transitional Transect WATCOO0006.
Late post-fire stage indicated by large or collapsing Triodia, mature and senescent. Callitris and Melaleuca are green. Diverse beetles, ants and termites evident. As at WAACOO0016 site is open to grazing by kangaroos and rabbits. Termites active.
.

Site overlays with South Western Australian Transitional Transect WATCOO0008.
Near road culvert. Open to grazing by rabbits and kangaroos. 10+ years since fire, Triodia mature. More strongly Allocasuarina, Borya, Ecdeiocolea,   and such laterite profile Genera.   Many medium-sized acacias dead.  Litter,  esp.  Allocasuarina litter.  Many,  sparse,  Triodia crescents,  and some Callitris senescent.  Several,  10-20+,  years since fire.  Site overlays with South Western Australian Transitional Transect WATCOO0008

Established in same vicinity as WA Museum site BS35a .Open to grazing by kangaroos, rabbits and emus. Likely once partly cut over given proximity to Boorabbin and railway. Site is home to several dragons,  about 40cm, grey with brown striped  tails.  Site is between granite about 200m west and salt lake over 300m east.

Site overlays with South Western Australian Transitional Transect WATCOO0007. Open to grazing by kangaroos and rabbits. Mature shrubs and Triodia indicate 10+ years since fire. Located between pipeline and major firebreak with high v power line to north. Like 0016, 17 & 18 the yellow sands occur on low rises and slopes, and there is laterite in places as observed when digging SWATT pits.
 At this site,  in contrast to 0016,17, 18, and others,  the highest live part of sedges was recorded (rather than the highest part) - in order to give a better sense of what was alive versus dead in terms of the whole clump/clonal entity. There is a patch of surface laterite gravel in the north-west corner.

-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Landform element and pattern is a plain on a sandplain. Surface strew has small amount of brittle calcrete gravel embedded in the sandy surface. No fire since last visit, site is long unburnt. Minimal grazing effect. Minimal introduced plant species. Homogeneity of the site extends 100m from the centre of the plot. Nearest infrastructure is the park access track 100m north east of the plot.

-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Co-located site. WAAMUR0030 overlays WA Transect site WATMUR0005.
Flora typically Eremaean. Red pink sand over more compacted substrate, with finer components. Extensive Triodia savannah/shrubland. Dune or breakaway about 300m east. Drainage very slightly north east. Burnt circa 5ybp to immediate east of plot and on east edge. Body of plot long unburnt with some very old Triodia rings, up to 2 to 3m diam. Open to grazing by rabbits (diggings), kangaroos, and stock (tracks).

-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Landform element and pattern is a sand plain on a plain. No surface strew or outcrop. Site is flat. Site is long unburnt. Triodia is forming very large rings or lines in some places. Grazing effect is minimal. No introduced plant impacts.  Community extends 100m from centre of plot. To the east of the plot there is more mulga. Nearest infrastructure is a gas line access track 50m from NE corner.
 

-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Co-located site. WAAMUR0031 overlays WA Transect site WATMUR0008
Long unburnt, 15 - 20years or more. Residual charcoal, and stump pits present. Triodia in rings or crescents often 2 - 3m. Rabbit diggings and old warrens through site. Even and recent, moderate to heavy kangaroo activity. Old stock prints and scats present. Dog or dingo scats and prints present, as at 0030. One of the more open areas in the vicinity, with a lower density of acacias. The breakaway 1km east has coarse weathered granite,  the upper layer of which is ferruginous or slightly lateritised. Some scattered rocks like this were on the plot surface.  There are tens or hundreds of A grasbyi established seedlings,  20cm,  scattered through plot.  There were dingo or dog tracks near the plot,  and there are goannas, and foxes in the area.

Site on gently sloping clay plain. Lots of gravel and bare ground. 2 degrees slope to the north east. Site is 100m south of an Acacia georginae community ( site NTAMGD0001). No introduced plants noted. Grazing effect is low-Cattle present but effect is minimal at present. Recent rain with most forbs and grasses fruiting and flowering. No woody vegetation. Fire history difficult to tell- none within last 2 years. Site is homogenous and sited >300 metres from wooded margins of Georgina River.
Acacia cambagei woodland with Flindersia maculosa with a mid- stratum of Eremophila mitchellii.
Eucalyptus coolabah low open woodland with a ground stratum dominated by Sporobolus mitchellii and. Scattered Chenopodium auricomum in the mid stratum.
Chenopodium auricomum low sparse chenopod shrubland to Sporobolus mitchellii low sparse tussock grassland. In a swamp/drainage depression.
Broad drainage depression. Minimal impact of introduced plant species- Sida rhombifolia and Themeda quadrivalvis present but cover low.
Eucalyptus crebra mid open woodland with a tussock grass understratum dominated by Heteropogon contortus with Themeda triandra and Heteropogon triticeus.

Soil is heavy cracking clay. Heavily grazed, cattle present. Plant identification difficult due to grazing. Much bare soil. No evidence of fire or weeds. Site is homogenous. Adjacent to a scrape used for watering stock. One koala seen in E. platyphylla.

-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Site is flat with no discernible slope. Land form element and pattern is plain on plateau. No outcropping or surface strew evident. A lot of leaf litter. Grazing effect is minimal as site is within an experimental cattle exclosure fence, but some evidence of macropods in the area. Impact of introduced plants is minimal with no dominant introduced plant species. Site had a cool burn in 2020 as evident from a thin grassy understorey and fire scaring on lower parts of trees. Site is homogenous, with the community extending 90m from the centre. Nearest infrastructure is the access track, which is 10m from the NE corner. 

-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Sandy plain on plateau top. No weeds, minor grazing. Evidence of recent (2 years ago) fire that scorched trunks of trees. Homogenous site. Paired with site QDAEIU0007, to be monitored by QPWS. One of the two sites will be fenced to exclude cattle. Overgrown remains of an old track are on the northern side of the site.

-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
The site is a Eucalyptus similis woodland to open forest with a Erythrophleum chlorostachys, Eucalyptus crebra, and a few other Corymbia species. The mid-story is made up of young Eucalypts, Psydrax, Erythrophleum and Grevillea parallela. the ground layer is made up of Themeda, Chrysopogon and some other tussock grasses. The average height of the Eucalyptus similis is approximately 10m, and the Corymbia’s and Eucalyptus crebra approximately 12m-13m. In the mid-layer the juvenile Erythrophleum average 0.40m high, the Themeda approximately 0.20m high.
In terms of fire, it was possibly burnt in the previous dry season. There is large amount of tree scarring, burnt matter and ash on the ground.
There is no formal grazing of this site, only signs of kangaroo’s.
There are no visible introduced plant species in the site.
In terms of landform and element and pattern, it’s a plain on a plateau. The slope and aspect, there is a 1 degree slope to the south.
In terms of the climate and vegetation response, there has been rain in the past week, and the vegetation response is active growth. The Chrysopogon and Themeda have shed their seeds but are still green.
There is minimal gravel.
The homogeneity extends 100m from the centre is the same community. The closest infrastructure is the track which is 140m from the Ne corner.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Sandy plain on tableland/plateau top. Very dry conditions. Evidence of recent (2 years) fire scorching trunks of trees. No weeds, minor grazing. About 3kms to nearest watering point.
Erythrophleum chlorostachys low woodland with Eucalyptus microneura and emergent Corymbia spp. on a sandplain.
Lysiphyllum cunninghamii low woodland with Terminalia aridicola subsp. aridicola on Sandplain.
Ground layer mostly bare, heavily grazed. Heavy leaf drop due to dry conditions. Site is homogenous and part of an extensive community.
Aristida latifolia low tussock grassland with Panicum decompositum var. tenuis and other tussock grasses on clay plain.

Sandplain. Very dry conditions. High grazing impact evident in ground layer. Site is homogeneous and part of an extensive community. Significant leaf drop in mid- and upper-storey species. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.
Astrebla squarrosa low tussock grassland with Sarga timorense, Eulalia aurea, Panicum decompositum var. decompositum and Chrysopogon fallax on a clay plain. Lightly grazed.
On broad drainage depression. Clay soil with loamy surface. Few weeds, little evidence of grazing, no evidence of fire.

Alluvial terrace along side drainage of the Norman River system. No evidence of cattle grazing or fire, some pig digging. Site is relatively homogeneous. Eucalyptus microtheca more common on northern side but occurs throughout. Introduced plant effect low - Passiflora foetida.
Grassland of Sporobolus virginicus with patches of Tecticornia indica low shrubland and bare saline soil. No weeds, some grazing by cattle and some pig digging.

Marine plain. Grassland of Xerochloa imberbis with Tecticornia indica, Tecticornia pergranulata and patches of Sporobolus virginicus and bare soil. Cattle hoof prints common and pig digging across site.

Vegetation is patchy, with much bare soil - typical of these coastal salt flats. Surface soil is covered in saline crust and soil is damp. No evidence of weeds or feral animals. Agile wallaby tracks across whole site.

Relic dune  with shallow drainage running through its centre with scattered mangrove shrubs. High component of woody weeds - Ziziphus mauritania, Azadirachta indica, Cryptostegia grandiflora and some Cenchrus ciliaris.

Very dry, little evidence of fire and weeds. Some grazing by cattle and wallabies. Homogenous site but this community is restricted to outer margins of broad drainage lines on alluvial plains in the lower reaches of northern Gulf rivers.

QNPWS monitoring site.

Plain with pale sandy earth in shallow valley between lows and ridges. Site is homogenous. Pig digging common across site and grazing by cattle and horses. No weeds. Recent fire has scorched south and west facing side of tree trunks to height of about 3 to 4 metres. Termite mounds present on site. Site is fenced by QPWS to exclude pigs, cattle, horses. Adjoins site QDAGUP0030 (horse, cattle exclosure) and QDAGUP0031 (control, open to grazing). Site dimensions modified slightly to accommodate fence (101x99m).

Site is fenced by QPWS to exclude horses and cattle and is alongside QDAGUP0029 (pig exclosure) and QDAGUP0031 (control site).  Soil is pale earth. Shallow depression running up to low sand ridge with hard pan at about one metre. Pig digging occurs throughout site. Termite mounds present. Fire scars present on southwest side of trunks. Site is more open in northwest corner otherwise homogenous.

Pale earth soil in shallow depression and seepage zone between low sand ridges. Evidence of fire in past 2 years with scorch marks on southwest side of tree trunks reaching to canopy. Significant pig digging and horse and cattle scats present. Weed free. Site is the control for two adjoining sites set up with QPWS as feral animal exclosures (QDAGUP0030 and QDAGUP0029)
Undulating clay plain. Some growth from rainfall about 6 weeks prior to visit. Low impact of introduced plant species- Cenchrus cillaris present.
Grazing impact moderate. Some cattle and kangaroos. Minimal impact of introduced plant species- some Cenchrus ciliaris.
Fire- Long unburnt some very old dead fallen litter. Low impact of introduced plant species- Cenchrus ciliaris low cover.

This site received no rainfall in previous year however a flow down the adjoining Thomson River flooded the site and caused growth of vegetation. Site QDAMGD0009 and all other sites in this vicinity e.g. MGD0012 did not receive summer rain. However this site was inundated by a major flow down the adjacent Thompson River that occurred after significant rain 100kms upstream.
Grassland of Astrebla spp. on cretaceous sediments. Very dry.

Acacia tephrina low open woodland with scattered Acacia harpophylla with shrub stratum of Eremophila mitchellii with Senna artemisioides subsp. alicia and a sparse ground stratum of Sida spp., chenopods and Cenchrus ciliaris on plain. Minimal impact of introduced plant species- Cenchrus ciliaris and Opuntia stricta present but low cover.
Astrebla squarrosa low open tussock grassland with scattered Astrebla pectinata and Astrebla elymoides. on Cretaceous sediments.

Acacia cambagei low woodland with scattered Eucalyptus coolabah and a mid-stratum of Lysiphyllum gilvum with some Santalum lanceolatum and a very sparse ground stratum of Cenchrus ciliaris. Moderate impact of introduced plant species- Cenchrus ciliaris moderate cover.
Astrebla lappacea low open tussock grassland with scattered Aristida latifolia on clay plain derived from Cretaceous sediments. Minimal impact of introduced plant species- Cenchrus ciliaris.
Acacia cambagei low woodland with ground stratum of Cenchrus ciliaris on alluvial terrace. Moderate impact of introduced plant species- Cenchrus ciliaris.

Astrebla pectinata / Cenchrus ciliaris / Astrebla elymoides low open tussock grassland on alluvial plain adjoining creek. Minimal impact of introduced plant species- Cenchrus ciliaris and Xanthium occidentale present.
Acacia cambagei low open woodland with ground stratum of Eragrostis xerophila and scattered Astrebla pectinata on a plain on Cretaceous sediments. Has much bare soil with gravel and cryptogram.
Acacia cambagei low woodland with sparse mid-stratum of Lysiphyllum carronii and bare ground stratum. Ground layer is heavily grazed. Minimal impact of introduced plant species- Cenchrus ciliaris.

Fire in October 2012 affected most E. pruinosa which are re-shooting from base and killed most Acacia holosericea. Ground layer is also fire affected. Cenchrus ciliaris is low and re-shooting. There is also Eulalia aurea, Enneapogon avenaceus and Aristida spp. Sandplain with some metamorphic rock outcrop. Boomarra Station. Site is open to grazing by cattle.
Woodland / closed forest of Acacia shirleyi with no understorey and bare ground. Idalia NP about 20 kms north of ranger base.
Witchelina Nature Reserve, about 6kms north of homestead. Open shrubland of Maireana astrotricha and Atriplex vesicaria with ground layer of Enneapogon spp., Sclerolaena spp. and forbs.

Sclerolaena ventricosa / Atriplex vesicaria low sparse chenopod shrubland to Calotis hispidula low sparse forbland.  Much bare soil and gravel with small vegetated gilgai.Plot consistently covered with a surface strew of pebble and cobble with a mixture of sandstone, limestone and ironstone . Site is long unburnt, no evidence of past fire. High impact of grazing from kangaroos and low impact from cattle (Some old scats found in plot).
Site is on a plain with a gibber strew- Unidentified metamorphosed sandstone. Homogeneity- community extends 50m south. Track 60m from old Strzelecki track

Senna artemisioides subsp. petiolaris / Eremophila maculata subsp. maculata / Acacia victoriae subsp. victoriae low open shrubland with scattered Santalum lanceolatum.  Site is homogeneous. Minor grazing by cattle.

Dune system with moderate slopes to the west and steep slopes to east. Dunes run parallel north east to south west.  The south east corner of site runs into a dune swale and so site is not entirely homogenous.

On the outer margins of a seasonal swamp/drainage depression. Site is homogeneous.  Evidence of high usage by cattle but appears to be destocked at time of site visit. Some weeds present. Site is close to dam in base of swamp.
In the centre of seasonal swamp / drainage depression. Weeds present and evidence of heavy grazing though no cattle present at time of site visit. Site is homogeneous.
Astrebla pectinata low sparse grassland with scattered Plantago drummondii and Tripogon loliiformis on a gibber plain.

On outer reaches of Diamantina River floodout. Recent rain 1 month previous, soil damp but little vegetation response. To the east of site is main channel 700m away to south is smaller channel/Anna branch. rises to east to low levee before dropping to main channel. Grazing effect low- Evidence of Kangaroos and some cattle. Introduced species impact minimal. Fire- long unburnt by age of Chenopodium and lack of scarring on surrounding trees.

Stable flat soil surface across site with little bare soil.  Site is on broad, slightly elevated, plain, extending to the west, but to the east has gentle slope north east. Tree bark charred and charcoal on ground- surrounding areas also with burns of differing age. Site resembles vegetation/physical elements of local community south of Litchfield park road. Fire here 2 years ago.

Rhodanthe tietkensii, Polycalymma stuartii sparse forbland to Cenchrus ciliaris tussock grassland with scattered Acacia murrayana and other shrubs and isolated Hakea divaricata trees. Site burnt 1 year previous. Grazing effect minimal but close to very old, long disused set of yards. Introduced plant effect moderate- Cenchrus ciliaris throughout the site but cover relatively low at present. Light rain during site visit but site very dry- most forbs dead and tussock grasses dry. Site re-visited for point intercept. Initial plant collection and soil undertaken in August 2011

Site is in broad drainage depression. Grazing effect is low at present- 2km from water point but no grazing since end of previous dry season. Introduced plant effect low- none noted. Fire- long unburnt with no scarring on trees and low ground cover to carry fire. End of the wet season.  Very little litter other than that from the Acacia georginae. Site is more or less flat. Sloping away slightly at the south west corner rising onto the Mitchell grass. Strew is mostly gravel not much larger than 50mm- mixed metamorphosed strew of sandstone, mudstone etc.

Grazing effect is low- no evidence of cattle. Probably heavily grazed at other times. Introduced species-some Stylosanthes but effect is low. Fire: long unburnt- no scaring on trees. Slope to the north west of about 1 degree down to Newcastle creek. Mix of metamorphosed rock sandstone gravel etc. likely washed down from surrounding hills. Homogeneity: North west corner is where water currently extends too. Site extends to the south 100m, east is edge of gas line track, 100m to the north and west.

2 drainage lines- 1 to the east towards the main channel 1 degree slope. On northern edge is another drainage line. Centre is highpoint within quadrat. Grazing effect moderate. Introduced species low- some Xanthium occidentale . Long unburnt- No scarring and recruitment age of E. coolabah. Strew- some large cobbles on levee in centre. Sandstone. Rest of site strew sparse.

Very shallow valley between Eucalyptus crebra low rises. Weed species impact high- Stylosanthes scabra, Themeda quadrivalvis and Melinis repens through the site. Some grazing from cattle with scats in the site. Pads from kangaroos. Unburnt 5 + years. no scarring on trees. North of site burnt in previous season. Site slope down from the west approx. 2 degrees but main slope is to the south. Homogeneity- site more or less contained/ bordered by denser Eucalyptus crebra woodland. Grasses mostly still green.

Drainage line through quadrat from south west through the site up to 1m deep. Steeper in north west corner of site. ridge to approx. 50m running north to south to the west of the site. Check soil sheet for surface strew lithology- mixed. Introduced species effect low- some Stylosanthes scabra . Some grazing but effect low- grasses waist high. Fire- some scarring to 6m approx. 5-6 years since last fire. Homogeneity- 100m to the south 50m west up slope 50m to the north to the east grading into Corymbia sp. woodland across track.

Alluvial plain with mixed surface strew lithology. Some drainage depressions 10m wide by 20cm deep where water would pool in wet season. Grazing effect is currently low but close to bore so likely more heavily grazed in past. Introduced plants- some Cenchrus ciliaris but cover is low. Site long unburnt- no scarring on Eucalyptus pruinosa.

5+ years since last fire. Introduced plant effect minimal- none noted. Grazing impact moderate. Homogeneity- west 20m 50m to the south north of sites grades into Acacia shirleyi woodland. 50m further to the east.

Very dry. At south west corner of site is track running off to north east. Homogeneity- 50m to east and south. To the north borders Acacia tephrina woodland. Track to west but community continues another 50m beyond. Introduced plant effect- moderate, some Cenchrus ciliaris and Stylosanthes scabra. Grazing effect- severe, most palatable species gone. Long unburnt, no scarring on trees/age of canopy.
Long unburnt 10+ years. Introduced plant effect- minimal. Grazing effect moderate- little feed for cattle. Homogeneity- 50m in all directions- difficult to see beyond that.
Long unburnt- some old scarring on Grevillea striata. Grazing effect low, some cattle. Introduced plant effect low- some Cenchrus ciliaris.

To the north of site across track has been burnt in previous year but site is long unburnt. Introduced plant effect low, a few Stylosanthes in plot. Homogeneity, community continues 1km to the north, south and west. To the east 200m. Grazing effect is low, site not recently grazed though a few scattered cattle prints in the site.

Site very long unburnt-  scarring on larger trees. Introduced plant effect- low, small patch of Cenchrus ciliaris. Effect of grazing - low, some cattle tracks in sites. Homogeneity- grades in and out Melaleuca and Lysiphyllum through landform. Community extends 50m beyond site in all directions. Very light rain previous night but not enough to stimulate vegetation response.

Time since last fire difficult to tell. Not burnt within last two to three years. Introduced plant effect minimal. Grazing effect is high- some distance from water point but most grass heads chewed off or pushed over.  Homogeneity- community continues to the west 600m where it joins a Gidgee woodland, 1km to the south with scattered Atalaya, 1km to north and east.

Older inactive alluvial plain. Grazing effect is low- grasses more or less intact. Introduced plants- minimal inside quadrat but rubber vine close by the southern boundary of the site.  Fire - difficult to tell but not in last 3-4 years. Subsoil damp. Homogeneity- community continues 1km to east and west and 2km north and south.

Gently undulating site but overall site is flat. Shallow waterhole in north of the site. Large patches of salt scald/crust through the site. Dry but subsurface still wet. Grazing effect- low but some evidence of pigs in the site. Long unburnt. Introduced plants minimal. Homogeneity- community continues 30m to the north where it borders a mangrove lined creek channel. To the south and west 600m. To the east 50m where it merges into mangrove channels

On relic dune. Site is on a drainage line on crest of the dune. Dam wall about 50m south of the site. Homogeneity- community is more or less confined to the site. Grazing effect- heavily impacted by pigs and kangaroos. Close to dam but cattle haven not been present in large numbers for quite some time. Effect of introduced plant species high- Cryptostegia grandiflora dominants in mid and upper canopy. Also some Hyptis and other annuals. Long unburnt- recruitment in Corymbia and Atalaya. Site is convex with eastern and western edges rising slightly and the centre being close to the lowest point.

Fire history difficult to tell but not burnt in previous 2 years. Grazing effect is moderate mainly from cattle. Introduced plant effect is minimal. Homogeneity- community continues 50m to the west as far as a relic dune then continues on the other side. Subtle change starting just north of the site with more termite mounds corresponding to a very small rise in elevation. To the south community continues 1km and to the east 500m where there is another relic dune.

On relic dune. Centre of the site is on a very low relic dune. Western edge is a drainage depression with heavier soil where Cryptostegia grandiflora is more concentrated. Dune running more or less north south. Grazing effect- heavily impacted by wallabies. Weed effect severe- rubber vine, neam and Chinese apple spread through the site.

Terminalia has mostly lost its leaves so cover is subsequently lower. 2 shallow drainage lines 10cm deep running north to south through the site. Homogeneity- difficult to tell beyond site due to thickness of vegetation. Eastern edge of site is edge of the community. 50m to the south, north and west. Grazing effect is low- cattle present but little feed. Long unburnt- trunks black but from fungus rather than fire. Introduced plant effect minimal. Check soil sheet for info on surface strew- possibly lateritic.

Shallow drainage line running 40m south of site. Sloping to south west 1 degree and a little more at south west corner. Strew mostly 5 to 50mm with larger cobbles. Strew lithology mixed- sandstone, mudstone as well as possibly some lateritic elements. check soil sample for more detail. Overnight rain light but no vegetation response. Grazing moderate- kangaroos in large numbers. no introduced plant species of note. Long unburnt- no scarring etc. on nearby coolabahs

Swamp. Drainage lines in site, main one from south east to north west curves through site. .5m deep sandy base. Denser E. coolabah in channels sparser on flat areas. No evidence of fire. No scarring in trees and also recruitment in E. coolabah. Grazing impact from kangaroos and also pigs. Introduced species- Cenchrus ciliaris dominant though sparse in ground layer. Also Sida spinosa. Little strew or outcrop. Light shower previous day.

On Cretaceous sediments. Very little relief for several kilometres. Very gentle slope to the north west. Vegetation community continues at least 500m in all directions from the plot. Introduced species- some Cenchrus ciliaris in scattered clumps particularly in north west corner. Grazing effect low- cattle present but site some distance from water point. Time since last fire unknown.

On an alluvial plain. Homogeneity- continues 500m to the south, same to east 1km to west as far as low hill. North is edge of Acacia cambagei community. Very few species. Introduced plant species- none seen. Grazing effect- moderate approximately 1km from bore. Fire- long unburnt. Strew mostly 2 to 10mm ironstone check soil sheet. Some larger mudstone pebbles/cobbles.

Fire- long unburnt no scaring on trees close by in river. Introduced plant species- low- some scattered clumps of Cenchrus ciliaris. To the west of quad slope is down to a creek which runs north to south. Some scalded areas in quad, denser patches where there is micro relief. Grazing effect low- some cattle present. Historically heavier. Some rain 2 months previous but vegetation mostly dry. Homogeneity- Community continues to the east 500km and 15m to west where there is a Coolabah flood out. 500m to north and 1km to south

Swamp. Some grazing from kangaroos and evidence of pigs, impact minimal. Likely heavily grazed historically- less than 1km from old yards. Long unburnt- no scarring on trees and little standing litter. introduced plant species- minimal. Shallow channels running north to south through the site.

Rapidly eroding toe slope of hills. Close to the basalt escarpment. Slope is broadly to the south away from the ranges. In south west corner is severely eroding gully creeping in on southern boundary and along western edge. Dry- only a few green tussock grasses in gully. Grazing effect is high, pads and scats. Long unburnt 10+ years. Introduced plants- only one small clump of Cenchrus ciliaris. Strew Lithology mixed. Larger cobbles basalt.

Stony plain Fire history difficult to tell- within last 5 years- maybe a little bit longer. Within the site are some deep holes to 40cms deep- possibly caused by trees burnt in last fire Introduced species effect- nil. Grazing effect is low- some old cattle scats in the site. Surface strew is mostly gravel and pebbles up to 50mm, some larger cobbles. Substrate is a mix of laterite, quartzite, and mudstone Homogeneity- site continues to the west 60m, north is road. To the East grades more into Eucalyptus leucophloia woodland, 50m to the south. Site is slightly elevated from clay plains. Slope is flat with no real discernible slope. Flat in visible vicinity.

Site long unburnt- no scars on Eucalyptus gillii. Grazing effect- some evidence of rabbits with diggings and scats. Also goats with some shrubs broken off. Introduced plants minimal scattered Sonchus oleraceus and Acetosa vesicaria.

Fire possibly in last 10 years though maybe slightly longer. Grazing effect moderate- mostly kangaroos. Introduced plant effect low- some scattered Sonchus oleraceus. Homogeneity- on southern edge is gully. Continues to the north east 100+ m up slope. South eastern edge is close to the hill crest and lookout area.

Slope and aspect 30-40o, two gullies converge at the North East corner, One come down from the south west and one from southeast. Lithology is metamorphosed sandstone and surface strew is much the same with a little bit of quartzite. Some outcrop more along southern edge. Community is relatively extensive, it extends up to the top of the ridge, a little bit more Eucalyptus flindersii on the rockier areas but Triodia irritans trends to dominate. Southwest corner is just next an old disused track that runs along the top of the ridge. Site is long unburnt. Minimal impact of introduced plant species. Minimal grazing impact, euros and possibly goats.

Average slope is 20 degrees but not even through the site. Drainage line runs out through the northern boundary and some more rocky outcrops through the centre of the site. Overall aspect is north west facing. Site long unburnt- some old dead timber but difficult to tell age. Grazing effect low- some evidence of rabbits and kangaroos have chewed grasses. Introduced plant minimal- some Sonchus oleraceus. Surface strew and lithology a mix of cobbles and larger boulders. Likely granite but need to check with soil sheet.

Undulating site- drainage line from north to south and site slope again to south east corner.  Weed impact is low- some Carrichtera annua and some annual forbs. Site long unburnt- no scarring or dead litter. Grazing effect is low- mainly kangaroos.Slope and aspect- centre point sits in a drainage line. With slope running in SW direction, running from NE. Substrate- limestone, sandstone, conglomerate. Gravels and small cobbles. Site has been long unburnt. Weed impact is low and grazing is minimal- kangaroos and possibly goats. Site situated south west of wheal turner mine. 12km North West of Arkaroola village. Homogeneity- site confined to plot. Nearest infrastructure is track 20m south of the plot.

Site on hillslope. Slope- 3 degrees to SW corner, but levels on north edge. Grazing is minimal- kangaroos. Introduced species is minimal. Some recorded last visit but all dry. Substrate- Sandstone outcrop with cobbles of sandstone. 15.7km north west of Balcanoona homestead. 15.6km south west of Arkaroola Village. Track 1km to the east. Homogeneity largely confined to plot, starts to thicken as It goes down hill slope

Homogeneity- site is more or less contained. North west corner opens up into Triodia hummock grassland while eastern edge grades into a Callitris glaucophylla. Mix of cobbles and boulders- larger rocks covered with lichen. Site is slightly convex- curving slightly at south east. Some forbs flowering through site, Grazing effect low- goats and possibly some cattle, scats seen. Long unburnt- no scarring on trees. Introduced species effect minimal- some Sonchus oleraceus

South Facing slope up to base of low range of hills. Lithology- mix of limestone and dolomite. Grazing effect moderate- Goats and rabbits. Site long unburnt- little grass to carry fire and shrubs spread widely. Weed effect- moderate- Carrichtera annua dominates ground layer although cover is sparse.

Very gently north sloping site. Mixed lithology and some other wash from further up the hill slope. Also some dolomite below surface. Mostly pebbles with some cobbles. Site long unburnt. Weed effect moderate to high- Carrichtera annua dominant ground layer as well some other annual weeds. Grazing effect is moderate- some cattle as well as goats and kangaroos. Light rain in morning of site visit as well as some other recent rain.

Slope is broadly to the south east getting steeper on northern edge of the site. Light rain previous day as well as other recent rain.  Weed effect moderate to high- some thick patches of wards weed and consistent through the site. Some other weedy annual forbs. Grazing effect- low. Some goats through the site. Fire- site long unburnt. No evidence of scaring on trees/ ash on ground. Lithology mostly pebbles- sandstone but some quartzite as well. Some small patches of sandstone outcrop with lichen cover.

Pit to 50cm. Auger to 80cm.and 5 subsites  in NW corner. SA Government photopoint #9935 stamped with SATSTP0001. Alluvial plain, no rock outcrop. Surface strew : 4/3/USA samples taken.
Flat site on Alluvial plain. Mixed surface lithology. Surface strew a mixed of pebbles and cobbles, most of it is weathered, metamorphic sandstone with some quartzite, ironstone and other unidentified rock. Fire- not recently burnt but difficult to tell how long from grasses. Effect of grazing- low, some from Kangaroos. Introduced plant effect minimal some Malvastrum americanum.

Grazing effect is low-some evidence of cattle, but mainly kangaroos. Also some rabbits. Introduced plant effect low-isolated clumps of Cenchrus ciliaris and some Sonchus oleraceus. Site long unburnt. Some dead litter but doesn’t seem to be from fire. No scarring on larger shrubs and trees.
Gibber Plain with sandy micro relief.
Low rise. Long unburnt, No weeds observed. Grazing impact low. Long haired rat holes in site. Adjacent to ACRIS bio monitoring site as16.
Co-located on NTG ACRIS biomonitoring Site.
Evidence of old disturbance on and near the site. An old track runs through the site and another just south of the site is badly eroded. However it appears that these tracks are no longer in use.
Broad longitudinal plain (north south aligned) about 5kms wide between dunes
Burnt 2011. grazing impact moderate. Weed impact low Cenchrus ciliaris present. Part of long swamp.

Shallow rill running from north west to south east. Site otherwise flat.
 Long unburnt. Weed impact nil. Some cattle pads but grazing impact minimal. Evidence of long haired rat burrows. Closest Acacia peuce- single tree 50m north of quadrat
Outer margins of Casuarina Swamp (also sampled at site NTASSD0015). Evidence of fires in 2011 - dead Acacias, much bare soil.

No slope but site interspersed with shallow drainage depressions. North east corner of site borders a lagoon some 20-30m wide by 1km long. Homogeneity- community is more or less confined to the site but extends 50m north and south beyond the site. To the west grades into more dense Excoecaria shrubland, to the east is the lagoon. Grazing effect low- some kangaroos and pigs. Introduced plant effect- low. Unburnt for previous 3-4+ years. Recent fire through Excoecaria shrubland south of the site.

Site on broad sandplain to the north of Waterhouse Range. Site burnt mid 2011, Regeneration underway in shrub layer. Minimal grazing effect, some old camel scats. Introduced species effect minimal- some scattered clumps of Cenchrus ciliaris. South of new powerline track.

Site in main channel of Hugh river, north of Waterhouse Range. Long unburnt- no scarring on any trees + sparse ground cover. Some grasses grazed likely by kangaroos, overall effect low. Introduced species affect moderate, some Cenchrus ciliaris, Cynodon dactylon, Sonchus spp. and Argemone sp. but also large number of native species. Undulating terrain but overall slope is to the south. North of gas line track. Homogeneity- east and west of the site is the edge of the main river channel. The community continues in the river channel 100m north and south of the site.

Site on outer floodplain of Hugh river north of Waterhouse Range. Long unburnt. Introduced species effect severe- Ground layer dominated by Cenchrus ciliaris. Grazing effect minimal though likely very heavy in the past ( close to old Owen Springs homestead.) Homogeneity- 50m + to the west to main channel, 100m to the south. To the north and east is low Mulga dominated rise.

Grazing effect is low to minimal. Fire- some scars on Eucalyptus tetrodonta and Eucalyptus miniata. Check with Bushfires NT plot data (site is Co-located with Bushfires Leaf fall plot). No introduced species noted. Site slopes more steeply to SW corner averaging 3 degrees through the site and 5 degrees at south west corner where gully is forming. Surface strew is a mix of cobbles and boulders mostly sandstone but possibly also some granite. Climate: At the end of wet season but soil surface is quite dry. On a plateau above Daly River Basin which drops away to the west.

Site is on a broad plain above heavy clays of the Mitchell grass downs. No grazing at present. Introduced species- ground layer dominated by Cenchrus ciliaris. Site burnt within 5 years-evidence of re-sprouting on canopy as well as burnt grass clumps.  Site is flat with only small contours for relief. Vegetation community continues 50m to the north and west and east. To the south borders the road and the community continues 50m beyond that. Site is sandy so no real surface strew.

Small swamp/ Drainage depression. Adjacent to a creek and site goes partially onto levee of a creek ( 10%) other side is 10% on the slope of metamorphic hill. Rest of the site is alluvial. Seepage off the hill. Running water in the site. Long unburnt- 5+ years since fire. Introduced species effect low- some Cenchrus ciliaris close to creek on the levee. No surface strew and very little bare soil. Lots of leaf litter.  No surface strew. An old track cuts through northern part of site. Introduced plant species effect is low- Cenchrus ciliaris present.

Site is a flat sandplain with the sand in the soil at depth. Termite mounds prominent.. Fire- some scaring but 5+years since last fire. Introduced species effect moderate- Cenchrus ciliaris common through the site. Site has been grazed but no cattle at present. Trees to 8m. Grass layer to 50cms. No surface strew- lots of bare soil and cryptogam.

Low hills surrounding Manton dam. Roughly 5 degree slope to the south east. Gets steeper to the south east corner where it dips into a gully. Subsurface damp. Recent fire possibly in last dry season. Check with Bushfires NT plot data (site is Co-located with Bushfires Leaf fall plot) Introduced species- none noted. Grazing effect: nil. Strew is mostly gravels with some boulders at south west corner probably granite- check soil sheet. Smaller strew is a mix of quartz and mudstone likely washed in from hill above site.

Termites mounds prominent. No surface strew or lithology. Lots of dead wood. No sign of recent fire -5+ years. No introduced plant species noted. Grazing effect- minimal. Recent rain with soil very damp.

Outer floodplain. 1km to nearest watercourse. Weed impact low -some Cenchrus ciliaris as isolated clumps. Grazing impact low. Lots of forbs and other perennials. Significant rain 1 month previous with follow up showers.

Homogeneity- contained north and south- coming out of river channel. Drainage line running from east to west- curves through site. Eastern edge of site is a waterhole.  Introduced plant effect high- Cenchrus ciliaris- Bathurst burr and other species. Grazing effect high. Cattle, kangaroos and pigs.  Long unburnt- no scarring on trees and recruitment of younger trees. Slope is broadly to the west but drainage ditches to 2m through the site.
Weed impact low- some Cenchrus ciliaris in small clumps .

Fire impact difficult to tell- no scorch marks on gidgee. Slight drainage line running due south close to south west corner. Coolabahs to South of site in drainage line. Slope- Broadly to the South. Several smaller channels. Older channels in site with main channel abutting the NE corner at large waterhole. Introduced plant effect.  Grazing effect low- no cattle but Kangaroos. Some impact from pigs seen on levee that is above high water mark on western boundary. Fire Long unburnt. Grazing impact low- kangaroos. Fire impact- long unburnt- No scarring on trees. Weeds- nil. Homogeneity- continues 60m in all directions. Road to the north but community continues on other side of road. Site on top of existing QPWS monitoring site

Shallow drainage line from eastern boundary to southern edge. At South westerly angle. Weed impact minimal. Long unburnt. Acacia aneura woodland with emergent poplar box and Ironbark. Acacia cambagei low woodland with sparse mid-stratum of Lysiphyllum carronii and bare ground stratum. Ground layer is heavily grazed. Minimal impact of introduced plant species- Cenchrus ciliaris.

Plain. No evidence of fire, but areas close by burnt within previous 3-4 years.  Lots of Mulga ant nests with echidnas but more likely goannas digging into mounds. No evidence of grazing. Weed impact low- some patches of Cenchrus ciliaris

Edge of small floodplain of Eastern Waterhouse Range Creek. Close to foot slopes of southern arm of Waterhouse Range. Weed impact high. Grazing impact low though has been heavily grazed in the past. Long unburnt.
Main channel of Hugh River. Weed impact low. Grazing impact low. Long unburnt
On top of the James Range. Long unburnt. Weed impact minimal. Grazing impact nil.

Plot in valley between hills of the James range.  Heavy rain throughout region on previous night. Grazing impact moderate, some cattle close to site. Long unburnt. Introduced plant species impact low.Cenchrus ciliaris present.

Recently burnt site on sandplain. Species identification difficult for some species due to their regeneration after the fire. Grazing impact low. Weed impact and species identification difficult to assess due to fire

Calcareous rise north of Waterhouse Range On limestone plateau. Grazing impact moderate- rabbit warrens within the site. Recent fire through the site though somewhat patchy in extent. Minimal impact of introduced plant species- -Cenchrus ciliaris present.

Recently burnt with only a few small drainage depressions remaining unburnt. Regrowth in the grass layer, not as yet in Acacia victoriae though not all were burnt in the fire. Grazing impact low. High impact of indroduced plant species- Cenchrus ciliaris high cover.
Plot on side slope of irregularly shaped dune. Recent patchy fire through the site with sections remaining unburnt. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.
Recently burnt inter - dune corridor. Regeneration- Lechenaultia and other species coming back.

Recruiting mulga to 1.5m then fringing up the  edge of sand dune on western edge. Long unburnt- at least 10 years. Recent fire to burnt to the north. Lots of old standing litter to 5-6m. Dense recruitment in Acacia aptaneura. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.
Long unburnt. Just outside boundary of Henbury meteorite crater reserve. Not heavily grazed at time of survey but likely has been in the past.

About 40mm of rain in previous 4-5 days. Damp underneath. No recent fire. Mix of Eucalyptus coolabah with diverse understorey.  Cattle pads in site but not heavily grazed. Moderate impact of introduced plant species- Cenchrus ciliaris moderate cover.

Homogenous- Slight run on are in SW corner. Run off area between 2 irregularly shaped dunes. Some Allocasuarina decaisneana but not many in quad but common in broader area. Recent rain- 8 days previous. 40mm. No signs of recent fire.  Low impact of introduced plant species- Cenchrus ciliaris low cover.

Elevated slightly from main channel of Finke river. Homogenous – slightly denser Eucalyptus camaldulensis on southern edge where main river channel is and borders denser thicket . Heavily grazed. No evidence of fire.  Not much litter in couch grass. Fringing Melaleuca glomerata thicket on southern edge- with scattered trees in site some reaching 10- 12m. Rainfall 8-9 days previous- 30mm. Low impact of introduced plant species- Cenchrus ciliaris low cover.
Cattle removed- regeneration in grasses. No recent fire. Rains 9 days ago- 30-40m. Minimal presence of introduced plant species.

On the edge of Alalgara waterhole. 2 lots of recent rain- 1st 30-40m 2nd unsure. Recent fire- 1 month ago. 1 long still burning but grasses regenerating. Northern side of quadrat is on edge of broader floodplain. Moderate impact of introduce species- Cenchrus ciliaris moderate cover.
On slope of low rise. Fringing Acacia aneura on western edge. Stony. Long unburnt. Some shallow gullies  to 20cm deep. Minimal presence of introduced plant species.

Recent rain- 40mm+ . Fire has trickled into SE corner of the site. Cool burn- no scorch marks on any of the tree. The rest  of the plot is long unburnt. Very homogenous. Sporobolus and several other species may have come from nearby hills hence higher than expected  diversity. Close to Finke river- Closest red gums of the outer channel are about 300m away with the main channel being about  500m. High impact of introduced plant species- Cenchrus ciliaris dominant, high cover.
Eriachne aristidea and Triodia basedowii dominant with Allocasuarina decaisneana.  Moderate impact of introduced plant species- Cenchrus ciliaris moderate cover.

Open site with scalded areas. No real over storey only 1 or 2 shrubs. Grazing impact low- grazed more heavily on other side of the fence. Rain in last month- regeneration.  Rocky site on clay soil with vegetation clustered in less stony areas. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.
Sandy intrusion on south east corner. Run on area at bottom of slope to the south of the site. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.
No evidence of recent fire. Rain last month- some annuals have come up. Grazing impact low.Triodia basedowii with some Eucalyptus gamophylla. Minimal impact of introduced plant species

Sand dune to North  but swamp  continues to South  East and West,. Chenopod understorey with only scattered shrubs. Grazing impact heavy- both  horses and cattle. No sign of recent fire- dead trees but likely from dry. 4 months or so since rain longer again since flood. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.

Sandy intrusion at base of hill. Weed impact low. Some grazing from horses- track on edge of quad- but grasses more or less intact. No evidence of fire. Previous rain- 4 months. Sandy at bottom grading to more rocky at the top of the site. South of quadrat the slope flattens out to a  chenopod shrubland. To the east is a drainage line and the railway and on the other side of the railway is another hill slope facing west. Low impact of introduced plant species- Cenchrus ciliaris low cover.

Rain previous week.  Long unburnt . Some standing litter from previous fire . Grazing impact low- some pads. Most grasses intact. Weed impact- moderate. Cenchrus ciliaris more dense in areas run on areas.

Gently sloping site at the base of range. Rain 1 week previous. Damp underneath.  Top of slope north of the site is limestone band covered by Triodia brizoides No recent fire. Weed minimal- some small clumps of Cenchrus ciliaris

Flat site in shallow drainage depression. Long unburnt due to sparse cover. Grazing impact moderate- 3km from water point. Grass layer still intact. Shallow drainage line running from NW corner to the SW corner at about 30m mark.  Larger channel off to the west just beyond the site. Some rock in drainage channel but mostly bare ground.  Weed impact- low. Scattered clumps of Cenchrus ciliaris
Low rocky rise. No major outcrops but stony throughout the site. Lots of cryptogam crust.  Long unburnt. No evidence of grazing or weeds. Approx. 10km from nearest water point.

Recent fire in north of the site with patches burnt along northern edge. Stony site with more open patches of bare ground. No evidence of grazing with the site being a long way from any permanent water points. No rain for past 2-3 weeks.
Sandplain over sandstone. Burnt in last dry season with active regeneration . Pockets of low sandstone outcrops. No evidence of grazing. Last rainfall a few weeks previous.

Site in low range of hills. Sandplain with rocky sandstone outcrops throughout. Very long unburnt. Drainage line/creek running through western edge.  Scattered ephemeral waterholes with water in creek. Some of taller rocky outcrops to 2 meters. Slope to south western corner to larger rise . Some evidence of grazing with some hoof prints but not heavy. No weeds of note.

Flood out of Burton Creek.  South East corner is on edge of main channel with the site rising out onto a small flood out  The South west corner rises just out of the flood out on a small rise. The site hasn’t been burnt for 4+ years. No recent rain for past few weeks. Not grazed at present. Minimal weed impact.

Northern edge of site is 500m from low rocky sandstone hill . Has been burnt regularly but hasn’t burnt in last two years. Recent fire close by across road has. Grazing impact low due to Triodia. Nearest Water point 3km away- some cattle prints within the site.
Stony/Gravelly site. Long unburnt. Last rain at least 3 weeks previous. Not real evidence of grazing. Weed impact nil.

Site borders edge of Burton river. Eucalyptus camaldulensis in the river channel but none within the site. Grazing moderate- grasses intact but cattle in site. Long unburnt with little standing litter-5+years. Last rainfall 3 weeks +.   South west boundary of the site close to bore track. Unlikely to have flood out in previous ( drier) wet season

Stony/Gravelly site. Homogeneous to 150m. Fire within the last 2-3 years with site having been burnt fairly evenly throughout. Grazing impact moderate with evidence of horses and cattle Last Rainfall- 1 month+. Not signs of stress yet. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.

Long unburnt site (4-5 years+) with no scorch marks and the shrub layer being intact. There has been a fire to the north of the site but the access road has acted as a break. Last rain was at least 1 month previous.  Weed impact minimal. Homogeneity- to the north the site abuts a track. To the south the vegetation community continues approximately 100m before  grading into a Eucalyptus leucophloia Mallee woodland similar to the previous site ( NTAGFU0010) Grazing impact moderate- horses and cattle around. Most grasses still intact. The paddock is not formally grazed. The site is 500-600m from and ephemeral waterhole in a shallow creek.

Site is on a plateau west of the high point of a low range of hills. Long unburnt- no scotch marks on trees. Grazing impact low as most of the site is fairly unpalatable. 1month + since last rain. Weed impact- low. Homogeneity- community continues 100m to the south. To the north is a track which has been burnt on the other side.

Long unburnt 4+ years- some standing litter from previous fire. Grazing impact is low with some cattle scats but no pads through the site. Homogeneity- Site abuts track on northern boundary. The community continues 50m to the south and west. From  the east edge the site grades into a Eucalyptus pruinosa Mallee woodland. Run on area- water likely sits around in wet season. Introduced plant species impact minimal- Stylosanthes hamata low cover.

On edge of Cumingia creek. Some drainage lines 20cms deep on northern boundary.  South West corner also has shallow drainage line flowing south east.  Grazing impact high. Weed impact low. Long unburnt. Homogeneity- site abuts track to the north. Community continues 100m down to river on southern boundary. To the East and West it continues another 50m.

Edge of Cumingia creek flood out.  Homogeneity- the community is quite discreet to the boundaries of the quadrat.  Grazing impact is moderate. Some of the tussock grasses have been eaten and there are some cattle pads within the site. Long unburnt 4+ years.  No rainfall for at least 1.5 months.  1-2 very shallow erosion channels in cattle pads. Introduced plant species impact minimal- Stylosanthes hamata low cover.

Site has been burnt within the last 2 years or so. Fire to within 30m whilst site being undertaken. Grazing impact is low. Some cattle tracks. Rain 1.5 months + previous. Homogeneity- the community continues 50m to the west but stops at eastern and northern

Site in shallow valley that slopes up at the South West and North East corners. 100m from little Calvert river which is still flowing.  Grazing impact low with some cattle prints and some digging most likely from pigs.  Long unburnt but Melaleuca viridiflora in southern section is much shorter possibly as a result of previous fire. Homogeneity- The site is more or less discrete with the edge of site being the edge of the community though does extend 20m the south east and the same to the north west.  No recent rain but still damp particularly in the North western corner. South west corner is a little bit drier. Minimal impact of introduced plant species- Hyptis suaveolens present.

Rocky site on side slope of low hill. Termite mounds and standing litter.  Fire 2+ years. Grazing pressure low- no cattle tracks seen. North East corner of the site abuts main Calvert hills road. Old cut line/track through northern boundary of the site which has reclaimed by Acacia shirleyi. Weed impact nil. 2+ months since previous rain. Homogeneity- South eastern boundary borders on a more dense Acacia shirleyi thicket with Triodia pungens dominating the hill crest above this.   Community continues 100m to the west, 20m on other side of road to the north and 50m to east.

Flat, gravelly site at the base of a low range of hills.  Some small undulations and occasional larger stones. Homogeneity- the site extends  50m to south ( over road) and the same to the East. To the western edge is borrow pit for road. North of the site grades into a Terminalia sp. shrubland. Termites minimal. The site appears to have been burnt approximately 2 years previous- no fruit under Eucalyptus  and Corymbia would seem to indicate this. Grazing impact low- some pats but no pads. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.

Swamp on the edge of unnamed tributary of the Kilgour river. Weed impact low- some Stylosanthes hamata.  Grazing impact low. Some pads in the site. Long unburnt- no standing litter and no scorch marks on trees. Slight slope to the south east towards a small river 200m away. Homogeneity- Community continues 20m to the west. The south west corner borders a track and the community continues another 50m on the other side.  On eastern  and northern boundaries the community begins to grade into a Eucalyptus  pruinosa Mallee woodland

Rocky site between two ranges. The main Abner range to the south and an unnamed range to the north.  Site slopes down to shallow creek on southern edge continues up the other side. A shallow drainage line runs more or less due east to west. Grazing impact low with one or two pads within site. Long unburnt- no scorch marks on Melaleuca stenostachya  and tussock grasses dense. A Recent  Fire on other side of track hasn’t crossed into the site. A drainage line runs through southern edge more or less west to east. Site continues up the slope on other side. Homogeneity- the community is more or less contained within the site. At the North East corner is a track. To the south the community grades into a Eucalyptus  leucophloia and  Triodia bitextura open Mallee woodland. Introduced plant species impact minimal- Stylosanthes hamata low cover.

Rocky site on a low rise. Site is almost convex with the high point where photo point is and sloping down on all 4 sides.  Homogeneity- community extends 50m to the West, 20m to the South.  To the east is a Eucalyptus Pruinosa sparse Mallee woodland. To the north the site borders a diversion track which bisects the line between the Eucalyptus leucophloia and Eucalyptus pruinosa communities. Weeds- Nil. Grazing impact low. 2+ years since last fire with no standing litter and scorch marks on Eucalyptus leucophloia . Somewhat  difficult to tell however with the absence of a  shrub layer but some recruitment in Eucalyptus leucophloia.

Sandplain on the top of the Abner range. Access via  newly upgraded mining exploration track. Homogeneity- site extends 50m to the west, east and north. To the south the site borders a track with the community continuing another 50m across the track. Community likely extends beyond this but the thickness of the vegetation dictates a more conservative figure. Weeds impact nil. Grazing impact nil. Some pig tracks close to quadrat.  No evidence of fire within 3+ years. Scorch marks on Eucalyptus setosa but difficult to tell how old.

Stony site with extensive low sandstone outcrops on to top of the Abner range. Access via newly upgraded mining exploration track. Weed impact- none. Grazing impact none. Long unburnt- no scorch marks on trees. Homogeneity- The northern edge grades into more open Triodia bitextura hummock grassland.  60m further north from the site is more dense stand of Grevillea pteridifolia as occurs at the previous site ( NTAGFU0023). To the south the community continues another 100m and another 50m to the East and West.

Melaleuca stenostachya swamp on the top of the Abner range. Access via new upgraded mining exploration track. Grazing impact- nil. Long unburnt. No evidence of scorch marks or standing litter to indicate recent fire. Homogeneity- Community extends 70m to the west, South and East. The northern boundary is set back 20m from the access track with the community continuing over the other side of the track another 50m

Flat site the edge of the Eastern creek. Some  evidence of grazing though likely more heavily  in the past. River in south east has cattle pads. Long unburnt- no scorch marks but recent fire on other side of the river.  Homogeneity- community continues 20m to the south and 30m to the north. To the west the community grades into a more open Grevillea striata shrubland and to east, beyond the site, it drops quickly into the main channel of the river. Minimal impact of introduced plant species - Passiflora foetida present.

Site is at base south west facing range. Creek running south east to south west just beyond the southern boundary of the site. Drainage line off road runs just through the northern edge of site. Grazing impact low though dead cow within the site. Fire- scorch marks on trees from 2-3 years previous. Dead Acacia hammondii in South West corner where fire has come in. Homogeneity Community continues  50m to west, 30m to the South and 20m North. To the East borders the road. Low impact of introduced plant species- Stylosanthes hamata low cover.

Rocky site sloping down from the north east corner. Increasingly rocky up the slope with a range of low hills along the eastern boundary. The north west corner is close to the track leading to Butterfly spring. Homogeneity- The community only extends to the west by another 20m (up to the track) To east the community is grading into a  eucalyptus miniata/leucophloia  woodland and to the South a Eucalyptus phoenicea sparse woodland. Grazing impact- low. No evidence of cattle. Burnt 1-2 years. Scorch marks on trees. Weed impact low- some Stylosanthes hamata present as trace cover

Edge of catfish waterhole. North east corner is on the edge of waterhole. Site sloping to the north east down to the waterhole with the south west corner being close to the road. Weed impact moderate- Stylosanthes hamata common within the site. Grazing impact- moderate some cattle/buffalo grazing and pigs digging on edge of waterhole. Homogeneity- community continues another 50m to the north west and to the south east. Fire- 2+ years. Recent fire close to quadrat stopped by shallow drainage line which runs west to east just to the north of the site.

Flat site on the crest of a hill. Long unburnt-  Not recent scaring on trees. Grazing impact-low. Some cattle droppings in the site and some of the grasses have been grazed. Digging possibly from pigs getting to roots of the Haemodorum. Homogeneity- The community continues 60m to the west and to the south. To the east is borrow pit and to the north is fence line and track with the community going another 50m beyond that.  Weed impact low- some Stylosanthes scabra

Flat site sloping slightly to the north east. A shallow drainage line runs just to the north of site. Long unburnt- no scaring on Melaleuca viridiflora. Grazing impact low- some cattle scats. Also Pigs digging in the wet. Homogeneity- community continues 100m to the south. To the north the community grades into an Acacia shirleyi woodland in a rocky gully. To the West is a road but community continues 20m on other side of the road. To the East is more Acacia shirleyi mixed with  Melaleuca viridiflora

Convex sloping site in a valley between low hills. Long unburnt. Homogeneity- community continues 50m to the  north and west (on other side of track). It continues 20m up the slope to the south. Grazing impact- low. Some cattle pads, horse scats.

Rocky, convex sloping site sloping predominantly to the North East but also to the south west. Fire- long unburnt. Previous fire hot- lots of fallen debris all through site. Homogeneity- South west of the site grades into a more open Eucalyptus leucophloia Mallee woodland. To the West and east the community continues another 50m. The northern boundary borders  the road where the community stops.  Grazing impact- low. Some Horse droppings and the odd cattle pat.

Swamp on a flood out. Long unburnt- no scarring. Homogeneity - community continues 50m over track towards river. North boundary of the site is close to track. Bad lands/eroded area mark the western boundary. Grazing impact- moderate. Cattle pads horses. Heavily grazed in past. Weed impact nil.

Stony site on south west facing slope of low rise. Flatter at top of site in the east with more bare ground towards the south west corner. A drainage line runs north to south just outside the western boundary of the site. Homogeneity- community continues south another 50m. To the West it grades into Melaleuca viridiflora/ Melaleuca stenostachya shrubland and to the north into an Acacia shirleyi woodland. Grazing impact low -some pads and tracks in quad. Fire- long unburnt due to sparse grass cover.

Rocky, sloping site on spur at the base of a low hill. Dropping into a gully on the north eastern edge. Grazing impact- moderate. Cattle pads in site but grasses intact. No evidence of weeds. Fire impact low. No scorch marks on Acacia shirleyi or Eucalyptus leucophloia or much fallen litter. Homogeneity- community continues 50m north west and south east along the ridge top. East and west of the site the community grades into a Eucalyptus leucophloia Mallee woodland

Swamp on edge of Mariok creek. Floodplain with lots of run on areas.  Site flat with a few shallow drainage depressions running through the site. Grazing impact-heavy. Cattle and horses. Homogeneity- community continues 50m on all sides. Long unburnt- no scarring on trees.

North sloping site on a low rise with the southern boundary of the site just creating the rise. Grazing impact low- some cattle droppings. Long unburnt- not much standing litter. Homogeneity- community continues west 100m along ridge cap. To the north another 50m down the slope where it grades into Eucalyptus leucophloia. The same applies on the southern edge. To the east is a track and the community continues for another 50m beyond this. Weed impact low.

Site on the edge of the Mariok creek floodplain at the base of a low rise. Weed impact- low. Long unburnt- no scaring on trees or standing litter. Grazing impact high but still grass cover. Homogeneity- site is more or less contained. To the north grades into Eucalyptus microtheca sparse woodland while to the east and south up the slope is more Eucalyptus leucophloia

Site in a valley between low hills. Long unburnt. No scorch on trees and recruitment in Corymbia polycarpa and  Acacia dimidiata. Moderately impacted by grazing but grasses still intact.  Homogeneity- vegetation is patchy around the site. To the east and west of the site is more Melaleuca viridiflora shrubland with emergent Eucalyptus tectifica. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.

Marked in SW corner by DEWNR photo point tag # 11898 stamped SATKAN 1.Very long unburnt. No evidence of fire scarring on Eucalyptus baxteri or on Xanthorrhoea semiplana subsp. semiplana Weed impact moderate- Ulex europaeus (Gorse ) and grassy weeds and forbs in North east corner. 
Steeply sloping site down to a valley in the North east corner.

Gently Sloping site with slope to the north west. Shallow ephemeral creek in north west corner. Site parallel to slope rather than up and down. Burnt within last 5 years. Site boxed in by Heysen trail to the south west-30m away. Other walking track abuts south east corner.SE corner labelled with DEWNR Photopoint tag 11900 and stamped SATKAN 2.Pit in SW corner
Site in Swale. Slope to dune in the North east corner. Plot running North west to South East.
Site straddles two dunes with a crest sloping to a swale then another crest in the North West corner. Plot running North west to South East. Pit at NW corner.
Dune Swale on Western side of Colson Track , Simpson Desert.  Plot running North west to South East. Swale.
Dune swale on western side of Colson Track. Plot running North west to South East.
Dune crest/slope. Plot running North west to South East.
Dune crest/slope. Plot running North west to South East
Swale. Plot running North west to South East. Run on area in North east corner.
Dune crest/slope. Plot running North west to South East.

SA Gov. Department of Environment & Natural Resources tag #11881 in SW corner.Not much disturbance. Banksia marginata have fallen over possibly due to phytophthora?. Very long unburnt- no scorch marks on trees. Slope- almost straddles a low dune. More sparse veg on the top of the dune.  Grazing impact low but heavy across in the  neighbouring paddock. Some kangaroo pads. No surface strew rocks etc.- sandy. Dune running from east to west so slope is to the south with the northern edge just over the top of the dune. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.

On side slopes of Black hill. North west facing (curving around the slope to the north). Long unburnt (burn close by within last few days).  No scarring on Allocasuarina muelleriana subsp. muelleriana. Grazing impact minimal. Weed impact low- some introduced  tussock grasses including Vulpia muralis. DEWNR Photo point 11870 stamped with SATFLB0012. Pit in NE corner.

Pattern is a rise- much more calcareous to west of site but element is a dune slope.  2 degree slope to the east. Very long unburnt- very mature spinifex and a lot of leaf litter and no scarring. Grazing effect is low. Introduced plant effect is minimal. Homogeneity- western edge of the plot is edge of community- rises up onto limestone ridge. Community continues to the north, south and east. Northern edge is 20m in from northern access track for park. Site is also DEW monitoring plot- photo point on northern edge and stereo photopoint towards SW corner. 1 possibly more lines of pitfall traps towards northern edge of plot.
