Calcrete pan at 30cm. Low open Mallee woodland ridge slope.

Gently sloping site close to the top of the spring gully ridge. Broadly sloping to the west forming into a gully on the western edge. Fire impact-10+ years. No scorch marks. Homogeneity- 50m to the south 20-30 to the west eastern edge the same. Weed impact moderate- Lavandula stoechas subsp. stoechas, Rosa rubiginosa, Prunus domestica and some tussock grasses. Grazing impact low- some kangaroo tracks. Marked with DEWNR Photo point tag 11871 stamped SATFLB0013 in NW corner

Slope to the west ( range running north south) increasingly rocky to the top.  Very long unburnt 100+ years. Weed impact low- some grasses at base of site. Grazing impact low-  21 years since stock removed.   Some grazing from Kangaroos. Homogeneity-  western edge more open rockier at eastern edge at top of the range. 50 to south. Western edge stops. 10-15m to the east. 10-15m to the north.Marked with DEWNR Photo point tag 11872 stamped SATFLB0014 in SW corner . No soil pit dug as too rocky.

Soil Pit in SE corner. Marked with SA Gov. Dept. Environment Photopoint tag#11882 and stamped SATFLB2. Fire on south facing slope, within the  last 2- 5 years. Some strew as well as some outcrop in the south west corner of plot. Weed impact  low- some  Asparagus asparagoides . Grazing impact low. Steep east facing slope . Eastern edge borders track. North east corner close to track.

SW corner marked with SA Gov.Department of Environment permanent photopoint tag #11883.Long unburnt. Weed impact low. No grazing. Sloping shallow gully from north to south. Several large rock outcrops. Small amount of strew in form of sandstone and quartzite gravel. Gently sloping site bordered by fire track on southern edge

Grazing impact high- goat tracks and droppings. Rabbit droppings also. Lots of Yellow footed rock wallabies close to the site.  Long unburnt- not much grass to carry fire. Overnight rain. Cheilanthes sieberi subsp. sieberi opening up. Slope uneven, 17- 18 degree slope to the south west.  South west corner almost in creek. Another creek running along southern edge of quadrat. Bottom transect on southern boundary goes through this gully. Weed impact low- some Carrichtera annua. Rocky on the surface, moss where there would be bare ground. Some outcrop at the top of the site. Steep slope on the mid reaches of the Brachina gorge catchment. Very rocky, soil sampling stopped by rock at most sub sites.

Top of the range above Brachina gorge. On cap of the slope dropping away to the north east. North west corner drops off edge of the ridge on the other side.Site straddles ridge.  Large amount of rock covered by cryptogam -boulders. Not a lot of bare ground. Long unburnt-10+ years.  Some dead fallen litter from previous fire. Grazing impact from goats- scats and tracks though less than previous site (FLB004) Weeds minimal.

South west marker tagged with DEWNR # 11873 with TERN # SATFLB0015. Fire in last 10 years- scarring on Eucalypt species but shrub layer has come back. Weed impact high including: Rubus anglocandicans, Genista monspessulana, Watsonia sp. Homogeneity.- Community continues down the slope 40m 50m.  Up the slope a walking tracks runs along the southern edge. Site is on spur. Slope is North to south in centre falling to the North west and Northeast on the northern edge. 7-8 degree slope in the centre grading up to 15 degrees at the north east and north west corners . Grazing impact- lots of kangaroo and echidnas diggings.

Comment from 21/08/2012 visit - On the slope of Mt hack escarpment.  Site heavily grazed. Goat scats and tracks throughout plot. Long unburnt- no scarring on Mallee.  Rocks to 10-15 cm in strew. Top section has a little outcrop. Not much strew bigger than 30cm. Slope to the south but also slightly convex- east to west. Weed impact minimal.
Comment from 21/08/2018 Surface strew is sandstone, as is outcrop. Slope and aspect, the southern edge is flatter increase in slope towards the northern edge up to a 5o slope. Overall aspect is southerly, it does dip away slightly to the south western corner. Site is long unburnt. Introduced species is same a previous visit. Grazing impact is similar to previous visit, moderately grazed by goats and kangaroos.

Lower side slopes of Mt Ohlssen bagge. Rocky- large boulders and outcrop. Burnt within last year.  Grazing low only because not much feed- Xanthorrhoea quadrangulata impacted by goats. Goat  droppings within the site. Some regrowth in Eucalyptus flindersii and E. Intertexta and  also at base of Allocasuarina muelleriana subsp. muelleriana and Casuarina pauper on the very lower layer of the trunk but  chewed out by goats most probably.
Adjacent to flux tower. About 10kms northwest of Calperum Station and about 20kms north of Renmark.
2 km. south east of the Flux tower SASMDD0001, 100m in easterly direction from track.
North of Rotten Lake on Calperum Station, 20.5 North of Renmark. High impact of introduced plant species- Salvia verbenaca high cover, Medicago minima low cover.

Patchy pockets of Acacia but fairly consistent. 200m to the south. To the east is a slight drainage depression. Site is flat with a few very shallow undulations through the site.

Limestone / Calcareous gravel through the site with the odd larger cobble. Grazing effect low- some evidence of rabbits, cattle and camels. Fire- very long unburnt, difficult to tell how long. Site is a drainage depression with rises to the east and west of the site. Fire- likely burnt within last 10-15  years. Lots of dead Acacia aneura- taller than current cohort to 7m.  Introduced plant effect moderate- Brassica tournefortii and Sonchus oleraceus common through the site. Remnant vegetation on private property. Site is on a 12 degree slope to the North east. Shallow gully through the middle of the site. Introduced species effect is moderate- some introduced grasses and some Senecio quadridentatus. Some cobbles in a few places- check soil sheet for lithology.

Plot is flat- rises very gently south of the plot .Weed effect is moderate- Carrichtera annua common through the site. Fire- difficult to tell but long unburnt. Very little cover once site dries out. Mostly limestone cobbles with some smaller gravel.

Site is a flat, shallow lake or swamp. Lots of holes through the site and some gently undulating low rises. Some limestone wash and some very small limestone outcrops. Fire- lots of standing dead litter but unburnt in previous 10 years. Homogeneity- drainage depression and associated community continues 100m to west. 200m to the north. 30m to the south and east

Plot is flat but sits in a drainage depression between very low rises. Some limestone cobbles and gravel- larger ones with cryptogam crust. Some very low limestone outcrop- almost at ground level. Very long unburnt but difficult to tell exactly how long. Grazing effect is low- some evidence of rabbits. Introduced plant effect is moderate- Carrichtera annua common throughout the site. Homogeneity- community continues another 50m north of the road which is close to the northern edge of the plot. 20m to the east and 50m to the west where there is a low rise. 100m to the south along the drainage line.

Undulating plain. Strew mostly limestone gravel- some pebbles. Some little pockets of outcrop/ rock.  2 degree average slope but drops away more steeply at the south east corner. Fire- long unburnt. Homogeneity- community continues 200m from the plot in all directions.

Plot is on a flat plain. Some limestone pebbles and gravels through the plot. Fire- long unburnt. No scarring on any of the larger shrubs. Grazing effect is low- some camels around but effect is low. Introduced plant effect minimal. Homogeneity- continues in a patchy fashion 100m in all directions

Community is confined to the plot. Nearest infrastructure is a station access track 50m from the southern edge of the plot.

Calcareous plain with gibber and bare ground. Evidence of cattle grazing. Site is homogeneous and part of an extensive community.

Comment from 28/10/2014 - Homogeneous site except small part of northeast corner that drops into the dune swale. The reserve is small (c.2ha) and surrounded by cropping land. No obvious impact from fire or ferals but some evidence (old warrens) of past rabbit impact. Weeds are prominent in ground layer especially Asparagus asparagoides and control program is evident (signage, markers). Site is on dune crest with slope to northeast, east and southwest. Comment from 25/09/2018 - Site is located at Pengilly Scrub. 11km north west of Gawler, 48km north north east of Adelaide. The land was bequeathed to the council 1968 and in 1988, the site had a conservation covenant placed over it. The site has had a fair bit of weeding done to it with the plot situated in the “less good” part of the site. The northern edge is much better in terms of remnant vegetation and native grasses but plot site was chosen due to homogeneity. Site was significantly burnt in the 2015 Pinery fire but has recovered quickly with 25 new species new regenerating, including some thought to be on way out, Westringia, Dodonaea bursariifolia, along the northern edge. Some selective herbicide use to control bridal creeper. Weed impact is high- Avena, Bromus, Asparagus asparagoides, Brassica, Oxalis pes-caprae. Grazing impact medium- hares, kangaroos. Slope and aspect-v complicated slope to north and south. Substrate is sand. Community is confined to plot

Plain. Flat site with no discernible drainage. Introduced plant effect is low. Grazing effect is low- mainly kangaroos. Fire history difficult to tell- some dead standing Acacia papyrocarpa but no scarring on any of the trees. 10-20 years at least since last fire. Some limestone gravel and pebbles. Also white cryptogam crust. Wet- rain in preceding days.

Very flat. Community continues 200m in all directions from the site. Wet- some recent rain. Lots of limestone gravel and Cryptogam through the site. Fire- some standing dead Acacia papyrocarpa but very long unburnt with no scarring on trees. Grazing effect is low- some kangaroos. Introduced plant effect moderate- Carrichtera annua through the site but cover fairly low.

Very long unburnt- no scarring on any of the trees and no dead standing litter 30+ years. Grazing effect is low- some rabbits and kangaroos. Introduced plant effect- minimal. Dune slope in Dunefield. Wet- recent rain in previous day and also before that.  Homogeneity- continues to the west 60m. Opens up to the north on the dune crest and another 50m to the east where it joins the road. Slope is 2 degree slope through the centre of the site to the north west but site is convex. Rises at the south east corner and the northern slope.

Very flat plain. Mixed of limestone gravel, pebbles and boulders- mostly gravel. Some low limestone outcrop and a doe-line and shallow sinkhole in the north east corner. Grazing effect is very low-no sheep but evidence of some rabbits and the odd cattle scat. Very long unburnt. Introduced plant species- some isolated Sonchus oleraceus and Erodium aureum but cover very low. Homogeneity- community continues 1km in all directions. Wet- recent rain in last few days.

Grazing effect is low- some evidence of camels with older broken trees. Very little surface strew. Site is flat plain. Introduced plant species- none noted. Homogeneity- site is in consistent patch of Acacia aneura / Acacia papyrocarpa woodland with the community extending 200m in all directions with just the odd emergent Allocasuarina pauper outside the plot.

Slope of low limestone rise. Some scattered calcareous material through the site. Grazing effect is low- evidence of camels with some foot prints through the site but effect is low. Fire- some dead Acacia papyrocarpa but long dead. 15- 20 years since last fire. Weed effect minimal- scattered Carrichtera annua. Homogeneity- 60m to south and west. 30m To the east where it joins the road and 50m to the north. Continues with scattered Acacia papyrocarpa and Atriplex vesicaria.

Flat plain. Very slight slope up to the south east corner. Introduced plant effect- some Carrichtera annua but cover is very low.  Some grazing from camels and also wombats- large burrow on edge of the site. Very long unburnt. Some calcareous gravels. Homogeneity- continues 1km in all directions. Northern horizon has dune.

Low limestone rise through the centre of the site. Uneven slope through the site. Minimal grazing. Introduced species high- Carrichtera annua, Malva parviflora, Brassica tournefortii, Sisymbrium erysimoides and Sonchus oleraceus but none dominant. Homogeneity- continues in a patchy form 50m in all directions. Fire- difficult to tell. Some long dead Myoporum platycarpum and Acacia papyrocarpa but no scarring on any of the trees.

Drainage depression rising on the western edge to a low limestone ridge. Broader pattern is a dune field with limestone underneath.  Slope listed as zero but site is bowl shaped, curving up from the centre. Introduced plant effect low- some Sonchus oleraceus, Carrichtera annua but minimal cover . Grazing effect is low but some evidence of rabbits on the edge of the site. Small limestone sheet / flat outcrop in north west corner with scattered limestone gravel scattered through bits of the site. Homogeneity- site has drainage line through the centre of the site where Tecticornia sp. is thicker but is indicative of surrounding community with patchiness at a less the 1 hectare scale.

Limestone rise in the centre of the site. Slope listed as zero but is 4 degrees in all directions downwards from the centre of the site.  Lots of Cryptogam crust and bare ground. Grazing effect is low- some old rabbit scats noted.  Weed effect low - Mesembryanthemum crystallinum present but cover low. Very long unburnt- some dead samphire but not from fire. Homogeneity- community continues along the coast from the back of the dune system with patterns of limestone spurs with sandier patches where sand has accumulated.

Site on the slope of low relic dune. Sloping gently to the south east. Very long unburnt- at least 1970s since fire possibly longer. Grazing effect low- rabbits in park but no evidence within the plot. Introduced plant effect low- some Carrichtera annua creeping in on the crest of the dune in the north western edge of the plot where it opens up more but cover is low. Lots of Cryptogam crust and leaf litter.
A sandplain fringed by relic dunes some distance away. High impact of introduced plant species- Carrichterea annua high cover and some Sonchus sp.
Sandplain sloping to a very low dune in north east corner. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.
Flat sand plain with calcrete underneath.Some limestone nodules or Calcretions- nothing bigger than 5 cms. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.

Drainage depression on sand plain. Plot is more or less in a bowl with dunes at southern and northern edges. On the southern boundary is a very low sandy rise with Dodonaea along it. Some recruitment of Dodonaea from here into the site. High impact of introduced plant species- Salvia verbenaca high cover.
Low samphire shrubland at Playa Lake, Scotia Sanctuary.Playa lake surrounded by lunette dunes. Southern third has sandy wash, remainder is clay. Centre point only point marked with picket.

Plain. Undulating rise with Mallee to the north east and south of the site. Very long unburnt-low cover to carry fire. Surface strew minimal but dense cryptogam crust. Very gentle slope, 1 degree, to the north east corner. Introduced plant effect is high- dense pockets of Carrichtera annua particularly in the south west corner. Grazing effect is moderate- rabbits and kangaroos.  Wet- recent rain. Homogeneity- community continues 300m north, west 300m, east 50m then Mallee, south 60m then Mallee

Austrostipa sp. and Danthonia sp. tussock grassland with a very sparse shrub layer of Maireana sedifolia, Nitraria/ Lycium and Geijera. Long unburnt. Some limestone gravel and some very low outcrop. Evidence of cattle grazing- dung, Rabbits and Wombats- warren in north west corner. Introduced plant effect is moderate- Carrichtera annua common throughout the site. Plain on a tableland.

Acacia aneura mixed shrubland with Acacia nyssophylla, Eremophila latrobei, Senna artemisioides subsp. filifolia and emergent Allocasuarina pauper. Ground layer dominated by Ptilotus obovatus. Very long unburnt. No introduced plant species noted. Grazing effect low- some evidence of camels through the site. Very flat- no discernible slope. Dry- though some rain over 1 month previous, grasses just beginning to hay off

Acacia rostellifera shrubland with Myoporum insulare, Acacia sp., and Rhagodia baccata. Ground layer of Threlkeldia sp., Carpobrotus and Tetragonia on rolling coastal dunes. Approximately 100m from the beach. Slope is zero but site is undulating throughout. Long unburnt with much dead material- Mostly Myoporum sp. and Acacia sp. Introduced plant effect is minimal. Grazing effect is minimal.

Eucalyptus gracilis / Eucalyptus socialis low Mallee woodland with some Eucalyptus oleosa. Mid layer of Melaleuca lanceolata, Eremophila scoparia and Pomaderris and a ground layer dominated by Westringia rigida. Plain with limestone gravel surface strew. Long unburnt. Grazing effect is low-some old camel dung and kangaroos. No introduced plant species noted. Recent rain. Active vegetation growth. Much litter around base of eucalyptus. Flowering in Pomaderris sp. and Eucalypts have buds.

Within fenced Scotia sanctuary, dune field with the plot on a gentle dune slope. Slope 2 degrees to the north. Very Long unburnt- 30-40 years. Grazing effect is moderate but lots of fauna diggings. Introduced plant effect is minimal. Cirsium vulgare present.

Melaleuca lanceolata, Acacia anceps diverse shrubland with other shrubs including Rhagodia crassifolia, Nitraria billardierei, Myoporum insulare and Geijera linearifolia. Ground Layer of Carpobrotus virescens, Zygophyllum billardierei, Threlkeldia diffusa and Atriplex vesicaria. Dune- 300m from the beach. Deep undulating sand with shell fragments. Few introduced species. Long unburnt. Some grazing from Kangaroos but overall effect is low.
Small plain surrounded by dunes.  Contour bank to the north, immediately adjacent to and just off the plot. High impact of introduced plant species- Carrichtera annua high cover.

Atriplex vesicaria Chenopod shrubland with some emergent Maireana sedifolia. Site is in very slight depression about 5 hectares in size. Surrounded by Maireana sedifolia. Some limestone gravel and boulders. Limestone starts at about 20cm below the surface. Long unburnt. Grazing effect low- no sheep but old rabbit warrens within the site. No introduced plant species noted. Site is flat. Some recent rain- active vegetation growth.

Acacia papyrocarpa low open woodland with a mid-layer dominated by Maireana sedifolia and Senna artemisioides subsp. petiolaris. Mixed forb and tussock grass ground layer dominated by Craspedia sp., Enneapogon sp. (multiple) Sandy soil with lots of Cryptogam. Long unburnt. No introduced plant species noted. Slope of 1 degree to the south east. Homogeneity- extends 200m in all directions. Recent rain- Fruiting and flowering in ground layer and the Acacia papyrocarpa.
Swale between dunes. Moderate impact of introduced plant species- Carrichtera annua moderate cover.
Minimal impact of introduced plant species- Medicago minima, Carrichtera annua, Sisymbrium sp. present.
Eucalyptus socialis, E. dumosa and Callitris verrucosa Mallee low woodland with mid layer of Acacia colletioides and Beyaria opaca and a ground layer of Triodia scariosa on a dune crest.
Casuarina pauper and Alectryon oleifolius subsp. canescens woodland with mid-stratum of  Maireana sedifolia and scattered Eremophila sturtii. Ground stratum is mostly bare.

Plain within sand plain with a gentle slope to the north east. Long unburnt- no evidence of fire in site or surrounding Mallee. Introduced plant species effect is high- Salvia herb is dominant through ground layer but much more native species than similar site on Tarawi (NSAMDD0010). Grazing effect is low at present- scratching at the bottom of shrubs from kangaroos. Would have been heavily impacted in the past- close to an old dam. Possibly cleared. Lots of calcareous gravel through the site.

Clay soil on floodplain adjacent to the river. Little evidence of grazing apart from some rabbit pellets. Ground layer dominated by introduced species. No evidence of recent fire. Site is homogeneous. Conditions dry at time of visit. Some tree stumps present indicating past logging.

Steep site on hill slope- up to 30 degrees at the south east and north east corners but average is 20 degrees and facing to the north east at 40 degrees. Grazing effect is low- mainly from kangaroos. Fire- no evidence of scaring on the trees. Recent fire close by. Site probably cleared in the past- some very old cut stumps. Introduced species effect is moderate- high number of species most notably Chrysanthemoides monilifera and Olea europaea subsp. europaea but overall cover low. Olives have been poisoned but are resprouting. Homogeneity- site is contained. Drops into the valley at the south east and north east corner of the plot. Track runs just past the south west corner of the plot.
Plain. Site is flat. Grazing effect moderate- some rabbits as well as goats. Weed impact low- possibly Brassica sp and Erodium sp. Long unburnt- no scarring on trees. No surface strew or outcrop.

On heavy clay floodplain.  No evidence of fire or grazing. Ground layer dominated by introduced species. Conditions dry. Site is homogeneous apart from small track through northern part of site. Trees are regrowing after previous logging.

On a sand dune with slope generally to south and north. No evidence of fire, some signs of rabbits, no weeds. Site is not homogeneous - northern side (about 20% of site) runs into  swale of Maireana in a pan. Site is a Callitris rehabilitation site. Site has two photo points. One in centre (photos) and one near northeast corner (photo points and laser scan). Minimal impact of introduced plant species- Schismus barbatus and Carrichtera annua present.

Eucalyptus dumosa Mallee low woodland with Eucalyptus gracilis and Eucalyptus socialis. Mixed species sparse mid stratum. Ground stratum is dominated by Triodia scariosa. Adjacent to David Keith site. ( Centre for Ecosystem Science UNSW)
Minimal impact of introduced plant species.

Plot is in a large drainage depression / swamp. Site gently undulating but more or less flat. Grazing effect is high- kangaroos, goats with cattle scats and tracks also noted. Long unburnt- no scarring on trees and very little ground cover to carry a fire. Homogeneity- plot is on the northern edge of the E. largiflorens community. Opens up into a grassland to the north. Continues 1km to the south from the plot. Minimal surface strew- some leaf litter. Introduced plant effect is low- some Brassica sp. under the trees and Medicago minima through the site.

Plain. Flat with a 0.5 degree  to the south. Long unburnt- no scarring on trees and mid layer thick. Introduced plant effect is low- none noted. Grazing effect low- minimal feed. Kangaroo pads but also possibly deer ( sited near plot) and goats. Very fine sandy gravel at surface.

Very shallow drainage depression- more Casuarina pauper on surrounding low ridges. Lots of cryptogam crust. Homogeneity- community is confined to the plot. To the north west grades into more dense Acacia aneura with very little understory. To the east community continues another 50m and to the north and south borders it borders on a more open Eremophila longifolia community.  Fire- very long unburnt. No scarring on trees and very little dead shrubs. Grazing effect is low- some cattle pads but quite old. Introduced plant effect is moderate- Medicago minima dominant in ground stratum but cover low at present.

Plain. To the north of the site is dune with Alectryon and Casuarina pauper. Grazing effect is severe- rabbits mainly ( 2 large warrens in the site) but also goats and kangaroos. Fire-has had a hot fire recently. previous to that, 10 years. Lots of coarse woody debris that would likely have been Alectryon oleifolius but none present in site now. Calcareous sandstone concretions- formed in root tunnels after fire. Mostly gravels with some larger pebbles. Homogeneity- community continues 60m to the west, north and east is track and then dune slope. Introduced plant effect is severe- ground layer dominated by Medicago minima with Marrubium vulgare also present. Community is transitional- likely to have been Alectryon woodland in the past but no sign of Alectryon regenerating.

Sand plain. To the south of the site is low range of hills but site is flat. To the north of the site is a deep erosion gully to 1m deep. Introduced plant effect low- some Medicago but cover low. Long unburnt- no burn marks or dead shrubs. Some old fallen timber.  Minimal surface strew. Grazing effect is moderate- kangaroos and rabbits. Homogeneity- continues 100m on other side of drainage channel on northern edge. To south opens up into Chenopod shrubland. Community continues 30m further to the east and west.

Drainage depression- plot is on edge of larger swamp which borders site on north west corner. Some gentle undulation through the site.  Grazing effect is low but evidence of goats- pads through the site. Very long unburnt- no scarring on any of the trees. Introduced plant effect is low- lots of Medicago seed and possibly Salvia verbenacea but currently low cover due to lack of rain. Minimal surface strew. Some scattered calcareous coarse fragments particularly towards south eastern corner of the site, minimal cover. Homogeneity- community is confined to the site. To the south borders a Dodonaea viscosa shrubland, north is lake bed/ swamp, north east and south west community continues 50m beyond plot.

Plot is on a plain. Lots of Cryptogam crust. Grazing effect is low at present- bulldozer has been through the site ripping 1 or 2 rabbit warrens. Very long unburnt- at least 10 to 15 years. Introduced plant effect is low- but difficult to tell as forbs are only beginning to shoot. Some Sisymbrium but cover low. No Carrichtera annua noted. Slope- site has a 1 degree slope to the north west but more or less flat though sloping slightly at the corners of the site.

Comment from 30/10/2014  Sandplain.  Homogeneous site, community extends >300m beyond site, apart from road to the south. Some disturbance - old track through site, metal waste, weed Carrichtera annua common. No evidence of feral animals or fire.
Comment from 12/09/2018 -  Site was previously set aside as a woodland reserve for farmers to collect wood and use as a dumping ground up until 1960’s. Hasn’t been burnt since then. Grazing minimal- kangaroos. Introduced species impact minimal- Carrichtera annua throughout site. Site is flat with no outcrop. Limestone underneath. Homogeneity- Community extends about 2km south, 1kmwest and north and 300m east. Site located 100m in from main road plus an old track to SW corner. Site located at Clements Gap Conservation Park. 920m North West of old Clements Gap school house. North east of Port Broughton, SA

Some rabbit impact. Site is homogeneous >200m with railway to north. Minimal grazing apart from low numbers of sheep and macropods. No evidence of fire. Few weeds apart from scattered Carrichtera annua.

Maireana sedifolia chenopod shrubland. Homogeneous >300m. No evidence of fire. Ungrazed for >10years. Macropod grazing evident. Surface dominated by cryptogam. No rain for approximately nine months. Inotrduced species effect is low- Carrichtera annua, Carthamus lanatus, Medicago minima, Sisymbrium erysimoides present.

Ground is bare. Evidence of old rabbit damage. Evidence of recent macropod and emu activity. No grazing for >10 years. Homogeneous >300m. Fence to south and west. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.

Tall shrubland of Allocasuarina verticillata and Eucalyptus odorata on low hills with numerous gullies. Unburnt since 1960s (Lyn Pedler pers comm, the owner). Evidence of rabbits on site. Ground layer weeds common e.g. grasses, salvia. Not grazed. Remnant vegetation, fenced from grazing. Relatively homogeneous >70m. Site of SA Govt Biological Monitoring photopoint.

Mt Billy Conservation Park, 10kms north of Victor Harbour. Eucalyptus leucoxylon woodland on east facing hill slope. No evidence of fire or feral grazing. Substrate dominated by litter and cryptogam. Tree stumps present indicate some past logging but no recent activity. Site is homogeneous, extends  >200m north, south and west. Road to the east. Eucalyptus fasciculosa is more prominent off the site to the west. Old, used track runs through western side of plot. Fallen timber, logs, woody debris common. Moderate impact of introduced species- Vulpia sp. moderate cover.

Plain- slightly elevated  from the main Murray river floodplain. Slightly undulating site- mounds around Maireana and Enchylaena but flat overall. Very long unburnt. Grazing effect is moderate, mainly kangaroos- tracks and scats through the site. Introduced plant effect is high- ground stratum dominated by Carrichtera annua with other introduced species also present. Minimal surface strew- likely Calcareous deeper down. Lots of cryptogam crust. Homogeneity- 75m to the closet road. 100m in all directions is the same community.

Plot is on gentle slope rising up from the  main river flood plain. 3 degree slope to the south east. Introduced plant effect is high- Carrichtera annua and Medicago sp. dominate the ground layer. Long unburnt- Some dead trees just outside the plot but difficult to tell whether from fire or drought due to age. Homogeneity- plot is homogenous. 80m from the centre to the north east is a drainage channel (manmade) from  the road. Main road is just to the north of that. Grazing effect is moderate, kangaroos- pads through the site. Minimal surface strew and no outcrop. Lots of Cryptogam crust and lots of leaf litter- dead Carrichtera annua and other annual forbs.

Dune crest- takes in slope on either side. Introduced plant effect is minimal. Majority of the site is long unburnt- fire 1 year previous has just trickled into the north east corner of the plot. South of the plot has also been burnt but not within the site. Grazing effect is minimal- some evidence of kangaroos. Slope- 10 degree slope to the south but also to the north- dune crest is through the middle of the site. Minimal surface strew but lichen crust that looks like limestone.

Swale in low dunefield. Very gentle slope to the north. Northern edge is just on the edge of dune slope. Fire- south east corner was burnt in January 2014. Rest of the site is long unburnt. Fire has come in 30m at the south east corner. Some scattered surface strew- limestone but low cover. Introduced plant effect is minimal- none noted. Homogeneity- community is contained to the plot at the moment due to effect of fire. Some Eucalyptus gracilis close to the road have been cut for timber but have long regenerated.

Steep, Mountainous site. Long unburnt- some old scarring on trunks. Fire close by more recently ( over ridge top) Introduced plant effect is moderate- includes Senecio pterophorus, Genista monspessulana and Briza maxima. Rubus sp. also- more dense in south eastern corner in gully. 45-35 degree slope- varies somewhat through the site. Some boulders and outcrop- check soil sheet for lithology. Grazing effect- some from goats and deer. Tracks and scats within the site.

Gently undulating plot with sand ridges to 60cms high. Grazing effect is moderate- kangaroos, rabbits and goats. Rabbits seen in the site with some large warrens. Site has been bait furrowed in the past. Introduced plant effect is moderate- Medicago minima common in the ground stratum  but cover low as still at dicot leaf stage. Carrichtera annua and Salvia verbenaca also present. Fire- long unburnt. Some dead Callitris but likely dead from other causes. No scarring on live trees. Some Callitris have been cut for timber in the past and have re-spouted.

Plot is in a swale. Majority of the site is flat but rises 2-3 degrees on the northern edge where the dune begins  Grazing effect is minimal- some distance from nearest water point. Introduced plant effect is minimal- none noted. Fire- plot was burnt in December 2013. Regenerating so plot is more open than it would have been in the past.  Minimal Triodia returning but other tussock grasses dominating. Homogeneity- community is confined to the plot. Does continue east and west along the swale but northern and southern edges are at the base of a dune with corresponding change in vegetation.

Swale but dune only on southern edge. To the north continues as a sandplain for quite some way. Fire- has been burnt twice. Most recently in December 2013 and approximately 5 years prior to that. Differing age classes of Eucalyptus within the site. Introduced plant effect is minimal- none noted. Grazing effect is low- kangaroos. Echidna diggings and scats also noted. Minimal surface strew- some calcareous rocks dug up by animals. Homogeneity difficult to ascertain due to different fire ages within the site.

Lake bed surrounded by Mallee dominated sand dunes. Closest Mallee are 5m from the north west corner. Homogeneous plot extends >70m but scalded area in north west corner where water runs in from the main bed of the lake to the north. No signs of fire. No weeds. No Grazing impact was evident. Just to the south of the plot is an old fence line. Roadway at closest is 20m from the western edge of the site. No slope.

Swale among dune. Litter is significant component of substrate, with Cryptogam and Bare ground. Gentle slope to the west but site generally flat. Long Unburnt. Grazing minimal- macropods using hummocks to lie in. Plot is homogenous >70m with10% on southern side touches on edge of sand dune but doesn’t really affect composition. Community is constricted to the swale- doesn’t extend much beyond the plot. Complex mix of several Eucalyptus sp. (Mallee"s) so basal wedge measures were all assigned to Eucalyptus socialis subsp. socialis. Basal wedge count for Southwest corner was missed.

Fire- long unburnt. No scarring on E. largiflorens and E. Camaldulensis. Fire history may be available from ALT. Minimal surface strew.

Spring creek delta. Plot on clay loam alluvial plain. Old disused/ overgrown track cuts through south east corner of quadrat. Minimal impact of introduced plant species-  Sonchus oleraceus present.

Stony gibber plain with occasional crab-holes- some deep gilgais with Acacia tetragonophylla and Acacia salicina, Santalum lanceolatum. Very slight slope ( ½ degree) to the north north west. Browse on Santalum from cattle. Browse on Sclerolaena by donkeys ( one seen at camp). No obvious cattle browse on grasses. Site located 400m north of fence line. Minimal impact of introduced plant species- Malvastrum americanum var. americanum present.
Swale in longitudinal dunefield. Lots of dead litter and bare ground. Track close to south west corner. Plot running north west to south east.
Large Swale, plot aligned North/ South. Grazing effect minimal. No introduced plant species noted.

No evidence of fire. Evidence of browsing / grazing by goats and rabbits.  Site is homogeneous <70m with tracks immediately west and north of plot. Low impact of introduced plant species- Brassica fruticulosa low cover.

Grazing is evident - rabbits common (active warrens present), Macropods and goats. The site appears long unburnt, evidence is no scorch marks on the single Hakea tree present.  Evidence of past logging, with presence of stumps of small trees / large shrubs. Moderate impact of introduced plant species- Echium plantagineum moderate cover, Medicago minima also present.

Eucalyptus populnea open woodland with sparse shrub layer. Bare ground and cryptogam prominent. Echium plantagineum common. Rabbit warrens present, have been ripped. Some evidence of rabbit digging still present. No evidence of recent fire. Site homogenous >100m.

Rabbit warrens common but not active. Some evidence on site of old fire scars, nothing recent. Flogged. Evidence of more recent fire close to but not on the site. Homogenous to 80m. High impact of introduced plant species- Carrichterea annua high cover.

Eucalyptus populnea woodland in terminal drainage depression. Homogeneous (<80m), surrounded by sand ridges. Small dam in depression immediately to south of site, in same community. Heavy grazing by Macropods. No evidence of fire. Weeds common e.g. Marrubium vulgare, Oxalis sp. and Salvia verbenacea. Evidence of past logging.

Plot is on a plain at the base of a series of low rises. Cobbles with some gravels to 20cm- minimal bare ground. Self-mulching soil. Lots of melon hole gilgai. Introduced species minimal- Cucurbitaceae species possibly introduced but cover very low. Long unburnt but difficult to tell how long. Grazing effect is minimal. Site slopes 2 degrees at 165. Homogeneity-  100m to where track is . 200m in all directions is the same community.
Atriplex vesicaria low sparse chenopod shrubland on limestone.  Gentle slope. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.

Acacia aneura low woodland on rocky hill slope, with sparse mid-layer of Eremophila longifolia and Senna artemisioides subsp. artemisioides. Ground layer bare and rocky with scattered short grasses and forbs. No sign of recent fire, no weeds. Some evidence of minor grazing by goats and Macropods. Mistletoe common on Acacia aneura. Scar on northern edge of plot from scrape for road building. Site is homogenous >80m but with road close to northern edge.

Site is homogenous >80m. No evidence of fire, feral animals, grazing.   Minimal impact of introduced plant species - Medicago minima present. Scattering of limestone strew restricted to southern edge of plot.

Big Toolunka Wetland. Gently sloping site to the north at 3 degrees. Plot sits on alluvial spur with main channel to the south of the plot and an old channel forming a billabong to the north. Some alluvial wash- gravels. Grazing effect is low- kangaroos and pigs. Possibly grazed more heavily in the past.  Long unburnt. Introduced plant effect is low.

Wool nook Bend- River Site. Floodplain- SW corner is 20m from water’s edge but approx. 3m above current water level  Minimal bare ground- lots of leaf drop from E. largiflorens and E.  camaldulensis. Flat site overall but undulating- some points where water would pool. Wet- rain previous day and previous week. Minimal flowering- scattered fruit and flowers on Enchylaena tomentosa and Disphyma crassifolium subsp. clavellatum but not consistent. Fruit and flowers on Chenopodium nitrariaceum.  Grazing effect low- some evidence of pigs. Introduced plant effect is low- some thistles and brassicas but cover low. Long unburnt.  Homogeneity- site is a little patchy with E. camaldulensis more concentrated along river side of plot. Beyond plot community is contained with river forming western edge of the site.

Wool nook Bend- Middle Site. Flat Site between main channel of the river and wetland on the other side. Minimal surface strew- lots of leaf litter with minimal bare ground. Rain in previous day and week. Scattered flowering in forbs but not really consistent. Grazing effect low- some evidence of pigs with diggings around trees. Introduced species- some thistles and Sonchus sp. but cover is low. Long unburnt- no scarring and a dense mid story.

Wool nook Bend- Wetland Site. Site on the edge of wetland/billabong. Very gentle slope towards billabong. Less undulating than previous site ( SAARIV002) Plot only homogenous to 40m- track cuts through western edge of the site. No way to fit with Billabong otherwise- north western corner is on other side of the track. Grazing- lots of evidence of pigs and also kangaroos. Long unburnt- dead Chenopodium and Duma but likely from drought rather than fire. Minimal dead trees or scarring on Eucalyptus. Introduced plant effect is low- some scattered forbs. Rain previous day and week. Some flowering on the Chenopodium.  Minimal surface strew

Site is relatively flat. Flood plain on plain. No obvious surface strew. Some weed species may be present but are not having a significant impact on the site. Site is not homogenous. There are two distinct communities, one with Cyperus gymnocaulos as an understorey dominant, and the other with lignum as a mid-storey dominant. There is a small transition zone between the two communities. There is evidence of fire on the site, more than 10 years old. Grazing effect is moderate, mainly from kangaroos. Lots of kangaroo dung present. Nearest infrastructure is the access track approximately 15m south west of the SW corner.

Moorook- Middle Site. Plot is a floodout on the broad floodplain. No surface strew much leaf litter with dense ground cover of Senecio. Grazing effect is low- possibly pigs and kangaroos but effect low.  Plot is flat- rising 1 degree north east. Some evidence of fire but at least 5 years possibly more since fire. Minimal impact of introduced plant species- Sonchus oleraceus present.

Element is a natural levee. Pattern is a floodplain. No surface strew visible. Lots of leaf litter. Site is gently undulating but there is no discernible slope. The most significant change in site since previous visit may be additional recruitment of Eucalyptus camaldulensis and the increase in height of juveniles (need to compare previous visit). Site has not been burnt since last visit. There is evidence of scarring on one old mature tree, but that is likely to be historic fire impact. Grazing impact is minimal. Kangaroos are present but having little effect. Introduced plant species impact is low, there may be some forbs (check species ID) but these are of low cover extent. Site is in close proximity to Campsite 18 at Moorook, may get foot traffic from campers and other light disturbance. Community is confined to the plot, and is homogenous 75m from the centre. Moorook River Plot. Plot is on the floodplain elevated slightly from the main channel of the Murray River. South west corner of the site is just into the channel of the river. Site has been burnt- dead timber and scarring on the trees but longer than 5 years since fire. Campsite to the east as possible ignition source. Grazing effect is minimal- some kangaroos. No surface strew- lots of leaf litter and dense cover of Senecio in the ground layer. Homogeneity- North east corner borders on the track and the south west corner is in the river. Probably the most homogenous site ( at a site level) of the SAARIV plots ( 0001 to 0009)

Moorook wetland substitute plot. Plot is on a floodplain 100m north of main channel of the Murray River. Introduced plant effect is low. Grazing effect low- some kangaroos.  Some evidence of fire ( similar to site SAARIV0005) but at least 5 years likely more since plot was burnt. Homogeneity- south eastern and western edges of plot are close to a track.

Big Toolunka- Mid Plot. Plot is on a swamp on a low lying island with the main channel of the Murray river to the south and an older channel forming a billabong to the north.  Site is more or less flat with some small rises through the site and the south west corner rising up to the levee of the main channel of the river. Plot is patchy at a site level with bands of Duma florulenta and Eucalyptus largiflorens alternating through the site. Some evidence of pigs. Surface strew minimal- lots of leaf litter. Long unburnt. Introduced plant species minimal- some Sonchus and other forbs but cover is low.

Big Toolunka- River Plot. Plot is the slope of the main river levee on a low lying island with the main channel of the Murray river to the south and an older channel forming a billabong to the north. Plot is patchy is a similar way to SAARIV0007 with bands of Duma florulenta and Eucalyptus largiflorens alternating through the site. Minimal surface strew but quite a lot of Cryptogam crust particularly on the low embankments. Grazing effect is low- some pigs and kangaroos- tracks in lignum. Introduced species effect low- some forbs and grasses, particularly on the main river levee but cover low at present.
Minimal impact of introduced plant species - high number of species at low cover.
Dodonaea viscosa subsp. angustissima on sandy soil. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.

Dodonaea viscosa subsp angustissima /Acacia loderi sparse shrubland with a ground stratum dominated Enneapogon avenaceus with Tetragonia sp. and Portulaca oleracea. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.
Enneapogon avenaceus low open tussock grassland with Carrichtera annua. Moderate impact of introduced plant species; mainly Carrichtera annua.
Acacia loderi sparse shrubland. Drainage depression in north west corner. Moderate impact of introduced plant species- Salvia verbenaca moderate cover.
Plot inside fenced exclosure. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.
Plot adjacent fenced exclosure at site NSABHC0015.  Fire history unknown. Grazed by cattle or sheep. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.

Plot at the base of range of low hills. Gentle slope- 2 degrees- to the west.  Plot is grazed by cattle. Drainage channel runs through at the 70m mark to the north east corner. Substrate is a mix of quartzite gravels and other rocks. Some larger cobbles- mix of granite and sandstone. Plot is not marked. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.

Undulating plot in complex of low rises with general slope to the south 6 degrees but steeper to the north of the site.  Very little bare ground- mostly covered by sandstone / mudstone mixed gravels with some outcrop in the creek through the middle of the site. Homogeneity- plot is homogenous- SW and NW corners are 20m from road ( Site is encircled on 3 sides by the road). Grazing effect is minimal. Surface strew mostly gravels with some outcrops of bedrock. Mudstone or sandstone. A couple of large termite mounds within the site. Homogeneity- site is homogenous. Plot on sandstone ridge. Flat towards the south west corner but slope increasing down to the north east corner where it drops off a small escarpment. Colluvial footslope. 12 degree slope at 180 degrees at its steepest but levels out on northern and southern edges. Surface strew is a mix of Ironstone cobbles and gravels with some boulders. Slope ends 10m from the bottom of the plot where it grades into more open Acacia incurvaneura. 20m from Counts Point road on the southern edge. Long unburnt- no scarring but tree on north edge has been hit by lighting- tree is alive but has burnt branches. Introduced plant species effect minimal. Minimal grazing- only Euros and kangaroos.

Flat plot on Alluvial fan. Lots of Ironstone gravel with patches of bare ground. Long unburnt- very sparse cover. Introduced plant species effect is minimal. Grazing effect is minimal. Alluvial plain on valley flat. Previously an open forest but has been burnt so most of the Acacia incurvaneura trees are dead. Grazing effect is low. Some very old overgrown shot lines? through the site running roughly East North East through the plot and continues over the main track to the west of the site.  One large old pile from bulldozer/grader. Homogeneity- beyond plot difficult to tell due to thickness of veg. Plot is homogenous. 100m from nearest used track.

Flat plot on sandplain. Very little surface strew but some ironstone gravels to small cobbles in a patch in the North East corner. Flat plot on a sandplain. Grazing effect is low- camel tracks through the site. Introduced plant effect is low- Cenchrus ciliaris around the base of the Corymbia hamersleyana. Fire- moderately long unburnt. Triodia is quite old. No scarring on Corymbia. Minimal surface strew. Some coarser sands but not separated as gravel. Flat plot on alluvial fan. Ironstone gravels- some fine but also some larger gravels. Long unburnt- minimal cover to carry a fire. Grazing effect is low- donkeys and camels in surrounding area. Introduced plant species effect is minimal. Community continues 20m beyond the plot in all directions. 30m through to a track south east of the plot.

Flat site on Alluvial Plain on a floodplain. No surface strew- lots of Cryptogam. Plot has been burnt since first sampled- regeneration in tussock grasses and scarring on the tree. Some taller/older tussock grass patches indicating the fire was probably patchy through the site. Grazing effect is low- donkeys and camels in the area. Introduced plant effect is low- some Malvastrum americanum present. Homogeneity- plot sits in broad valley. 700m to the north of the site is the same community. To the west and east 200m. To the south begins to rise rapidly up to a low rise 20m south of the site. 20m from a track on the northern edge.

Flat plot on a sandplain. Sandy- very little gravel and lots of leaf litter. Grazing effect is minimal.  Not burnt in current dry season- older scarring on E. tetrodonta and a dense layer of Sorghum plumosum?  through the ground layer. Recent fire between the south east corner of the plot and the road but not burnt into plot. Introduced species effect is minimal. Homogeneity- community extends 20m beyond plot. Sandy site with a very gentle slope to the east. Minimal surface strew- sandy with lots of leaf litter. Unburnt in current dry season. Gentle slope through the site, plot is on a spur at the base of low hills. 3 degrees slope coming down from the range of hills at the south west corner. Slopes to both the north east and north west. Plain, no slope. Minimal surface strew and no outcrop. Grazing effect is minimal- no grazing at present except for occasional water buffalo.  Plot has been burnt in last 1-2 years.
