Introduced plant species effect is low-  Hypochaeris glabra,  Sonchus oleraceus and Aira cupaniana present but minimal cover. Homogeneity-  south west corner is 10m from track which runs away at angle away from the site. Difficult to tell extent of community beyond plot due to thickness of vegetation.

Flat sandplain of deep yellow sandy soil. Half degree slope to the south. No Formal grazing- Kangaroos present. Introduced species effect is nil? . Long Unburnt- fire to the north of the site. No Surface strew. Homogeneity- South east corner is approximately 10m in from road which is running north easterly away from the south east corner.

Sandplain of deep yellow brown sandy soil. Sloping very gently ( 1-2 degrees) to the south west. ( Relic dune?) Some laterite gravels on the section that rises up to the south west corner. Very long unburnt but canopy noticeably shorter than neighbouring site WAAAVW0001. Not Formally grazed but lots of kangaroo dropping through the site. Introduced plant species effect is minimal ? Homogeneity- to the south of the site there are more Eucalyptus. Track running north to south 30m beyond the western edge of the plot. 75 metres from the centre is homogenous.

A complex Hill slope  of low rises.Drainage lines run through the centre of the plot from north west to south east with the plot sloping up from this on the other side. Plot Goes over the capping at the south west corner in the opposite direction. Main slope of 4 degree to the south east. Substrate is Iron Rich sandstone/laterite. Some shallow outcrop at the south west corner.  Minimal grazing. Tree has been cut in site- firewood? but disturbance minimal otherwise. Sandier through the creek channel as well. Very long unburnt. Introduced species effect is low- some Cape weed and other species but cover is low.  Homogeneity- North west corner is 5m in from access track. Community is confined to the plot- south west corner is a little more open with more rock.

Hill crest on low rise. Mostly gravels with some larger cobbles. Mostly laterite with ironstone.  Complex slope. 3 degree slope to the south but steeper more to the south west corner. Straddles spur of low hill. South west corner just into creek line. North eastern corner is a tongue of more sandy material from further up the slope. Long unburnt- no scarring on trees but some ash under some of the older trees 10+ years. No formal grazing- kangaroos. Introduced species is low. Aira cupaniana and Cape weed but overall cover is low.

Gently sloped sandplain with few laterite medium gravel/ occasional cobbles on shallow yellow brown sandy soil. Grazing effect is moderate- many tracks through the site- kangaroos and other native animals but not formally grazed. Lots of Termite mounds scattered though the site. Mallee fowl spotted just outside of the plot.  Introduced plant effect is low- Hypochaeris glabra,  Pentameris airoides subsp. airoides and Vulpia muralis present but cover minimal. Fire- very long unburnt given the age of Callitris. Minimal dead timber. Homogeneity- 50m from eastern edge to a track and then a Wheatfield on the other side of that. 100m from centre is within the same community.  Corresponds to SWATT Plots: SWA304

Gently sloping sandplain. 2 degree slope to the south east.  Some laterite fine gravel on shallow yellow sandy soil. Mostly course grained sand not differentiated from bare ground. Possibly more recently burnt than site WAAMAL0002 based on size of Callitris. Grazing effect is low- mainly Kangaroos and other macropods. Some ant mounds but less than in WAAMAL0002. Introduced plant effect is low- Hypochaeris glabra present but very low cover. Homogeneity- 50m north of a track. 100m from centre of the site is the same community.
Sloping plot on eastern edge of reservoir. 3 degree slope to the south west. Dominated by introduced species. Plot is bounded by access tracks at the south west and north east corners.

Complex topography. General slope is to the north north east but both south east corner and north west corner just grazed the woodlands on either side of the narrow valley. There is also a substantial drainage line that runs along eastern edge where there is a swampier area. Another drainage line also comes in just south of the north west corner but is much shallower and could possibly be an old track. Old disused “A4” track also runs through the site- less eroded than the track closer to carpark south of the site. Long unburnt- woodlands on either side have not been burnt for a long time, fire in woodlands to the south of the site in 2003? Introduced plant effect is low- some Trifolium repens and possibly Poa pratensis/weedy grasses and Acetosella vulgaris in creek but cover is low. Main grazing effect is from deer, hoof prints and scats in creek line. Site was not formally grazed as other sites (VCAAUA0013 and 14) were. Surface strew is sedimentary (probably sandstone) cobbles ( confined to creek where there has been erosion) No rock outcrop.

Plot is on a very shallow spur that runs north-south through the middle of the plot. Aspect to the north west but also to the north east corner- 2 degree slope. Plot is sitting on basalt but no gravel or outcrop visible. Homogeneity- plot is homogeneous but Poa hiemata more common at south east corner. Community is confined to the plot- to the south is snow gum woodland and north east is fenced enclosure. Not currently grazed but likely heavy in the past. Introduced plant species effect is high likely due to past grazing- Trifolium repens, Acetosella vulgaris, Hypochaeris radicata and other species present . Fire-  Burnt 2003?- snow gums surrounding the plot burnt at this time. Corresponds to LTERN plot: Lankey’s Plain Grassland.

Gently sloping plot on a slight spur with a slope to the north east but also slightly to the south east. Fire- burnt in 2003? Grazing- wombat burrows in south west corner and through the plot. Old corner posts of cattle yards but not currently formally grazed. Introduced plant species effect is low – Trifolium, Hypochaeris and a few other species present. Homogeneity- Vegetation community is consistent through the site- some scattered heath shrubs on the eastern section. Celmisia pugioniformis occurs in denser patches through the site.  Community is confined to plot- north of the plot is boggier community. Western edge is 20-60m from woodland. Closest point to track is 300m up the ridgeline but track may have previously run through valley. Sitting on sandstone-  but minimal surface gravels and no outcrop, a couple of fens scattered through the site.

Gently sloping plain in the broad valley of Cope Creek. No surface strew or outcrop- metamorphic substrate, possibly granite. Long unburnt. Introduced plant species effect is low. Grazing- less grazing by horses as there are more people.  Homogeneity- Plot is homogenous 90m from the centre in all directions. The north east corner is 80m from Cope Saddle access track. Overlaps LTERN  plot established in 1979.

Plot with complex slope predominantly to the north west but also to the south east. Outcrop is granite with some sizeable outcrops through the site to 2m. Minimal surface strew due to dense ground cover. Unburnt but surrounded by burnt areas. Some dead trees in plot but died of other causes rather than fire. Introduced plant species effect is low- Acetosella vulgaris present and possibly some of the grass species. Grazing effect is minimal. Homogeneity- community is confined to plot. Community sits on ridge capping with northern and eastern edge transitioning to a heathland. North west corner is 10m uphill from Cope Saddle access track.

Gently sloping plot with a 1 degree slope to the north west. Fire- possibly burnt in 2003- snow gum woodlands surrounding the plot were likely burnt at this time.  Introduced plant species effect is minimal- probably came in from horses. Horse scats and pad in the site. Minimal surface strew and no outcrop. Plot is sitting over metamorphic substrate. Homogeneity-  plot is 1.2 km east from track to Mt Nelse fire track. Vegetation community is quite extensive but southern edge is close to snow gum woodland but west, north and east extends 30m beyond the plot. Corresponds to LTERN plot: “Cultivation” grassland .

Plot sits on broad, flat plain. Sandy at the surface but clay below the surface. Minimal surface strew- litter- broken twigs etc from goats. Lots of cryptogam crust. Long unburnt- minimal ground cover and shrubs well-spaced to carry fire. Introduced plant species effect is low at present- most grasses and annual are dry. Silene sp. possibly present. Homogeneity- 20m beyond plot is the same community. difficult to tell how far community extends beyond this due to thickness of vegetation. North west corner is 30m in from Burke/Hungerford road which runs slightly south west away from the north west corner.

Linear drainage depression. Plot is broadly flat but has gently undulating ridges. Patchy at a subsite level. Eucalyptus populnea is on raised section, some pan sections that have more bare ground. Sandier sections have more of the Eremophila sturtii and Senna artemisioides subsp. petiolaris. Minimal surface strew. Lots of leaf litter under Eucalyptus populnea but largely bare in pan sections. Plot has not been cleared as at site NSAMUL0004. Introduced plant species effect is low. Grazing effect is low- kangaroos and goats. Long unburnt. Homogeneity- NE corner is 50m from powerline access track. Community is confined to the plot.
Plot is flat in very broad creek channel that flows towards the north west.
Footslope of low hills. Minimal surface strew- some sandstone gravels and pebbles. No rock outcrop. Very gentle slope to the north- drainage line ( old track? outside the plot to the north east.

The Landform element is a hill slope with a pattern of hills. South west corner is on the ridge crest with the rest of the site slope down in northeast direction at 6-7 degrees, levelling off at the northeast corner. There are outcrops present and cobbles and some gravels and boulder. Lithology metamorphosed sandstone. Site was burnt in 2013, most of the Eucalypts are still alive but a majority of the Callitris endlicheri are dead. Regeneration of the Acacia buxifolia and Acacia harpophylla has probably happened since the fire. Heavily impacted by goats and some roos, most of the grasses have been heavily grazed. Introduced plant species impact is low with Heliotropium amplexicaule and Urtica incisa present. Vegetation community is confined to the plot. Site gets more dense in southwest corner with Acacia harpophylla and some Eucalyptus dealbata on ridge line.

Landform element is a plain and pattern plain. No surface strew or lithology. Long unburnt no scarring present. Some selective logging most likely Eucalyptus crebra. Grazing impact of goats and pigs. The plot is homogenous with the vegetation community extending 50m beyond the plot to the road.

The site is flat with a landform element of a plain and pattern plain. Site is very similar to NSABBS0005, and inside the new Australian Wildlife Conservancy predator free enclosure currently under construction May 2018. No surface strew or outcrops present. 150m from fence line of AWC enclosure (inside enclosure). Minimal impact of grazing from pig, goats and roos. Minimal effect of introduced plant species. The vegetation community extends well outside of the plot.

Bed of 12 Mile Creek. Minimal surface strew- some alluvial wash in the creek. Most of the Chenopodium auricomum have been grazed by Kangaroos. 20m from south west corner is old bore and tank so would have been more heavily grazed in the past. Plot is largely flat with deeper channel of the creek flowing eastward. Community is confined to plot- south west corner rise up out of main swampy area. A shallow channel runs north close to the south west corner- deeper main bed of creek is north of that. North east corner just comes up on to sandier ridge in middle of channel which is  sparser.

Flat plot on broad plain. Minimal surface strew. Sandy at surface but hard underneath. Grazing effect is low- Goats and Kangaroos. In semi fenced enclosure but still roos present. Introduced plant effect is currently low- Medicago and other forbs may be present. Cenchrus ciliaris present but cover low at present. Plot hasn’t had whole sale clearing as at site NSAMUL0003. Long unburnt. Community is confined to the plot- extends slightly beyond plot but north eastern corner is 10m from track heading away in a south westerly direction.

Plot sits on broad plain. Plot has been cleared at least 3 times- initially by hand around the 1920’s then with a chain saw post WW2 and then with a bulldozer in the 70s or 80s. Hasn’t been burnt. Minimal impact of introduced plant species. Grazing effect is moderate – goats and roos but minimal feed at time of visit due to lack of rain. Homogeneity- community is confined to the plot. Sits in linear grove. South east corner is 15m from reserve access track.

-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Previously burnt in a control burn (2016/17), but remains unburnt in the most recent fires. There are many more species in the regrowth, which were not collected the first time.
The physical description hasn’t changed.
The site is Eucalyptus pauciflora open woodland, with Eucalyptus viminalis scattered through the site. The mid-story is quite sparse with some regrowth of the Eucalypts and the Red-stemmed shrub, and the ground layer is very diverse with lots of forbs and Poa labillardierei.
The site is wet, there have been decent rains in the past few days so the soil is still damp. The vegetation response is fruiting and flowering. There are fruit on the Eucalyptus pauciflora, and many of the forbs are flowering, Lomandra has fruit and the Poa species have seed heads.
More introduced species recorded on this visit. There is Black thistle scattered throughout the site, as well as a few weedy forbs.
Grazing in the site is low, but evidence of kangaroos throughout the site.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
The landform element is a hill slope with a pattern of mountains. The plot has a slope to the south at 5 degrees even throughout the site. A lot of surface strew visible in the site due to fire burning off the grasses. A lot of basalt gravel and cobbles and some larger boulder possible shale or outcrop. VERY recently burnt, 8 weeks ago Feb 2018. Most of the upper canopy is still alive but most of the younger snow gum have died or have been scorched and are reshooting. The majority of the lower stratum has been burnt with some small patches of grasses unburnt. Minimal grazing impact by pigs and roos. Introduced plant species impact is low, some Scotch thistle is present but other introduced plants may have been burnt out. Community is confined to plot. 30m from Western edge of plot is track to Governors lookout where fire has stopped. Southeast corner is 15m in from the road moving away toward the southwest corner which is 40m away from the road to the south and east.

Aspect 2 degrees to South. Steeper through the middle of site on a river terrace. South east corner is at the high bank of the creek moving further away towards the southwest corner out of the site. Surface strew not apparent but just under the surface sandstone and alluvial wash. Long unburnt, no evidence of fire. Evidence of past logging cut with possibly saw or axe. Grazing mostly Kangaroos, low impact. Minimal introduced species but potentially annual weedy species may occur. Vegetation community confined to the plot.

The landform is a plain with no slope. Surface strew predominately quartz with some flecks of ironstone and sandstone as well. Mostly gravel 1mm to 50mm. Plot is long unburnt. Low impact of grazing by roos and possibly goats.Check IDs/point intercepts for introduced species impact. Homogeneity confined to plot. Site exist in a patchwork of more open chenopods and then smaller groves of Casuarina pauper occurring in pockets throughout plot. Some C. pauper are present outside the plots by the southern edge and more 60-70m away. South east corner is 5m from Noon Flower Track.

Landform element is a stream channel in a floodplain.Eucalyptus camaldulensis woodland in river channel. The plot has an aspect of 1 degree to South in direction of river flow. Oonartar track 50-60m from south west corner. Plot is long unburnt, with no evidence of previous fire. Grazing pressure is low, mostly by roos and emus, potentially goats. Introduced species impact is low with some Xanthium spinosum, horehound and Lycium ferocissimum present. Community is confined to plot. Three distinct channels through plot. Deepest is on the eastern side. The Eucalyptus camaldulensis woodland is homogenous throughout the site, extending only a metre or so from the banks.

Plot is on a gently sloping plain, 4 degrees to the west sitting on the broader high plains. No outcrop in site but close by is Gneiss. Some very small patches of fine gravels, also likely to have Gneiss in plot. Introduced plant species effect is minimal, some Trisetum spicatum present and some weedy annual forbs. Un-grazed since cattle removed in 2005 but deer increasing. Very long unburnt. Homogeneity- community is confined to the plot. North east corner is 15m from Bogong High Plains Road. Western edge is grading more into a grassland.  Corresponds to LTERN Plot: Cope hut unburnt grassland.
some very small patches of fine gravels, likely Gneiss.

Alpine peat swamp. Not grazed, (check with Sam Grover- RMIT in terms of grazing effect and fire). Snow gum woodlands that border the site have been burnt but uncertain as to whether it burnt into bog. Introduced plant species effect is minimal. No surface strew but one small outcrop/large boulder of granite. Plot is homogenous but community is confined to the plot. 120m north ( upslope) of the plot is a walking track while 650m south east is fire track that leads up towards Mt Nelse. Plot is within the catchment of the OzFluz Alpine flux tower.

Plot sits in the saddle of Mt Jim. 3 degree slope to the east, consistent through the site. No strew due to dense ground cover. Some outcrop and larger rocks of Basalt. Most of the rock is covered by Cryptogam with no other cryptogam visible in site. Some horse scats in the site which may explain weeds in site. Long unburnt. Homogeneity- extensive grassland- eastern edge of the site dips down into some slightly more boggy areas. Community extends 80m in all directions. Plot sits among network of hiking trails. Closest point is the north east corner which is 50m from track.

Steep sloped plot – 10+ degree slope to the north east to creek. Large granite outcrops which are covered in Cryptogam ( will be Cryptogam in Point intercept), scattered through site. No real surface strew due to ground cover. Plot was burnt in 2003- lots of dead but regenerating Snow gum- have regenerated beyond half way up to previous height. Grazing effect is low- no cattle but deer are present in area. Introduced plant effect is low- some annuals at south west corner close to track . Homogeneity- community is confined to plot- swamp in north east corner. 5ms to infrastructure- Wallace Hutt track.

Gently sloping saddle coming down between low rises. 2 degree slope to the north west but increasing slightly at the north west corner. Overlooking falls creek ski fields. Cattle removed in 2005, Sambar deer increasingly present. 100m from Maisie’s control plot and another 100m to “fenced” plot. Introduced species effect is low- Acaena and possibly grasses. Fire- Burnt in 2003. Homogeneity- community is confined to plot. North east corner is around 25m from Bogong high plains road. Corresponds to LTERN plot: Rocky Valley Burnt Grassland

Gently sloping plot with a 2 degree slope to the east. Burnt 2003? Homogeneity- vegetation community extends 20m in all directions from the centre further to the north, south and east but north west corner is 15m. from old horse yards and more wooded area. Plot borders on old Kelly lane track ( long disused) on eastern edge. Grazing effect is currently low- wombats present ( though no burrows close to plot) deer also present. One lone Eucalypt shrub in the plot.

Plot sits in broad swale rising very gently to the south east. Leaf litter under the trees but bulk of bare ground is made up of cryptogam crust. Grazing pressure less than previous site ( NSACOP0002)- kangaroos, goats, rabbits and echidnas. Long unburnt- no scarring on trees- older trees have fallen. Coarse woody debris where trees have fallen. ( check with NPWS if has been chained in past). Introduced plant species effect is low at time of visit- very dry. Homogeneity- community is confined to plot SE corner gets into more sandy Triodia sp. community.

Plot sits on low rise, 10-20cms above surrounding landscape. Ironstone cobbles and gravels with some scattered (iron rich) sandstone Grazing effect is moderate- kangaroos and goats but still heads on grasses and Atriplex stipitata are still intact. Introduced plant effect is low at present as forbs have dried out. Medicago minima, Salvia verbenaca and Centaurea melitensis present but cover low. Most cover still extant is native. Long unburnt- no cover to carry fire. Homogeneity- community is confined to plot. 200m back to old Glen lea access track ( rarely used)

Plot is on low rocky rise 20m up from surrounding plains. 5 degree slope to the north east- flatter on western edge but getting steeper to the north east. Embedded boulders/outcrop and lots of cobbles and gravels of sandstone possibly metamorphosed. Flecks of ironstone and quartz through the site. Minimal introduced plant species noted at visit. Grazing effect is from low to moderate kangaroos- no goats noted but likely present. Long unburnt- very sparse ground cover. Homogeneity- community extends 40m west and north. Eastern edge is 20m to road.

Plot sits in the channel of Cannina Creek. Slightly deeper channel runs east to west along southern boundary. Site is mostly flat with a 1 degree slope to the east with some undulations due to deposited material. Minimal surface strew. Grazing effect is severe- Kangaroos and cattle- all of the Chenopodium have had leaves eaten away. Long unburnt. Introduced plant species effect is low at present but difficult to tell due to dryness and grazing. Homogeneity- Vegetation community is confined to the plot- either side of the plot is more open plains. North east corner is 20m in from jump up loops track moving away from the track into the plot.

Plot on the slope of low granite hill. Some lichen on patches of outcrop ( called cryptogam in Point intercept data). Large sheets of Granite through much of the site.  8 degree slope to the north. Fairly consistent slope but some raised granite patches. Grazing effect is low- mainly from Kangaroo and Euros. Recruitment  in Mulga since rabbits numbers reduced. Very long unburnt. Small scale cutting of mulga but very old- check with Bush Heritage Australia for more detailed history. Introduced plant effect is low- Carrichtera annua, Echium plantagineum and Medicago minima present but cover low.  Homogeneity- community is confined to plot- Northern edge of plot is a granite outcrop. Community extends to the south over hill. Northern edge is 15m from turn around from Gnamma hole track ( very narrow). Main track 1km to the west.

Plot sits on broad flat plain. 1 degree slope to the south east. Very long unburnt- minimal grass cover to carry fire. Introduced plant effect is minimal at present- possibly Carrichtera annua ( not sited) and Medicago ( probably minima) is present. Flecks of gravel but minimal surface strew. Homogeneity- community confined to plot. South east corner opens out into chenopod shrubland. Community extends in valley to west of the site. North of the plot is more open but Acacia carneorum present  in smaller groves.

Plot sits in a broad valley/ Drainage depression between ranges. To the west is low rise.  Gentle slope to the south 2 degrees. Creek through the site- quite deep in places ( 2-3m deep in water holes) Rest of the site is floodplain of creek- no real change in vegetation along the creek. Some sandstone cobbles in the creek channel. Long unburnt- some trees show evidence of fire but no scarring on trunks. Grazing is only from Kangaroos. Younger Eucalyptus on east of the site and west outside of the site have leaf die off- probably because of the dry.  Most of the older Eucalypts seem ok. Homogeneity- community is confined to the plot. Park access track running north to south 10m west of the plot.

Lower bottom slope of the range. 3 degree slope but 5-6 degrees at SW corner. NW aspect. Mostly cobbles of metamorphosed sandstone origin. Some pockets of very low outcrop as well. Burnt in 2013 but not as severe as further up ridge- not as much crown burn. Pig trap in the middle of the plot. Old concrete block ( amenity block from old campground?) and old disused track just creeps in on western edge. Introduced plant effect- check with Herbarium Ids. Homogeneity- community is confined to plot- SW corner rises up onto slope of ridge with ironbarks. Northern edge is close to the road and western edge is turn around area for walking trail. 10m from northern edge to road. 10m from western edge to turnaround area.

Site is flat. No surface strew or lithology apparent, mostly quite sandy. A fair amount of dead course wood debris. Long unburnt. Grazing impact minimal, mostly kangaroos and goats. Community extends 50m from plot in all directions. Introduced plant impact is low, some Opuntia sp. present and possibly some introduced forbs. Some of the older trees, Eucalyptus crebra have been cut, maybe some selective logging previously.

The plot is inside Australian Wildlife Conservancy enclosure on the Pilliga State Conservation Reserve (fence under construction at time of visit May 2018). The site is flat. In terms of homogeneity, 100m from the centre in all directions is the same community. Nearest infrastructure is the enclosure fence, 100m North of the site. Site is long unburnt, no evidence of scarring. In terms of grazing, there are lots of burrows possibly rabbits or something native Perentie? Introduced plant species minimal impact.

-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
The site is a Eucalyptus pauciflora, Eucalyptus viminalis and Eucalyptus laevopinea woodland, with a mid-story of young Eucalypts. The ground layer is made up of a variety of grasses, forbs and weedy  species including Geranium sp., Poa labillardierei, Hydrocotyle, Swainsona, White paper daisy and Long leaved lomandra. 
The sites land form and element hasn’t changed since the previous visit, still a hill slope and the element mountains. There is a volcanic plug to the South west of the site. There is a drainage line throughout the northern edge of the site and curves over towards the south west corner. 
The site was burnt in 2019 in a wildfire, so it has burnt since our previous visit. Some of the trees have been killed off completely, however many are shooting epicormic growth. A large part of the canopy is intact suggesting the fire was a low intensity. 
In terms of climate and response, there was a good summer rain so the site is very green. Recent rain in the past few days. The vegetation response is fruiting and flowering, including Erodium and paper daisies. The eucalypts are not fruiting or flowering. The grasses have seed heads. Less grass cover compared to the previous visit, with more forbs visible. Increased weedy species since last visit.

-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Site is long unburnt ~50years, no evidence of scarring on any of the Eucalyptus species. The site is only marked at the South West corner and centre point. Grazing impact is low, evidence of pigs and kangaroos through site. Distance from infrastructure, North East corner is 20m down the slope from the road and running away from the plot. Homogeneity is confined to plot. Complicated slope and aspect. Slopes down from the road into a slight ditch at the North West corner, but also curving over the slope at the South East corner and the North East corner is sloping down into a ditch. No discernible slope to site.

Extensive granite sheets through site some with cryptogam and some large boulders and cobbles of granite. Evidence of historic mining. Long unburnt with evidence of previous fire i.e. dead burnt timber. Community is confined to plot. North East corner close to a creek with ferns and still has water running through it. There is a shallow drainage line that runs North West through the site. Introduced plant species minimal. Evidence of grazing minimal, pigs and kangaroos present. Distance to infrastructure North east is 20m in from the Blatherarm campground.

Neofabricia myrtifolia and Jacksonia thesioides mixed heathland on a dune slope. No surface strew or lithology. Deep sand. Landform element is a dune slope in the pattern of an irregular dune field. The dunes are almost parabolic at times but generally not too linear. Dunes are very well vegetated. Slope is 10 degrees to the south. Site is long unburnt, a few scattered dead shrub but no real evidence of past fire. Minimal grazing impact. Minimal impact of introduced plant species. Homogeneity is 80m from centre. The road is >30m from south west corner which mark the edge of the heathland.

Landform element is a swamp with a pattern of alluvial plain. Site is predominately flat with a few drainage lines and water holes through it. Soil is very clayey with no surface strew or lithology. Evidence of previous fire (scaring on bottoms of Melaleuca trunks), likely 2-3 years ago. A lot of regeneration, but not in this dry season. No evidence of grazing or grazing animals. Homogeneity- Site sits on an extensive wood/shrubland of Melaleuca viridiflora although some areas have been burnt more recently than others.

Site is in a swale. NE corner rises up into a dune but does not intersect any other transects. There is a creek channel that runs roughly south easterly through the site. The slope is a 2 degrees in a south easterly direction. Some scattered sandstone gravel is present through the middle of the plot. Along the channel is a very thin banned of riparian vegetation. Two isolated pockets of Eucalypts one is the south eastern corner and along the eastern boundary with a more extensive patch occurring just past the south west corner.The community is confined to the plot.

Slope and aspect- 2 degree slope to south west. Homogeneity- community extends 75m from centre of plot. Distance to infrastructure- SE corner 40m in from access track to Crystal Vale station. Fire- scarring on trees. Possibly burnt early last dry season. Introduced species effect- high, dominated by Hyptis suaveolens. Grazing- presently low. Cattle on property but doesn’t appear to be many through site. No surface strew or outcrop. Some low termite mounds to maximum of 1m.

Landform element plain and pattern is rises. Aspect is a gentle 2 degree slope to the north. Site is very sandy with no apparent surface strew or outcrop. Homogeneity, 75m from centre is same community. Evidence of past fire, likely 1-2 years ago. Low impact of grazing although there is a cattle pad running through the north eastern corner. Introduced plants impact is low with some small patches of Mesosphaerum suaveolens in south west and north east corners. Closet point of infrastructure is Crystal Vale Station access track 30m from southeast corner.

Landform element is plain and pattern is rises. Site is flat. There’s no outcrop but there is some ironstone surface strew. Site has been burnt within the last 5 years. Effect of introduced plants is low, with some patches of Mesosphaerum suaveolens particularly in the south west corner . Grazing impact is low, cattle are present on property. Homogeneity- community is confined to the plot. North east corner is 25m in from Holroyd River Station access track.

Landform element is a plain and pattern is rises. Site has been burnt recently but not this dry season, most likely previous year. Grazing impact is minimal, some cattle scats through the site. Introduced weed impact is minimal some Mesosphaerum suaveolens present. Site is flat. South west corner just drops off cliff into the creek. North east corner is ~20m in from a road.

Site is located on Yarraden Station, 40km south south west from Coen. Landform element pattern. Slight drainage depression. No slope. gentle undulation but more or less flat. No surface strew or outcrop. Slight scarring on eucalypts and xanthorrhoea but long unburnt. Grazing and introduced effect low. Homogeneity- community extends approximately 1km south and 500m east. Holroyd road is closest infrastructure at 100m along northern edge of plot.
Musgrave, 61.9km North West

Complex slope, there is a low rocky ridge that runs through the middle of site in a westerly direction. Site slopes by 3 degrees in all directions from the centre of the plot. Surface strew is granite as cobbles. Site is long unburnt. Some scarring on tree, but a lot of leaf litter and a diverse forb layer. Grazing effect is low, cattle pads run through eastern edge of the site. Introduced plant impact is low with some Mesosphaerum suaveolens and Stylosanthes scabra present . Homogeneity is confined to the plot. North west corner is 5m in from the main development road.

Landform-plain, part of larger plain. Fire-long unburnt, perhaps several years. Introduced- effect low. Some Themeda quadrivalvis along western edge. Some Stylosanthes sp. Grazing- minimal. Homogeneity- confined to plot but continues 1km east and 300m south. There is an access track, Telegraph Road, 50m from the western edge, where the Themeda is thickest. The Peninsula Developmental Road is located 700m north east of the plot and the Piccaninny homestead is 4.5km south of site. Site located 100km north North West of Coen.

Flat Alluvial plain. Lots of algal crust from where water has sat following wet season. Scattered ironstone gravels. Plot was burnt in previous dry season- minimal ground cover or recruit in Corymbias and scarring up trunks. Minimal grazing, No stock. Extensive termite mounds- some overgrown. Introduced plant effect is low, some Stylosanthes scabra, Mesosphaerum suaveolens and Themeda quadrivalvis. Homogeneity extensive community extends over track. South west corner is 30m in from fence line access track. 100m in all directions is the same community.

Slope and aspect is flat. Site sits in drainage depression and alluvial plain. Very long unburnt. No formal grazing but some scrub bulls were seen. Possibly feral pigs. Homogeneity- community extends 200m north, east and south from centre of plot. Community extends to track, which is 20m from western edge of plot but extends a further 500m west beyond the track. No surface strew or lithology. Site is 30km south west from Piccaninny Plains homestead.

Plot sites on extensive plain/remnant plateau. Not burnt in previous dry season. Introduced plant effect is low- Stylosanthes scabra,  Grazing effect is minimal- grazed in the past. Pigs present. Minimal surface strew. Homogeneity- plot sits in broad  Eucalyptus tetrodonta and Corymbia nesophila woodland. 70m in all directions is the same community.  20m from south west corner is Bertihaugh station access track.

Site situated on plain. Grazing- impact low. Evidence of goats, pigs and horses but minimal impact. Homogeneity- community extends 100m from the eastern and southern edge of plot but is contained on the western and northern edge. Lithology- low ironstone outcrop through site as well as ironstone surface gravel. Infrastructure- Track 15m from north east corner of plot with Bertiehaugh station 4.6km North West of site.

Landform element is a plain and pattern is a plain. Grazing impact is high, mostly pigs (diggings) and some evidence of cattle and wallabies. Surface and lithology non present. In terms of homogeneity the community is extensive, but the South West corner is 20m from the road to the Coolabah out station and the other side of the road on the Western edge is a denser thicket of another community. 20m beyond the plot is the same community.

Landform plain, gentle slope to NE 1 degree. Surface strew and lithology- none. Same as outcrop. Introduced species and grazing- minimal. Homogeneity- extends 20m beyond plot. Closest infrastructure- Bamaga road runs 20m along eastern edge of plot. Several years since last burn.

Slope is 3 degrees  down to the Northern end of site. Ironstone and sandstone surface strew 5-30mm diameter. Surface strew consistent across site. Evidence of past fire. 1-3 years ago. Low introduced plant impact. Grazing impact low, wild pigs and wallabies present. North of the site is a creek 30-40m from North East corner (fire goes up to creek). 50m from South West corner upper gets dense. Site is homogenous. Site is 72.1km South Bamaga and 71.4km North of Bertie Haugh Station. Site is located in Jardine River National Park.

Landform element and pattern. Plain and plain. Slight 2 degree slope to the south. Surface strew- Metamorphic gravel. No outcrop. Homogeneity- Community extends 20m beyond the plot in all directions. Site is located 19.4km North West of New Mapoon and 3.4km West South West from Thursday Island. White sandy soils. No surface strew or lithology apparent. Evidence of past fire 10-15years ago. Low recruitment of Melaleuca spp. in site. Minimal impact of grazing. Minimal introduced species impact. Closest infrastructure is an unnamed track 30m South of the South West corner. Site is homogenous. Community is continues 100m East and West of the site, 60m North and 20m South, where it transitions into denser Melaleuca spp. woodlands.

Site is on a flat plain with no discerning slope. Located 9.4km west, south west from Bamaga and 11.4km south west of New Mapoon. Closest infrastructure is a track 100m north west corner. Homogeneity- Community extends 100m to the north and east where it hits a floodplain, 500m south where the community changes along a river system and 1km west until it hits an airfield.  Grazing- low impact, cattle. Introduced species- minimal, dodder, Hyptis. Last fire 1-2 years. Hot fire as tops trees and branches killed off.  No surface strew.

Landform- swamp on sandplain. Element is swamp in drainage depression. Slope and aspect- flat, no discernible slope. Burnt regularly- last dry season, due to lack of midstory. Plot straddles the top of a ridge forming a small plateau. Complex slope with a slope down on northern side at a 5 degree slope to but also at south western and eastern sides. Large granite outcrop- 3-4m high in the middle of site. Most of the outcrop is covered by Lichen ( called crypto in PI) No strew apparent due to dense ground cover. Trisetum spicatum is common through the site at low cover. Hypochaeris radicata, Cerastium vulgare, Taraxacum sp. and Acetosella vulgaris also present. Gently sloping plot with a 1 degree slope to the south. No surface strew due to dense cover but some flat basalt outcrops. Relic dune, 1 degree slope to east. Homogeneity- community confined to plot. Eastern edge borders shallow dip. Narrow access track 50m from SE corner, moving away from plot. Site very long unburnt, some scarring on Melaleuca. Introduced species- minimal. Grazing effect- minimal. No surface strew or outcrop.

The plot is located on the western slopes of Telowie Gorge Range. Nearest infrastructure is the western edge is about 10m in from the Western Boundary Track, but it’s no longer used and there is a fence line there. There is an old fence line that runs about length of transect EW4, but it hasn’t been used for a very long time and there is no discernible difference on either side. Surface strew is mostly cobbles with some boulders and gravel and some small course sandtone outcrops. Substrate is mostly sandstone, with some calcareous sandstone present (present in soil pit). Site was severely burnt in the 2015 Bangor fire, with the exception of the North East corner (it’s in the same community, but it seems the fire didn’t creep into the gully or the other side of the ridge). The rest of the site is regenerating. Grazing impact is low. Unsure if there are goats present, but there are kangaroos and wallabies. Introduced plant species impact is high, mostly Carrichtera annua with some Bromus rubens. Slope is relatively even to the West, it does get steeper to the North East corner where it starts to drop down into the gully to the North. The predominant slope is to the West, 17-18 degree slope steeper up the top. Just North of South West corner is an area that has possibly been cleared previously, that has largely regenerated with Sida petrophila. In terms of homogeneity, community is confined to plot. On the Northern edge it drops down into the gully where is gets thicker and is also gets into thicker scrub on the Eastern boundary up the rocky slopes. The substrate across the site is a mixture of closely cropped moss, lichen and cryptogram.

Landform element is hills slope, pattern hills. Site slope at 13-14 degrees with a Northern aspect. Introduced plant impact is low with Hypochaeris glabra and Cerastium glomeratum. Grazing impact is low, evidence of kangaroo scat. Surface strew is coarse sandstone cobble and outcrop with some pebble quartz. Past fire, 4 years ago. Scarring on Eucalyptus spp. 8m up trees. Understorey regenerating. Nearest infrastructure 30m South of SW corner and Go Cart Track is 40m SW from SW corner.

Landform and pattern, plain on plain. No outcrops. Mostly pebble size surface strew and some cobble in scattered patches through the site. Grazing impact is moderate, cattle grazing on property (evidence of tracks and scats in site). Site is long unburnt. Closest infrastructure is Yappala Rd 30m from North East corner.

Site landform and pattern is a Hill slope in hills. Metamorphic sandstone outcrops through the site and surface strew of cobble ranging 20-200mm, but mostly 50-70mm. Homogeneity- community is confined to the plot. Transitions on the southern edge of the plot as it becomes more sandy. Vegetation community extends along lake edge 100m east and west. Site slightly changes to more an Acacia aneura shrub land to the SW. Site is long unburnt. Nearest infrastructure is 600m NW of Old Stuart Hwy. There is an old unmaintained fence line the runs WNW through the very northern edge of plot.

Landform and pattern is a plain and a sand plain. No surface strew or outcrop apparent. Nearest infrastructure the track to 30m North of North East corner. Rain gauge and pitfall line near NE corner. Introduced plant species is minimal. Grazing impact is minimal, there is evidence of kangaroos in site. Site is homogenous extending 150m to the West, South and East of plot. Stops at track 30 m to the North of NE corner. Site is long unburnt.

Site is not aligned to the grid, with NW corner the most northern point. Slope is an average of 5 degrees, to the south east (135 degrees), flatter near the top and steeper towards the bottom of the site. No surface strew or outcrop, only lots of leaf litter. Grazing impact is low, mainly kangaroos, no grazing by stock. Site is long unburnt, with no anecdotal evidence or scarring on trees. Introduced plants numerous but cover low- Ochna serrulata and and Asparagus plumosus bing the most abundant.  Homogeneity- community is confined to the plot, as vegetation becomes denser at the bottom edge in proximity to the creek. Nearest infrastructure is the access track to the barracks, 15m away. To the north of the site is a droughtnet shelter and infrastructure associated with the super site (litter fall traps). Most trees are tagged and marked at 1.3m for DBH measurement.
