Limited data from first visit Plant voucher and leaf tissue sample Barcodes only collected by TERN Ecosystem Processes team

Flat gibber plain with no rock outcrops. Gibber/ironstone surface strew 2-10mm (buckshot) even across whole plot with siltstone and quartzite. Site is homogenous, although the SW corner does encroach upon a drainage line.

Surface strew, basalt pebble to cobble size. Site is on a bit of a saddle, slope to the NE and SE 2-3degrees. Introduced plant impact is low, Cenchrus ciliaris and Opuntia present. Grazing impact is low, cattle present. Nearest infrastructure is the track 20m East of North East. Site is homogenous, extend 150m South, 100m West, 75m East and 200m North. Site is long unburnt (5 years at least), scarring present on some trees. Evidence of last year’s burn off to the East (outside of plot).

Site is located on Crown Land 4.3 km north west of Dalby that was set aside for a town abattoir that was never built.  Site doesn’t seem to have been previously cleared. There is evidence of the odd tree cutting and fallen debris. Introduced plant species is low, Opuntia stricta is present. Site is long unburnt, no scarring on Eucalyptus populnea. The neighbouring property does put cattle in the reserve sometimes. There is a hot wire along part of the boundary, presumably to keep cattle in. No surface strew or outcrop. Cenozoic sediments. A narrow quad bike track runs NW to SE just inside the NE corner.

Site is flat, the general slope of the landscape is SW towards Condamine River. Some corn husks, cotton and Sorghum has washed into site from neighbouring farmland. Landform element drainage pattern. No surface strew or lithology. This site has been burnt 3 times by the local council to control Lippia sp. Grazing impact is low, some kangaroos present. Introduced species impact moderate, Opuntia tomentosa and O.aurantiaca , Urochloa panicoides and Phyla canescens. Plot is homogenous, community extends 150m North, 100m West, 100m South, 60m East into denser E. populnea with farmland  90m to East.

Surface strew and lithology, none apparent. Site is flat, no slope. Introduced weed impact moderate, Bryophyllum x houghtonii, Sonchus sp., Opuntia spp.. Site is homogenous, community extend 100m East, 70m North. Nearest infrastructure is Jondaryan-Mount Tyson Rd, 60m W from SW corner. Site is long unburnt. There has been selective logging in site, not for some time though.

Landform element is plain, landform pattern is a sandplain. Very sandy minimal surface strew. No outcrop. Gentle 2 degree slope to South. Site is long unburnt. Previous selective logging, currently a lot of fallen logs. Grazing impact is low. Introduced species is low, Cenchrus ciliaris present. Community is confined to plot. The SE corner is 10-15 in from the track. Northern edge 30m in from the track to the north. Grading of the track has created some disturbance, pushing fallen debris towards the site.

Landform element and pattern is a plain within a plain. No slope. No apparent surface strew or outcrop. Site is long unburnt, No evidence of recent fire. Introduced plant species impact is low, Cenchrus ciliaris and Cactaceae sp. present. Grazing impact is low, kangaroo scat present. Site is homogenous and community extends 100m South, 70m East. To the North and West community transitions to a more open community with less A. excelsa. Nearest infrastructure is access track 40m west of SW corner.

Long unburnt, no recent scarring only very old scaring on older trees and stumps. Site has been logged previously, unsure of how extensive i.e. clear felled or selectively logged. Evidence of logging seen in the number of regenerating stems and large amount of coarse woody debris. Grazing pressure high and largely from kangaroos with a distinct browse line apparent on the banksias, sparse grass in mid-layer and distinct pads through site. Some diggings are also present and could be rabbits or bandicoots. The Eucalyptus woodland community is consistent at least 90 m extending out from centre of the plot. The site is approximately 30 m in from the main access track through the park. In terms of surface strew, there is a lot of leaf litter and coarse woody debris but also just below the surface there are small circular fragments, unconsolidated alluvial, colluvial and talus deposits.

Landform element and pattern, swamp in a flood plain. Located adjacent to Lake Eda. No surface strew or outcrop, quite sandy. Site is flat, no slope. Grazing impact is moderate, grazed this dry season from cattle. Site is inside a recently constructed enclosure, to look at the impact of grazing. Introduced plant impact is low, check ID determinations. Site is long unburnt, evidence of fire present on older shrubs. Site is homogenous although grasses are slightly more prevalent in SW corner. Community extends 200m to the west and east of plot and transitions to the north and south. Nearest infrastructure is access track 5m north of NE corner.

Plot sits on crest of low hills. Slopes 2 degrees to East increasing to 5 degrees near the eastern edge of plot. Surface strew present- cobble size basalt. Outcrop also present, basalt with the majority on the eastern side of plot.  Grazing impact is minimal. Introduced plant impact minimal, some Passiflora foetida var. hispida present but at low cover. Possibly burnt April 2018.  Site is homogenous and community extends to the 200m to NE and South. Nearest infrastructure is access track 5m south of SW corner.

Landform element and pattern, hill slope in mountains. 20 degrees slope to SW. Basalt outcrops present, mostly along western edged and SW corner. Basalt boulder surface strew also present. Long unburnt, no evidence of past fire, quite a lot of thatch. Grazing impact minimal. Introduced plant impact is low,  Bidens pilosa, Cirsium vulgare, Gomphocarpus physocarpus, Lantana camara, Opuntia tomentosa present is small numbers. Nearest infrastructure is Bunya Mountains Rd, 15m east of NE corner.

Site slope is uneven due to the outcrops throughout the site. The general slope is to north at 1 degree. Lots of quartzite outcrops throughout site, particularly along south edge. Boulder size quartzite surface strew. Site burnt May/June 2018.  Grazing impact low, possible scrub bulls. Introduced plant impact minimal. Community confined to plot. Site opens up towards north edge as it moves into deeper soils. Nearest infrastructure Gibb River-Kalumburu Rd, 4.2km West of plot. A very shallow quadbike access track is ~70m south of SW corner. Site is located adjacent to a fauna monitoring plot THS0005.

Landform element and pattern is a plain in hills. Site slope is relatively flat along the southern edge with gradual 5 degree slope to the NNW. No outcrop apparent. Surface strew present, pebble to cobble size; mostly basal in the south-western end of plot and ironstone/sandstone in the north-eastern end. Introduced plant species impact is low; Cenchrus ciliaris, Opuntia tomentosa present. Grazing impact is minimal; Brumbies present on property and cattle scat found in plot. Homogeneity is confined to plot. Site burnt within last 2-3 years. Nearest infrastructure is vehicle track 60m South of SE corner.

Lithology, outcrop and surface strew is quartzite. Slope 10 degrees to NE, sloping towards NW corner. There is a shallow drainage line that starts developing in the NE corner, Mulga slightly taller along there. Grazing impact low, Kangaroos present. Site is long unburnt. Introduced plant species, minimal. Plot is homogenous, community does extend 75m in all directions from plot centre. Minimal infrastructure, faint track running along fence line to the North of the track, more defined down the slope near the well (1km away).

Landform element and pattern, plain on a sandplain. Grazing impact is moderate with kangaroos targeting grasses. Introduced plant impact minimal.
Nearest infrastructure is a vehicle track 60m North from NW corner. Site is long unburnt. Site is homogenous, community does extend to the East 70m and 80m to South.

Lunette dune on the Southern edge of Lake Puckridge. The Northern end of the plot goes down into a scalded area, but further North of that is more of the same Samphire community. Site is long unburnt. Minimal introduced plant species. Minimal grazing, kangaroos and possibly rabbits. In terms of homogeneity the site is confined to the plot. There is more Samphire on the dune to the North but the community is largely contained to the South and SW where it changes into a Melaleuca woodland. The site is flat with a slight 1 degree slope to the North. Surface strew, some quartz present, mostly sand.

-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Landform element and pattern is a plain and a plian. Not outcrop, gibber surface strew (0.5-3cm). Grazing impact is high, evidence of kangaroo grazing on most of the grasses. Most of the healthier grass are protected amongst shrubs. Introduced plant impact is low, Lepidium sp. present. Site is low unburnt , no evidence of past fire. Site is homogenous, community extends 200m north, 200m south, 100m east, does not extend west. Old grader track to the east of the plot heading NNE.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Landform element is a plain, pattern is a plain. Surface strew, dominated by small ironstone gibber with also sandstone, silt stone gravel, some large boulder to 20cm. Low impact of grazing. Long unburnt. Introduced plant species minimal. Community ends 100m beyond plot (away from road) and 30m to towards the road from the SE corner. Site is homogenous.

Flat site on a plain. The site is deeply sandy (down to a metre or so) with no surface strew or outcrop. Plot has not been burnt this dry season. No introduced plant species recorded. Grazing is minimal as the site is not formally grazed. Extensive stand of mixed Eucalyptus miniata/tetrodonta woodland, likely extending to previous site (WAANOK0002). South-east corner about 30m in from main Kalumburu Road and a disused vehicle track is located about 10m in from the south-east corner. .

Plot is on a plain.  Pebble size sandstone gravel throughout site. Some lateritic outcrop present along western edge. Site is recently burnt in last dry season. Grazing impact is low, evidence of cattle and horses scat. Site is homogenous. Community extend to NW 100m and 75 to E, less T. canescens to the south. Nearest infrastructure is Gibb River-Kalumburu Rd 2.4km WNW of NW corner.

Landform element and pattern, plain in a plain. Some limestone gravel, patchy through site. No outcrop. Site is homogenous, continues 100m East, South West and 70m North (to the road). Site is long unburnt, no evidence of fire scars. Introduced plant impact is minimal. Grazing impact is low, but site has been previously grazed (de-stocked ~2 years ago), kangaroos present. Scat of possibly cattle or camel in plot. Nearest infrastructure access track 30m of NE corner. Existing 30mx30m plot situated inside the plot, in line with the centre of the northern edge.

Plot sits in a small swamp at the base of a range of low hills. Burnt almost annually.  The grazing impact is minimal, though some cows present. Introduced plant species effect is high-Themeda quadrivalvis (grader grass) is the dominant species in the ground layer and Passiflora foetida var. hispida is present throughout the site. The site is reasonably flat with a 1 degree slope to the SE. Homogeneity: Community is confined to the plot. The SW does start changing into a plain rather than a swamp. Nearest infrastructure is the Theda homestead, 600m to the SW. There are some boulders in the NE corner which have rolled down off the hill. There is little to no surface strew, very silty soil.

Landform element and pattern, plain on a plain. No surface strew or outcrop apparent. Sandy soil. Introduced plant impact is minimal. Grazing impact is minimal, previously grazed (de-stocked ~2 years ago). Site is homogenous. Community extend 100m to west, continues extensively to the North and East, interrupted to the SW by the access road 40m from SW corner. Site is long unburnt. Existing 30mx30m plot situated inside the plot, in line with the centre of the southern edge..

Black soil plain, just north of a rainforest pocket. Site is flat with a few small undulations.  Part of the site has had a cool season burn on the northern side, possibly in the last wet season. Introduced plant effect is moderate to high with Themeda quadrivalvis dominant in ground layer and Stylosanthes hamata,  Euphorbia hirta, and Mesosphaerum suaveolens also present. Grazing effect is low, though cows are around. No surface strew or lithology.

Landform element and pattern; Plain in a plain. Site is flat. Quartzite gravel surface strew. Hardpan 30cm below soil surface with the top 30cm relatively soft. Site is long unburnt. Grazing impact is low, one or two recruiting Acacia aptaneura. Introduced plant species impact is minimal. Site is homogenous and community extend 80m from the centre. A lot of cryptogam crust. Cryptogam results may higher due to light overnight shower making the cryptogam more visible. Nearest infrastructure is station access track ~50m East of SE corner.

Long unburnt site, some recruitment in smaller shrubs. The site is flat, on a sand ridge sloping up from the lake to the west of the site. Homogeneity 75m from the centre of the plot then transitions into melaleuca shrubland. Distance to closest infrastructure is a fence 40m away on the western side of the plot. Grazing is low, some cattle around, some digging from rabbits, wallabies are also present. Introduced species moderate along the western edge, mainly Achyranthes aspera with Cenchrus ciliaris also present. No surface strew.

Landform element and pattern, plain on a plain. Minimal surface strew, a small amount of quartzite scattered through site. Site is long unburnt. Introduced plant impact is minimal. Grazing impact is minimal, area de-stocked ~2years ago. Site is homogenous, continues 200m to the North and West, stops SE of the plot where access track is. Nearest infrastructure is the station track 20m south of the SE corner.

Landform element and pattern, hill slope in rises. Surface strew is pebble size ironstone, quartzite and granite. Introduced species impact low. Grazing impact is low, kangaroos present. Nearest infrastructure is the station access track 20m North of NE corner. Site is long unburnt, a lot of fall coarse woody debris but no fire scarring. Site is homogenous. Extends 150m East, South and North 60m. Slight slope to North East ~1 degree, with a drainage line down the centre of site.

Floodplain of the Roebuck Plains, slightly elevated and seasonally flooded. Homogeneity of the site extends 200m in a westerly direction. The NE corner is about 10m from the lake access track, the community extends on the other side of the track, and becomes sparser to the south. The site is flat with minimal surface strew. Limited grazing with some cattle but now been fenced. Has not been burnt for some time. No introduced plant species note

Landform element and pattern is plain within a plain. No surface strew or lithology present. Surface substrate mostly bare ground with some cryptogam. Site is flat, no discernible slope. Site is homogenous, site sits in a broad expanse >100m from centre in all directions. Long unburnt, quite a few dead trees and shrubs within plot. Possibly burnt more recently to the North of plot, where there is more recruitment. Grazing impact is minimal. Introduced plant impact is minimal. Nearest infrastructure is the access track 30m East of SE corner.

Landform element and pattern, sand plain within a sandplain. Site was burnt ~2years ago in a controlled burn. Grazing impact minimal. Introduced plant species impact minimal. Gentle slope 1 degree to SE. No outcrop or surface strew present, though some coarse grained sand. Site is homogenous and community is quite extensive, continuing 100m East, 200m to North and South and 400m to West from the plot centre. Vegetation of Eastern side of access track is a similar community if not the same, but hasn’t been recently burnt. Nearest infrastructure is the access track 50m East of North East corner. Existing pitfall line 10m NE of NE corner, perpendicular to access track.

The site is flat, with no surface strew and has a sandy substrate. The site has not been burnt for a few years, though has some old scarring on trees. Grazing pressure is low, possibly some horses in the area. No introduced plant species recoded.  Homogeneity: the site sits to the north of Doongan and Theda monitoring plot. Very homogenous,  and extends 40m in all directions. The SE is 10m in from an old track, and the new highway is 100m to the SE.

The vegetation community is confined to the plot, about 75 m from the centre. The north-east corner is a few metres in from an access track while the southern edge is about 10-15 m in from a rarely-used track that runs up the ridge. The site is situated on a spur or hill crest as the site is almost on the ridge capping. The slope through the middle is about 6-7 degrees with a north easterly aspect. On the northern edge the slope is a little bit steeper at ~8 degrees and tends towards the south east. The site has been disturbed in the past with some timber cutting, unknown as to whether it has been clear felled or not, but there has definitely been some logs cut possibly for firewood. Regenerating. About 30 m north is a mudstone quarry. The site has been set back from the quarry while still capturing the underlying mudstone lithology. Surface strew is sparse with some gravels and cobbles, however, the lithology is predominantly mudstone with some finer grained sandstones. Very long unburnt. One big dead old stump potentially burnt but no recent scarring. Site situated in a conservation covenant – just over the fence the land is more formally grazed. Grazing pressure is high from kangaroos and deer

Landform element and pattern, sand plain in a plain. No discernible slope. No outcrop or surface strew apparent. Sandy soil with some cryptogam crust. Site is homogenous and community is quite extensive, extending >400m East (does pass over a station track), >900m North, >1km South (does pass over a station track), >1km West (does pass over a station track). Introduced plant species impact is minimal, some Sisymbrium erysimoides. Grazing impact is low. Nearest infrastructure is 30m S of SW corner. Site is low unburnt, some scarring on old Mallee Eucalypts.

Plot is flat- Sandy at surface but very hard below that. Some evidence of goats outside of the plot- fence seems effective at keeping goats out. Very long unburnt. Minimal surface strew- sandy at the surface. Plot is possibly co-located with Bush Heritage monitoring plot either existing or plan. Check with BHA. Close to old water point but introduced plant species effect is low- mainly Sisymbrium erysimoides. Plot sits in extensive Acacia xiphophylla community but fence line 30m to the south and disused bore to the north west mean community only extends 75m from the centre.   200m north of main Shark Bay road.

Plot is on a dune slope in a low  dune field. 2 degree slope to the north west at 45 degrees.  No surface strew- lots of course woody debris. Long unburnt but fire has crept into southern part of the plot 5-6 m. Grazing effect is low-  rabbits and possibly goats but in low numbers. Introduced plant effect is low- Hypochaeris, Sisymbrium and other species- particularly under trees where they are more protected.  Community is quite extensive- extends at least 75m from the centre. Western edge is 20m in from reserve boundary track.

Limestone plain, dunes to the east and west. Surface strew and very low outcrop is limestone. Plot is flat. Long unburnt- no evidence of recent fire. Grazing effect is low- some kangaroo scats. Lots of caterpillars present- have been eating forbs. Introduced plant effect is high- Onion weed and Sisymbrium consistent through the site. Homogeneity- community extends 800m to the north east and 70m to the south. North west and south east if a more shrubby community. Station track is to north west about 80m from the plots.

Dune slope rising up to crest of the dune that overlooks bay. Avg 5-6 degree slope to the west but flattens out at the top. No surface strew. Long unburnt but some dead trees. Grazing effect is low- some rabbits and goats. Lysimachia and Hypochaeris but cover is quite low. Homogeneity- 75m from centre of the plot is same community- more or less confined to the plot but continues along dune slope to the north and south. South west corner is 50m in from Steep Point access track.

Plots is a dune slope in a dune field with 5 degree slope that peters out on the eastern edge. Slope is to the east. No surface strew- very sandy. Long unburnt- lots of old dead growth in the shrub layer but no evidence of recent fire. Grazing effect is minimal- kangaroos possibly goats too but in low numbers. Plot is homogenous- community extends across the track and for 200m+ to the south. Track is 10m in from the eastern edge.

Plot sits on the slope of a low hill with a shallow drainage line running past the south west corner.  Large amounts of course woody debris from dead trees within the site. Grazing effect is moderate- paddock has historically been grazed by stock in low numbers? . Introduced plant effect is moderate- check herb Ids for grasses. Homogeneity- community is confined to the plot as the plot forms a denser woodland in a mosaic of open grassland and woodland patches. The nearsest infrastructure is a fence 450m to the west of the plot.

Dune slope dropping down to cliffs on western edge. 6 degree slope to the west. Some very low limestone outcrops and some limestone cobbles but mostly covered by sand. Long unburnt. Not grazed but possibly some rabbits. Introduced plant effect is low but Senecio may be a weed- check Ids and inform Rangers.  Plot is homogenous- a little bit rockier on western edge. Extensive community along dune slope to the south. To the north is turnaround area for steep point car park. North east corner is about 15m from track moving away to the north west corner which is about 35m south of turnaround area.

The site is flat with the landform element and pattern being a plain. The site is long unburnt with no sign of scorch marks. Timber has been cut in the past likely for firewood and there is a fair amount of coarse woody debris. In terms of surface strew, there is a small amount of cobble sized particles but the substrate is mostly moss and leaf litter. The effect of introduced species is minimal with some Aira present. Grazing is also minimal with a few deer and cattle scats evident but these are over a year old. The nearest structure is a vehicle track about 20-30 m northwest of north east corner and the community is fairly homogenous and extends in all directions for at least 100m from the centre.

The site is grassland on a hill crest with the landform pattern being hills. The site slopes around 7 degrees to the east with an aspect of 180 degrees. The underlying rock outcrops in several places and there are large rocks and boulders strewn throughout the site. The predominant rock type is dolerite, although there may be some underlying basalt. The nearest infrastructure is the dirt road used to access the site which is approximately 800m to the east of the site. The vegetation community is relatively homogenous and continues in a mosaic pattern (i.e. grassland is interspersed with woodland patches) to the south west and east of the plot. The site has been long unburnt. There is some evidence of fire scarring on older dead trees but none of the living trees show fire scars. The impact of introduced plants is minimal, although there is some Aira and boxthorn present. Grazing is moderate.

Open plain.Small surface gravel, covers entire site. Homogeneity extends for at least 1km in either direction. Grazing has been heavy by kangaroos, but they have all died off in the past few months. A pipeline and road 20m from NW corner. Overall very severe drought conditions, no rain for many months.

Small surface gravel. Homogeneity extends for at least 1km in either direction. Grazing has been heavy by kangaroos, but they have all died off in the past few months. A road 30m from NW corner. Overall very severe drought conditions, no rain for many months.

Landform element and pattern is a plain on mountains. Lithology is dolerite boulders scattered through site, more in the SE corner. Aspect is to SE with a gradual slope of 1 degree increasing to 3 degrees nearer to the SE corner. Introduced plant impact is minimal- Hypochaeris radicata present but minimal cover. Grazing impact is minimal, evidence of wallaby scat. Site is long unburnt, no evidence of past fire. Site is homogenous and extends 70m to North, 150m to West 80m to South, 60m to East. Nearest infrastructure is Ben Lomond Village 680m NNE of NE corner. There is a pole line (Little Hell Circuit) ~80m East from the eastern edge of plot.

The site is positioned on a hill slope in a broader landform pattern of low hills. The site slopes 4 degrees to the north east. The nearest infrastructure is an old fence line which is still intact and is situated about 25m from the south west corner. There is also an access track to the nearby dam which is 20m from the north-west corner. The vegetation community is homogenous and continues about 100m along the ridge to the west. The north eastern corner comes down onto the lower slope so the vegetation community changes ~75m from the centre of the plot. The site is long unburnt although there has been patch burning in adjacent areas is recent years. The site is moderately grazed, mostly from native species including wombats and wallabies (active burrows, presence of scats), and the site has likely been grazed by sheep in the past. The ground layer is largely dominated by introduced grasses such as bromus, as well as introduced forbs including Trifolium, Hypercaeris and Cirsium vulgare.

Landform element and pattern. Site is on a hill crest in mountains. Aspect, site is relatively flat, but does slope >1 degree to the North and South. Lithology, there is a lot of dolerite outcrop and boulders, with some gravel. Site is long unburnt, no evidence of past fire. Grazing impact is low, wallaby and wombat scats present. Introduce plant impact is minimal. The site is homogenous and the community does extend 100m East, 60m North, 60m South and changes into a heathland to the west of plot. Nearest major infrastructure is Ben Lomond Alpine Village 1.4km North of plot. The Little Hell Circuit pole line is 100m NE of NE corner.

Landform pattern and element, swamp in hills. Aspect, slight slope to NE 1 degree, general slope of gully is to NNW towards Jacob’s Ladder. Site sits in a gully. Lithology, large dolerite boulders scattered through plot, most are buried with some exposed surface. Site is homogenous and community does extend  200m North, 200-300m East, 80m South and 80m West. Introduced plant impact is minimal, some Hypochaeris radicata present. Grazing impact is low, evidence of wallabies and wombats present. Nearest infrastructure is Ben Lomond Rd ~100m West of SW corner. Site is long unburnt, no evidence of past fire.

The site is a sandplain on a plain. There is no discernible slope and the site is sandy with no surface strew or outcrop apparent. The nearest infrastructure is the station track which is about 60-70m to the north-east. There is also evidence of an old fence line with old pickets but no wire just outside the western edge of the plot.  The plot is homogenous and the Mallee woodland community extends 60-70m to the north, 70-80 metres to the east and at least 100m to west and south. The impact of introduced plant species is low and the impact of grazing is minimal with some evidence of native grazers, like Kangaroos and Emus, through site. The site is long unburnt with leaf litter present around the base of the Mallee Eucalypts.

Landform element and pattern is a plain within a plateau. Site is on a slight rise with <1degree slope  away to the East and West of site.  Introduced species impact is low, Anthoxanthum odoratum, Holcus lanatus, Hypochaeris radicata, Vulpia bromoides present Grazing impact is moderate, seasonal grazing by sheep & cattle and well as wallabies. Site is long unburnt, no evidence of past fire. Surface strew present, cobble sized dolerite and basalt. Occurring is patches across site. Plot is homogenous and community does extend >500m South, >500m North, ~100m East (to the road) and >150m West. Nearest infrastructure is Highland Lakes Rd ~60m East of SE corner.

Landform pattern and element, hill slope in hills. Aspect, moderate slope averaging ~8 degrees to east south east. Slope does undulate. Lithology- boulder field of dolerite surface strew some larger than 1500mm, dolerite outcrop present in site mostly in north corner. Minimal impact of grazing. Introduced plant impact is minimal-  Cirsium vulgare and Senecio jacobaea present. but minimal cover.  Site is long unburnt-  evidence of past fire with dead old growth with fire scars 8m up trunk. Site is homogenous and community continues for >200m in all directions from plot. Nearest infrastructure is power line access track, 150-200m North of plot and Poatina Road 1.6km East of plot.

Landform element and pattern is a plain within a plain.  Site aspect, slight slope <1 degree to the North.  Introduced plant impact is low-moderate  Aira praecox common, Teesdalia nudicaulis, Hypochaeris radicata, Leontodon saxatilis, Acetosella vulgaris and Anthoxanthum odoratum also present at low cover. Grazing impact is moderate, site is grazed >80years; sheep and cattle. Site is long unburnt, some evidence of past fire-ash. Lithology, scattered basalt cobble. Site is homogenous and community does extend from the centre, 70m South, 120m West, 150m N, 100m SE, where community transitions into a Richea sp. heathland. Nearest infrastructure is Stone Hut Road 100m South of plot, there is also a fence running WNW just north of the plot.

Flat plot on deep yellow sands. Site sits to the north of abandoned cropland. No introduced plant species noted. Effect of grazing is low- mainly kangaroos + large flocks of emus close by. Fire history uncertain- suspect long unburnt.  Homogeneity- community is confined to the plot as south east corner is close to access track and abandoned cropland is on the other side of this. Closest infrastructure, SW corner 50m. north of track.

The site is an Acacia shrubland located on a granite rise in a larger sandplain landform. The site slopes about 2 degrees to the south. There is an exposed granite outcrop in the centre and towards the western edge of the plot with pebble sized surface strew. The nearest infrastructure is an access track 100m west from the south west corner. The vegetation community is homogenous and continues at least 100m from the centre of the plot in all directions. The site is long unburnt with some old charred stumps present but no fire scarring is evident on any of the living shrubs. There is a decent amount of coarse woody debris around the site as well. The impact of introduced weeds is minimal with some weedy species such as Hypercaeris and Gallium present. The property has been destocked since 2003 and as such the grazing impact is also minimal with evidence of native browsers only, largely kangaroos.

Landform element and pattern is swamp in a shallow alley in a broader plateau. Overall slope to South at ~1-2 degrees t. Lithology, mostly buried dolerite boulders with the tops exposed, scattered through site and some gravel. Some fragments of basalt also present in the site. Grazing impact is minimal, no evidence of macropods in site. Introduced plant impact is minimal - Taraxacum officinale and Trifolium subterraneum presen. Community is homogenous and community extends 500m south, 100m east, 150m west, 130m north. Nearest infrastructure is the Lake Augusta Rd 200m West of plot from SW corner. Old disused fence in site running East-west through southern end of plot.

The site is a plain on a plain with sandy soil and no surface strew or outcrop apparent. The vegetation community is homogenous and more or less confined to the plot. The community does extend about 100m to the east and west but transitions to a more open mulga woodland to the north. The nearest infrastructure is an access track which is 20m south of the south west corner. There is also an existing monitoring plot situated within the TERN plot along the southern edge around the 50m mark. This is a 30x30m rangelands plot. The site is long unburnt with no evidence of past fire in the site. The grazing impact is minimal. The site has been grazed in the past (some old cow pats) but the property has been destocked since 2003 and is recovering well. There is evidence of native grazers such as kangaroos. The impact of introduced plant species is also minimal.

The site landform pattern and element is a plain on a plain and therefore flat. There is no surface strew or coarse woody debris. The community is homogenous and broad continuing at least 75m in all directions from the centre of the plot. The nearest infrastructure is a track approx. 30m from the eastern edge. There is also impact from a nearby grader bank in the south eastern corner of the plot. The embankment is situated outside the plot but has altered drainage so that water flows into the plot. The site is very long unburnt and the impact of introduced plant species is minimal (possibly introduced Stemodia species). The site is not currently grazed and has not been for a little while (old cow and horse scats present). There is a small degree of recruitment in palatable shrubs such as the Sennas and Eremophilas, however there is a large amount of dead mulga with no recruitment evident. This is largely due to poor conditions.

The site is a plain situated on a plain with no outcrop evident but with some fine gravel-sized ironstone surface strew scattered in patches across the plot.  The nearest infrastructure is an access track located 20m to the north west of the north west corner. The vegetation community is homogenous and extensive, continuing a few hundred metres in all directions. The site is long unburnt with no evidence of fire scarring on any of the trees. The impact of introduced plant species is minimal as is the impact of grazing, with only a few kangaroo scats present.

The site is a plain on a sandplain with no surface strew apparent and only a small patch of low-relief sandstone outcropping in the south eastern corner of the plot.  The soil is quite sandy. The site is homogenous and the community extends at least 200m from the centre of the plot to the south, north and east but extends only about 100m to the west where it is stopped by a mining road. This is also the nearest infrastructure, between 75-100m from the south west corner. The site has not been burnt recently, at least not in the past 1-2 years, although there is fire scarring on some of the trees. The impact of introduced weeds is minimal and grazing is low to moderate with evidence of cattle through the site. The nearest water point is 5.9km north of the site.

The site is situated on a dune slope in a dune field with a 7 degree slope tending towards the west. There is a small amount of limestone outcropping in the north west corner and some limestone gravel as well. The vegetation community is homogenous although does get thinner towards the base of the sand dune (western edge) but the vegetation species are the same. The community extends a few 100ms to the north and ~100m to the east and stops at a track to south. To the west, the community transitions in the dune swale to become a dense shrubland with a similar species composition with the addition of a few other Acacia species. The nearest infrastructure is the Shark Bay 4WD track which is 20m from the south west corner. There is also a disused 4WD track just outside the western edge of plot. In terms of grazing, the impact is low with evidence of rabbits, macropods and emus and the impact of introduced plants is minimal. The site is also long unburnt.

The site is a lunette with the broader landscape being an alluvial plain. No surface strew or outcrop apparent, however, there is a handful of patches of limestone gravel. The site is homogenous and the community extends 60m from the centre of the plot to the south, 150m to the east, 70m to the west and 30-40m to the north. The community transitions to a more open chenopod shrubland to the east and a sandy samphire shrubland to the south. The nearest infrastructure is the access track 30-40m north of north west corner. A Rangelands Plot is also located just to west of plot. The site is long unburnt with no evidence of previous fire and a fair amount of coarse woody debris. The impact of introduced plants is low to moderate with a few weed species present e.g. Sisymbrium. The impact of grazing is also low with rabbit and macropod scats observed.

The site is a perched swamp situated in the swale of a dunefield. There is a small amount of cobble-sized limestone fragments as well as a little bit of sandstone gravel. The swamp is relatively flat but drains to the north. The site is homogenous and the community extends 60m from centre of the plot to west, about 40-15m to the south where it is stopped by a road, it finishes along the eastern edge of plot and extends 80m to north but transitions to more of a Melaleuca dominated shrubland. The nearest infrastructure is the main 4WD track through the park and it is about 10-15m to the south from the south west corner. The site is long unburnt and the impact of grazing is low with only evidence of macropod scats and pads. The impact of introduced weeds is also minimal.

Landform element and pattern is swamp in a plateau. Boulder size surface
strew present, patchy through site, lithology dolerite. Site is long
unburnt no evidence of past fire. Grazing impact is low, wombat and
wallaby present. Introduced plant impact is minimal - none recorded. Aspect, gradual slow
WSW ~1 degree. Site is homogenous, slightly denser to east. Communtiy
extend 200m south, 70m east, 150m north, 100m west. Nearest
inftrastructure Lake Augusta Rd 300m west of  south west corner.

Landform and pattern is plain in low hills. Site slopes to south south west ~1 degree. Lithology, some dolerite outcrop along southern and western edges. Site is long unburnt, although fire scars of nearby tree 5-10years?. Grazing impact is high, lots of wallaby and wombat scat. Introduced plant impact is moderate, high cover of Leontodon saxatilis, Anthoxanthum odoratum  and Holcus lanatus. Aira praecox and Trifolium campestre also present.  Site is homogeneous, becoming more swampy south of plot. Community extends 200m North, 80m east, 50m west, 300m south. Nearest infrastructure is a Flux tower 20 north of north east  corner and access track 500m east of south east corner.

Landform element is hill slope and landform pattern is hills. Slope of 8 degrees to east. Large boulder surface strew, dolerite, most of the boulders covered in bryophytes. Introduced plant impact is low -Hypochaeris radicata present. Grazing impact minimal, evidence of wallabies and wombat. Site is long unburnt, some fire scarring on old Eucs. Site is homogenous and community extends north 200m, 100m east, 70m south, 70m west.Nearest infrastruture is Highlands Rd 30m west of  south west corner.

Landform element and pattern is swamp on a plateau. No discernible
slope. Large dolerite boulders scattered through site. Introduced plant
impact is low-moderate - some Cirsium vulgare, Holcus lanatus, Taraxacum officinale, and Vulpia bromoides with Vulpia bromoides the only species with significant cover (1.5%) . Grazing impact is low-moderate, wombats and wallabies in surrounding
area and scat present in site. Burnt last year in Jan-Feb fires in
Central Highlands. Site appears homogeneous and extend 150m East, 80m
North, 20m South, 300m West (Going by satellite imagery and on-ground
observation). Nearest infrastructure is the Marlborough Hwy, 80m North
on plot.
Note: Burnt clumps/tussocks were recorded as dead in point-intercept.

Landform element and pattern is swamp in a plateau. Lithology, exposed boulder <5% cover, dolerite. Slight slope to west, ~1 degree. Grazing impact is low, evidence of cattle, sheep and wallabies. Introduced plant impact is low possibly some Hyperchaeris sp. Neareset infrastructure is the Highlands Rd 50m from NE corner. Site is homogeneous, extends 100m to south, 100m to West and NW, 70m to North.

Landform element and pattern is a swamp in a plateau. Some dolerite boulders near south west corner. 2 degree slope to south. Introduced plant species impact is minimal - non recorded. Grazing impact is low, evidence of wallaby and wombat scats. Site is long unburnt, no evidence of past fire. Site is homogeneous, community extends 300m South, 150 East, 150 West, 100m North, 3-400m south west.  Nearest infrastructure is the  Central Highlands Rd, 75 m east from south east corner.

Land form element and pattern, hillslope in a plateau. Slope is 2 degrees
with aspect of 60 degrees. Lithology, dolerite, cobble and boulder size
surface strew present. Grazing impact is low, some grasses
have been grazed wallabies, wombats. Introduced plant impact is likely
low - non recorded, although difficult to tell due to past fire. Site was burnt is the
Jan-Feb Central Highlands fire in 2019.  Site is homogeneous, community extends, 100m North, 500m West, 500m South, 250m East.  Open area beyond north west corner. Nearest infrastructure is Central Highlands Rd, 130m East from site edge. Old over-grown cleared line 100 west of site edge

Landform element and pattern, dune slope is a dune field. Slope ~2-3o to the South, although there are some swales running NNW across the site. Lithology, there is some low calcrete outcrop and cobble/gravel surface strew present in patches (covering 15-30% of plot). Introduced plant impact low, some Lysimachia arvensis and introduced grasses present. Grazing impact low, evidence of Kangaroo and Emu scat. No evidence of past fire. Nearest infrastructure is access track 350m east of NE corner. Plot is homogenous and community does extends 100m South, East, West and changes into mobile dunes to the north.

Plot sits on a dune slope with a 5 degree slope to the east. Grazing effect is low- camel tracks in plot, Emus and kangaroos also present. No Introduced plant species recorded. No surface strew, lots of bare ground through the plot. Burnt c- 2008.  Homogeneity, community extends 150m in all directions. South 20m from the plot is a track.

Dune Slope in a dune filed. Slopes down north west at a 6 degree slope. Very sandy, no surface strew. Burnt c- 2008. Less recently than SAAEYB0021 more recently  than SAAEYB0022. Grazing effect is low- kangaroos. Introduced plant effect is minimal- Pentameris airoides subsp. airoides present.   Homogeneity – 80m from centre is the same community. Extends 300m to the west south and north. Fire track along boundary 30 east of the plot.

Duneslope on Sandplain or irregular dunefield. 1 degree slope with a northerly aspect. No surface strew. Burnt summer of 1999-2000 (GE). More recent scar to the south west from 2004.  Old/mature clumps of spinifex and not much dead timber remaining in Mallee. Lots of tracks from Kangaroos- likely using as shelter from neighbouring cropland. Introduced plant effect is low. North of plot is c80m in from cropland and becoming increasingly weedy towards that north from the plot- Vulpia myuros f. myuros, Sonchus oleraceus, Hypochaeris glabra and Arctotheca calendula present but low cover. Homogeneity- 70m from centre is same community. Track 70m north of plot but more weedy going north and denser along track edge.
Only Soil, Metagenomics, Bulk density and Photo Panoramas collected
Site only has soil,  Metagenomics and photo panoramas taken

Landform element and pattern, dune slope in a irregularly shaped dune field. Site slope gently to west, 3 degrees. No surface strew or lithology (site on deep sands). Site in long unburnt, no evidence of scarring, 10-15years without fire at least. Low impact of grazing, kangaroos. Introduced planting impact in minimal. Site is homogenous, extensive 100m form centre is same community. Access track 30m from southern boundary.

Plain, slightly undulating. Long unburnt. Grazing – lots of kangaroo and emu scats some rabbits. Animal pads through the plot. Introduced plant effect is low to moderate Lysimachia linum-stellatum common through the site but a large number of other species in ground storey -   Moraea setifolia, Aira cupaniana, Asparagus asparagoides f. asparagoides and others but cover of other individual species is low. Surface strew is gravel to small cobbles- calcrete. Small patch of outcrop on north west corner. Plot is homogenous- community extends 80m from centre. 250m to the east of plot is a fence line and then the main road just beyond that.

Plot rises to a shallow calcrete ridge in the middle of the plot. Nominal 1 degree slope to the south but site is almost concave due to ridge in middle. Mix of cobbles and gravels with isolated patches of very low calcrete outcrop.  Introduced plant effect is moderate to high in ground story- Anagallis arvensis, Melilotus indicus and other grasses and forbs.  Denser patches of forbs confined to moss cover are mostly introduced plant species. Some patches of Asparagus asparagoides.  Mid layer is all native.  Some patches of moss broken by kangaroo beds and tracks- grazing on perennial native grasses, Eutaxia very heavily grazed. Long unburnt, minimal scarring - very old fire scars on old Mallee. Mallee fowl mound beyond south east corner of the site- inactive.  Homogeneity- vegetation is consistent through the site but a  limestone ridge through the middle of the plot is a little more open. Plot is between from the Walk the Yorke’s track and main Pondalowie road. 80m east of road and 10m west of walking trail

Site is on a dune slope in an irregular dune field. 6 degree slope predominantly to the south east but also to north east. Dune ridge runs north east/south west direction. Some surface strew-  a mix of  calcrete cobbles and pebbles. Outcrop on northern edge. Long unburnt- no evidence of fire.  Introduced plant effect is low- Lysimachia, Vulpia myuros f. myuros, Melilotus indicus, Briza minor and other grasses and forbs present particularly on the southern side of the plot. Most common in areas of Kangaroo disturbance including growing out of scats.  Grazing from Kangaroos- Opercularia turpis and Hibbertia platyphylla subsp. platyphylla noticeably grazed. Plot is homogenous- at least 75m from centre is same community. Northern edge is slightly more open.  240m east of plot is park access track running north to south

Landform element and pattern is a hill slope on rises. Calcrete outcrop present across plot along with cobble sized surface strew (also calcrete). Site slope of 5 degrees to SW. Introduced plant impact moderate, Aira cupaniana, Asparagus asparagoides, Bromus madritensis, Erodium cicutarium, Hypochaeris glabra, Lagurus ovatus, Lysimachia arvensis, Parentucellia latifolia, Rostraria cristata, Silene apetala, Stellaria pallida, Vulpia myuros f. megalura and Vulpia myuros f. myuros. Grazing impact in minimal, evidence of kangaroo and emu. Site long unburnt, no evidence of past fire. Nearest infrastructure is the access track ~20m west in NW corner.

Landform element and pattern is dune slope in a dune field. Calcrete cobble sized surface strew through site and some isolate outcrop on northern edge. Site is long unburnt, no evidence of past fire. Introduced plant impact is low, Avellinia festucoides, Catapodium rigidum, Cerastium balearicum, Erodium cicutarium, Hypochaeris glabra, Lysimachia arvensis, Sonchus oleraceus, Stellaria pallida and Vulpia myuros F. megalura present. Grazing impact low, large quantities of emu scat in plot. Nearest infrastructure is the Coffin Bay Rd 20m north of NE corner. Community is confined to plot.

Calcrete plain with sheet outcrop and cobble sized strew.  Slight slope – 3 degrees to the south east. Numerous introduced plant species - Lysimachia arvensis, Aira elegantissima, Briza minor, Hypochaeris glabraand other grasses and forbs but cover is low. Most abundant in areas disturbed by kangaroos- often growing directly out of scats.   No emu scats, low number of Kangaroo scats. Long unburnt- no scarring on trees.  Plot is homogenous. 200m from centre in same community. Site is patchy at a sub 1ha level but reflects pattern of broader landscape. Eucalyptus oleosa subsp. ampliata, Acacia rupicola and Templetonia retusa denser in southern part of plot while northern half of plot is more open- more exposed limestone outcrop and a higher density of Melaleuca lanceolata.  Track 130m east of south east corner of plot.

Flat calcarenite plain.  Minimal introduced plant species – Lysimachia arvensis, Lagurus ovatus, Sonchus oleraceus and Galium murale present but at very low cover. Extensive moss cover- very few areas of bare ground. Grazing effect is from Kangaroos and emus. Very long unburnt. Homogenous- some heterogeneity at a sub 1ha level. South west corner is very dense while centre and north have more open areas with calcrete outcrop but typical of patterning across broader landscape. Fire access track 10m from south east corner of plot, highway beyond that.

Flat site on plain with calcrete cobbles and some larger boulders. Thin veneer of soil covering calcrete sheets.  Rocky and uneven through the site.  Long unburnt. Termite mounds in site. Introduced plant effect is low to moderate - Trifolium campestre most common especially in small open areas but many other species present at low cover incl Aira elegantissima,  Lysimachia arvensis, Briza minor, Bromus spp. and Sonchus oleraceus.  Lycium ferocissimum noted at plot layout but not collected. Grazing effect is from Kangaroos- beds and scats in the plot. Some native grasses and orchids ( Thelymitra especially) have been severely grazed and there is no recruitment in Allocasuarina verticillata or Bursaria spinosa subsp. spinosa. Small number of emu scats. Long unburnt- no scarring on trees.    Plot is homogenous- 75m from centre is same community. Slightly more open through the centre of the plot. 110m  from north east corner is property access track.

Dune slope in dune field 5 degrees north west. Cobble strew on northern edge- calcrete. No outcrop.  Introduced plant effect is low- Sonchus oleraceus, Asparagus asparagoides, Galium murale and Sonchus oleraceus present but cover low . Grazing effect is low - mostly emus and kangaroos with some rabbit poo. Long unburnt – 40+ years. Homogenous- 100m from centre in all directions. 260m to the south is road.

Plain. No slope. Outcrop is dense calcrete as is surface strew- pebbles. A high number of introduced forbs and grasses including Trifolium campestre,  Sherardia arvensis and Sonchus oleraceus present but cover low. Grazing is from kangaroos- scats and (sw corner) tracks and trails. Boundary trail has emu scats also. Very long unburnt ( Across the road burnt 2010)  Plot is homogenous 60m from centre ( as far a track) other side of track is regenerating from fire c2010

Plain. No discernible slope.  Some calcrete outcrop and pebble sized calcrete strew. High number of introduced species- Bromus rubens, Vulpia sp, Lysimachia arvensis, Oxalis pes-caprae, Galium murale and others but low cover – except for kangaroo disturbed areas and on outcrops. Grazing effect from Kangaroos - scats and beds. Emus scats also present. Long unburnt. No scarring. Fire north west of plot in 2013.  Homogenous- community in consistent through the plot. North of plot has less soil and calcrete outcrop which is more open and devoid of trees- has low shrubs and thick cover of moss and forbs. Elephant ( Boundary track) is 30m from east of plot- highway beyond that. Community extends 300m in all directions.

Plain. Calcarenite outcrop and gravel strew. Slope of 3 degrees to the north. Very long unburnt. Northern section of the part of park burnt in 2013 but didn’t burn into plot.  Lots of evidence of kangaroo activity  with introduced grasses and forbs common around disturbed areas.  Higher density of introduced plant species in open areas- Hypochaeris sp., Trifolium campestre and Euphorbia peplus being the most common  Emu scat with broad bean growing in it. 1 mature Allocasuarina verticillata in north west corner – underneath is 1 lone grazed seedling. Some Eutaxia microphylla but heavily grazed as are orchids and Gahnia with native grasses grazed or only found under protected shrubs. Plot is heterogenous at a sub 1ha level reflective of broader landscape patterns- large areas of open ground with moss cover over calcrete. Acacia triquetra/Acacia rupicola dominant in some patches and Melaleuca decussata in others. Most open in centre and south west of plot. North east on north west are denser.  Community extends 100m from centre of plot. 120m north of plot is park access track.

Undulating plain. No outcrop or surface strew. Large patches of semi bare ground with patches of moss and lichen and herbaceous plants.   Very long unburnt 40+ years. Grazing effect is mainly from Kangaroos with numerous bedding sites under trees and shrubs with introduced plant species  Lysimachia arvensis, Sonchus oleraceus and Galium murale common in these. Cover of introduced plants is very low.  Grazing effect is noticeable on orchids. Emus also present. Homogenous to 80+ metres from centre  but dominance of Eucalypt species varies around the plot. North west corner is slightly denser than south east corner.. 350m from main road on eastern edge and 320 south of paddock boundary on northern edge.

Flat site on a plain. Calcarenite outcrop with pebble strew. Long Unburnt- no scarring on trees.    Introduced plant species effect is moderate- large number of species but all individually at low cover.   Trifolium campestre, Sonchus oleraceus and Asparagus asparagoides are the most common. Grazing from Kangaroos - beds and tracks in site. Homogenous to 75m from centre. East and north east of plot is less dense. North east corner is 10m in from powerline track running north west to south east.

Landform element and pattern dune crest in a dunefield. Quite a lots of  calcrete outcrop and cobble through the site. Evidence of past fire on older shrubs (Last fire 31/12/1991 +/- 6 months). Introduced plant impact is low/moderate, some Lysimachia arvensis, Lagurus ovata, Rosararia cristata and Vulpia myuros present.  Grazing impact low, evidence of kangaroos. Site is homogenous and community extends 60m South, 90m west, 80m North, 50m east from the centre. Nearest infrastructure is 30m north of NE corner.

Landform element and pattern is a hill slope in a sand plain. Gentle 3 degree slope down to the north west corner.  Recently burnt in Jan 2020, intense fire with most shrubs burnt, some on eastern edge less burnt. Surrounding veg also burnt, except to the NE a shrubland pocket is unburnt including the Callitris. No stock on property for 20 years. Evidence of lots of kangaroo grazing with scats, tracks and the grasses (Austrostipa and Rytidosperma) in the open are munched. Minimal impact from introduced plant species. Erigeron bonariensis and Carrichtera annua present but minimal cover.  Vegetation community is homogenous, extends about 30m to the north, 20m to the west, 40m to the east, under 100m to south, then becoming Mallee on all sides with a patch of Callitris to the NE. Nearest infrastructure is small access road about 40m NE of the NE corner. Main access road 300m to the NE.

Landform is a plain, element is a plain. Lithology, small quartz gravel and some pebble. Introduced plant impact is minimal. Grazing impact moderate, grasses heavily grazed, evidence of kangaroos. No evidence of past fire. Site is homogenous, community extend 200m in all directions. Nearest infrastructure is 100m west of NW corner. Disturbance, two shallow drainage line, 1st  running E-W 30m north of plot, 2nd cutting close to SW corner, and a dry fenced dam 200m north of plot.

The site is a plain on a plain with no outcrop or surface strew apparent. The vegetation community is homogenous and confined to the plot, that is, it extends 75m from the centre of the plot. However, the community extends at least 400m from the south east corner to the south east. To the north east the community is mulga woodlands. The nearest infrastructure is the Ti-Tree East TERN Processes Flux Tower and the turnaround track is about 10m north of the north-east corner. The site is long unburnt (last burnt in early 2001) with no evidence of fire visible. The spinifex die-off is related to drought conditions. There is no evidence of grazing and the impact of introduced plants is minimal.

The site is a hill-crest on a mountain comprised of quartzite and quartzite-sandstone. Quite a lot of outcrop and pebble sized surface strew. Site slopes to the West and East, especially the SW corner (about 7 degrees). Average slope of 5 degrees to the East, more so the further East you are within the site. No evidence of invasive species or grazing. Site burned in patches 1-2 years ago, more at the Eastern (30m in) and Western (10-20m in) edges of site. Upper canopy is intact but the lower shrubs are more burnt. Nearest infrastructure is the access track about 4.5km NNW.

Road reserve, 100m north of Barkly Hwy. ~51.2km NE of Tennant Creek, ~47.6km ESE Phillip Creek Homestead. Landform element is a plain, pattern is a sandplain. Site is flat. No outcrop present. Some patches of ironstone present, pebble sized. Homogeneity: there is a shallow drain line with denser vegetation just to the south of the plot. Community extend from the centre of plot; 100m North, 70m East, 70m South, 100m West. Site recently burnt but not in the year, potentially within the last 5 years.

Site burnt relatively recently, within the last 5 years. There is more mature spinifex outside of the plot. Lots of mixed surface strew consisting of ironstone, quartzite and a few others deposited here. The landform is a plain and the element is a sandplain. slope and aspect 1 degree gentle slope to the south. Plot is not formally grazed as it is on the road reserve. Old cattle scat in site. Introduced plant species effect is nil. Homogeneity: Communbity is  confined to the plot, the south east corner becomes denser with Acacia. The closest infrastructure is a track 30m from the south west corner, and the Stuart highway is 60m to the south of the plot.

Flat plot on a sandplain. No surface strew.  At least 5-10 years since the last fire. There are a few old burnt tree stumps, but fairly strong regrowth with the Acacia spp. Introduced plant species effect is low-  there is a small amount of Cenchrus ciliaris mainly under the Corymbia. Grazing effect is low-  a few old cattle scats throughout the site. Homogeneity: The community continues for 75m from the centre of the plot. Plot close to corner of two tracks. There is a approximately 30m to the south and 25m to the east

Shallow dune slope on a sandplain. Slope and aspect is a 2 degree slope to the south west.  No surface strew or outcrop.  The site is relatively long unburnt-  at least 5 years. Grazing effect is minimal with a evidence of camels present. Introduced plant effect species is minimal- none recorded.  Homogeneity is 100m from centre in all directions. In terms of infrastructure, there is a very old fence and track approximately 60m to the South. ,

Landform element and pattern is a plain on a sandplain. No slope. No surface strew or lithology. Site is long unburnt (Difficult to tell). No introduced plant impact. Grazing impact is low, evidence of scrub bulls in and around plot. Site is homogenous, extending 75m in all direction from centre (although community is quite extensive). 40m to the North of the site is a Telstra telephone exchange. Access track is 30 west of NW corner.

Dune slope in a dune field - 1 degree slope to the west. No outcrop or lithology present. Introduced plant impact is minimal - non recorded.  Grazing impact is low, camel seen near plot. Site recently burnt within last year. The majority of the vegetation was burnt except for the crowns of the Corymbia sphaerica. Nearest infrastructure is the access track 30m South of the south west corner. Plot is homogenous and community extends over 100m in all directions.

Landform element and pattern is a plain on relictual floodplain of the Burdekin river. Surface strew is a mix of gravel and cobbles, largely covered by the grasses. Unconsolidated unidentified material from old river wash. Plot is flat. Introduced plant impact is high with the ground layer dominated by Bothriochloa pertusa and Cenchrus ciliaris with Stylosanthes hamata,Urochloa mosambicensis and Stylosanthes scabra and other grasses and forbs present . Has been cleared in the past, some regeneration of trees and only a couple of mature Eucalyptus brownii.  Grazing impact at present is low as there is a lot of ground cover but evidence of heavy grazing from cattle in the past with cow pats and uneven surface. Site appears long unburnt. Site is homogenous at least 80m out from the centre point. Nearest infrastructure is a track that is 40m from the north east corner.

Plot is situated on an old flood plain from the Burdekin River, raised up from the current level of the river with alluvial wash. The landform element is a plain and the pattern is a plain. There is no slope or aspect, the plot is relatively flat. Site is grazed- a large heard of cattle at the site during visit. Unsure of stocking densities.  The site it long unburnt with no scaring or other evidence. The effect of introduced plant species is moderate- some Bothriochloa pertusa throughout the ground layer. There is a considerable amount Carissa and other increaser species that indicate that the site has heavily grazed previously.  The sampled vegetation community extends for 80m from the centre of the plot. Distance to infrastructure 40m to a paddock fence.

The element is a hillslope and the pattern would is a rise. The crest of the rise would be about 60 metres away, with a 4 degree slope to the south east. The surface strew is mixed, with mainly quartz gravels. Introduced plant species effect is moderate-  the ground layer is dominated by Bothriochloa pertusa, Urochloa mosambicensis, Cenchrus ciliaris and other introduced grasses. There has been light grazing at this site, however there are still inflorescence on most of the grasses.The site looks long unburnt with scarring on trees. The plot is homogenous, with a slight increase of Carissa to the bottom of the slope. It extends 75m from the centre of the plot.  There is a very large pit 10m to the NW corner, and the station track is another 40m beyond that. There does appear to be an old track through the site, approximately 30m in, heading to the SE.  Hasn't been used for a very long time and is very overgrown. There is also evidence of wood collection with a few trees that have been cut down. 

There has been significant rain in the past 2 weeks and is wet. The vegetation growth is active. The eucalypts aren’t flowering, and the grasses are green but have shed all of their seed

Landform element and pattern is a plain on a plain with minimal slope. No surface strew or outcrop. The cryptogam crust is extensive, more than bare ground through most of the site. Minimal evidence of introduced plant species- Schismus barbatus present but very low cover.  Grazing pressure from kangaroos. Westringia rigida and grasses have been particularly effected. Goats on property but no evidence of them in plot. Very long unburnt with no evidence of scarring on trees, potentially over 100 years since last fire. Community is confined to the plot. Mallee becomes denser beyond western boundary of site. Site is largely concentrated in the Myoporum and shrubland, community extends 75m from the centre. Nearest infrastructure is the main access track to the property dam, which is 20m from the NE corner.

Landform element is hill slope with a pattern of rises. No surface strew or outcrop, site is sitting over granite.  4 degree slope down to the creek in the North East. Introduced plant species impact is moderate with Lantana camara forming dense thickets and  Asparagus plumosus, Ochna serrulata  and other introduced grasses and forbs common throughout the site. Predominately native in upper storey. Grazing impact is low but a hare and a kangaroo were spotted nearby. Site is long unburnt, no evidence of past fire. Small scale cutting down of trees in the past. Community is confined to the plot. The community continues 75m northeast from the centre down to the creek. The nearest infrastructure is the walking track which is 15-20m from the west side of the plot.

Landform element and pattern is a plain in a plain. No surface strew or outcrop.  Site slope of 1 degree to the north east.  Site is within the main fenced enclosure on Secret Rocks. Site recently burnt in December 2019. Introduced plant species effect is low -   Carrichtera annua, Chondrilla juncea and Sonchus oleraceus present but minal cover. Grazing impact is low - some kangaroos but plot is inside kangaroo exclosure. Nearest infrastructure is the boundary track and exclosure fence, 400m south of plot.

Site is not aligned to the grid, with north west corner the most northern point. Landform pattern and element is slope on hill. There is a 4 degree slope down to the north north east of the plot. No surface strew or outcrop, only lots of leaf litter. Site sitting over granite. Grazing impact is low, mainly kangaroos, no grazing by stock. Site is long unburnt, with no anecdotal evidence or scarring on trees. Introduced species impact moderate- extensive control of Lantana camara undertaken but still some throughout the site. Asparagus plumosus and Ochna serrulata and other introduced species also present but cover low. Vegetation community is confined to the plot, with denser vegetation in gully below the site and a Lantana control line above the site. Nearest infrastructure is an access track 10m from the North of the site.
